st and Africa (Washington, D.C., 31 October 2014).\n\n===Primary sources===\n*The stories of several American fighter pilots, shot down over North Vietnam are the focus of [[American Film Foundation]]'s 1999 documentary ''[[Return with Honor]]'', presented by [[Tom Hanks]].\n*Lewis H. Carlson, ''WE WERE EACH OTHER'S PRISONERS: An Oral History of World War II American and German Prisoners of War'', 1st Edition.; 1997, BasicBooks (HarperCollins, Inc). {{ISBN|0-465-09120-2}}.\n* Peter Dennis, Jeffrey Grey, Ewan Morris, Robin Prior with Jean Bou : ''The Oxford Companion to Australian Military History'' 2nd edition (Melbourne: Oxford University Press Australia & New Zealand, 2008) {{OCLC|489040963}}.\n*H.S. Gullett, ''Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u201318, Vol. VII The Australian Imperial Force in Sinai and Palestine'' 10th edition (Sydney: Angus & Robinson, 1941) {{OCLC|220900153}}.\n*Alfred James Passfield, ''The Escape Artist: An WW2 Australian prisoner's chronicle of life in German POW camps and his eight escape attempts'', 1984 Artlook Books Western Australia. {{ISBN|0-86445-047-8}}.\n* Rivett, Rohan D. (1946). ''Behind Bamboo''. Sydney: Angus & Robertson. Republished by Penguin, 1992; {{ISBN|0-14-014925-2}}.\n* George G. Lewis and John Mewha, ''History of prisoner of war utilization by the United States Army, 1776\u20131945''; Dept. of the Army, 1955.\n* Vetter, Hal, '' Mutine at Koje Island''; Charles Tuttle Company, Vermont, 1965.\n* Jin, Ha, ''War Trash: A novel''; Pantheon, 2004. {{ISBN|978-0-375-42276-8}}.\n* [[Sean Longden]], ''Hitler's British Slaves''. First Published Arris Books, 2006. Second Edition, Constable Robinson, 2007.\n* Desflandres, Jean, '' Rennbahn: Trente-deux mois de captivit\u00e9 en Allemagne 1914\u20131917 Souvenirs d'un soldat belge, \u00e9tudiant \u00e0 l'universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles '' 3rd edition (Paris, 1920)\n\n==Further reading==\n* Devaux, Roger. ''[http://www.genea.free.fr/guefangue/index-en.php Treize Qu'ils Etaient]{{Dead link|date=October 2014}}: Life of the French prisoners of war at the peasants of low Bavaria (1939\u20131945)'' \u2013 M\u00e9moires et Cultures\u20142007\u2014{{ISBN|2-916062-51-3}}\n* Doylem Robert C. ''The Enemy in Our Hands: America's Treatment of Prisoners of War From the Revolution to the War on Terror'' (University Press of Kentucky, 2010); 468 pages; Sources include American soldiers' own narratives of their experiences guarding POWs plus [https://web.archive.org/web/20130510234107/http://www.pritzkermilitarylibrary.org/Home/Robert-C-Doyle.aspx Webcast Author Interview] at the [[Pritzker Military Library]] on 26 June 2010\n*Gascare, Pierre. ''Histoire de la captivit\u00e9 des Fran\u00e7ais en Allemagne (1939\u20131945)'', \u00c9ditions Gallimard, France, 1967 \u2013 {{ISBN|2-07-022686-7}}.\n*McGowran, Tom, ''Beyond the Bamboo Screen: Scottish Prisoners of War under the Japanese.'' 1999. Cualann Press Ltd\n*[[Arnold Krammer]], ''''Nazi Prisoners of War in America'' 1979 Stein & Day; 1991, 1996 Scarborough House. {{ISBN|0-8128-8561-9}}.\n*Bob Moore,& Kent Fedorowich eds., ''Prisoners of War and Their Captors in World War II'', Berg Press, Oxford, UK, 1997.\n* Bob Moore, and Kent Fedorowich. ''The British Empire and Its Italian Prisoners of War, 1940\u20131947'' (2002) [https://www.amazon.com/British-Empire-Italian-Prisoners-1940-1947/dp/0333738926/  excerpt and text search]\n*David Rolf, ''Prisoners of the Reich, Germany's Captives, 1939\u20131945'', 1998; on British POWs\n* Scheipers, Sibylle [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:0159-2011050916 ''Prisoners and Detainees in War ''], [[European History Online]], Mainz: [[Institute of European History]], 2011, retrieved: 16 November 2011.\n*Paul J. Springer. ''America's Captives: Treatment of POWs From the Revolutionary War to the War on Terror'' (University Press of Kansas; 2010); 278 pages; Argues that the US military has failed to incorporate lessons on POW policy from each successive conflict.\n*{{cite book |last1=Vance |first1=Jonathan F. |location=Millerton, NY |publisher=Grey House Pub, 2006. |title=The Encyclopedia of Prisoners of War & Internment |edition=Second |format=PDF |date=March 2006 |type=Hardcover |page=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofpr0000unse_z5l2/page/800 800] |isbn=1-59237-120-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofpr0000unse_z5l2/page/800 }} |{{ISBN|978-1-59237-120-4}} EBook {{ISBN|978-1-59237-170-9}}\n*Richard D. Wiggers, \"The United States and the Denial of Prisoner of War (POW) Status at the End of the Second World War\", ''Militargeschichtliche Mitteilungen'' 52 (1993) pp.&nbsp;91\u201394.\n*Winton, Andrew, ''Open Road to Faraway: Escapes from Nazi POW Camps 1941\u20131945.'' 2001. Cualann Press Ltd.\n* Harris, Justin Michael. [http://ecommons.txstate.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1011&context=histtad \"American Soldiers and POW Killing in the European Theater of World War II\"]\n* United States. Government Accountability Office. [https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo40670 ''DOD's POW/MIA Mission: Capability and Capacity to Account for Missing Persons Undermined by Leadership Weaknesses and Fragmented Organizational Structure: Testimony before the Subcommittee on Military Personnel, Committee on Armed Services, U.S. House of Representatives.''] Washington, D.C.: U.S. Government Printing Office, 2013.\n* On 12 February 2013, three American POWs gathered at the [[Pritzker Military Library]] for a [https://web.archive.org/web/20130628142149/https://www.pritzkermilitarylibrary.org/Home/POW-experience.aspx webcast conversation] regarding their individual experiences as POWs and the memoirs they each published:\n**[[Rhonda Cornum]] \u2013  with Peter Copeland ''She Went to War: The Rhonda Cornum Story'' 1992 {{ISBN|9780891414636}}\n**[[John L. Borling|John Borling]] \u2013 a collection of his poetry ''Taps on the Walls: Poems from the Hanoi Hilton'' 2013 {{ISBN|9780615659053}}\n**Donald E. Casey \u2013 ''To Fight for My Country, Sir!: Memoirs of a 19-year-old B-17 Navigator Shot Down in Nazi Germany'' 2009 {{ISBN|9781448669875}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Prisoners of war}}\n{{EB1922 Poster|Prisoners of War}}\n*[http://www.icrc.org/Web/Eng/siteeng0.nsf/htmlall/section_ihl_prisoners_of_war Prisoners of war and humanitarian law], ICRC.\n* [http://yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk/index.php?title=Category:Prisoners_of_war Prisoners of War] UK National Archives.\n* [http://yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk/index.php?title=ADM_103 Prisoners of War 1755\u20131831] UK National Archives ADM 103\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070203194602/http://www.bbc.co.uk/ww2peopleswar/categories/c1204/  Archive of World War II memories] BBC.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080330210330/http://www.historynet.com/wars_conflicts/world_war_2/3037296.html Soviet Prisoners of War: Forgotten Nazi Victims of World War II] HistoryNet.\n*[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/pow.asp Reports made by World War I prisoners of war] UK National Archives\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140822065123/http://www.storyvault.com/video/view/japanese_prisoner_of_war_journey_to_japan First hand account of being a Japanese POW. Part 1 in a series of 4 video interviews] Storyvault\n* [http://www.historicaleye.com/Axispows.html German POWs and the art of survival] Historical Eye\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20010627212117/http://virtualwall.org/pmsea.htm Current status of Vietnam War POW/MIA]\n*Clifford Reddish. [https://web.archive.org/web/20171010101923/http://www.cliffordreddish.eu/ War Memoirs of a British Army Signalman as a prisoner of the Japanese]\n* [http://archives.cbc.ca/IDD-1-71-1642/conflict_war/pow_camps_Canada/ Canada's Forgotten PoW Camps] CBC Digital Archives\n* [http://www.lexikon-der-wehrmacht.de/Gliederungen/Kriegsgefangenenlager/Stammlager-R.htm German army list of Stalags]\n* [http://www.lexikon-der-wehrmacht.de/Gliederungen/Kriegsgefangenenlager/Offizierslager-R.htm German army list of Oflags]\n* [http://www.colditzcastle.net/  Colditz Oflag IVC POW Camp]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130523174505/http://lamsdorfreunited.co.uk/ Lamsdorf Reunited]\n* [http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2Pris.html New Zealand PoWs of Germany, Italy & Japan] New Zealand Official History\n* [http://kiuchi.jpn.org/en/nobindex.htm Notes of Japanese soldier in a USSR prison camp after World War II]\n*[http://www.icrc.org/web/eng/siteeng0.nsf/htmlall/57jnwx?opendocument German prisoners of war in Allied hands] (World War II) ICRC\n* [http://www.ww2pow.info/ World War II U.S. POW Archives]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121218033254/http://www.koreanwarpow.org/ Korean War POW Archives]\n* [http://www.europeanfilmgateway.eu/node/33/efg1914%20prisoners/multilingual:1/showOnly:video Historic films about POWs in World War I] European Film Gateway\n* [http://donmooreswartales.com/2010/05/12/harry-glixon/ Jewish POW swapped by Germans in World War II]\n\n<!--spacing-->\n\n{{Incarceration}}\n{{Particular human rights}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prisoner Of War}}\n[[Category:Prisoners of war| ]]\n[[Category:Aftermath of war]]\n[[Category:Imprisonment and detention]]\n[[Category:Warfare]]\n[[Category:17th-century neologisms]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eQualifications:expansion / remove extraneous definite article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prisoner_of_war"}
{"title_page": "Heckler", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Redirect|Heckle}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n[[File:Heckler2.jpg|right|thumb|250px|A heckler in Washington, D.C. leans across a police line toward a demonstration of [[Iran]]ians during the [[Iran hostage crisis]], August 1980.]]\n\nA '''heckler''' is a person who harasses and tries to disconcert others with questions, challenges, or gibes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Heckler |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/heckler |publisher=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref>\nHecklers are often known to shout disparaging comments at a performance or event, or to interrupt set-piece speeches, with the intent of disturbing performers and/or participants.\n\n==Origin==\nAlthough the word ''heckler'', which originated from the textile trade, was first attested in the mid-15th century, the sense \"person who harasses\" was from 1885.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=heckler|title=heckler {{!}} Origin and history of heckler by Online Etymology Dictionary|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary|accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref> To ''heckle'' was to tease or comb out [[flax]] or [[hemp]] fibres. The additional meaning, to interrupt speakers with awkward or embarrassing questions, was added in [[Scotland]], and specifically perhaps in early nineteenth century [[Dundee]], a famously radical town where the hecklers who combed the flax had established a reputation as the most radical and belligerent element in the workforce. In the heckling factory, one heckler would read out the day's news while the others worked, to the accompaniment of interruptions and furious debate.<ref name=McKie>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/apr/28/broadcasting.comment |title=Unplotted ripostes |last1=McKie |first1=David |date=28 April 2005 |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nHeckling was a major part of the [[vaudeville]] theater. Sometimes it was incorporated into the play. [[Milton Berle]]'s weekly TV variety series in the 1960s featured a heckler named Sidney Spritzer ([[German language|German]]/[[Yiddish]] for 'squirter') played by [[Borscht Belt]] comic [[Irving Benson]]. In the 1970s and 1980s, ''[[Muppet Show|The Muppet Show]]'', which was also built around a vaudeville theme, featured two hecklers, [[Statler & Waldorf]] (two old men named after famous hotels). Heckles are now particularly likely to be heard at comedy performances, to unsettle or compete with the performer.\n\n==Politics==\n{{See also|Heckler's veto}}\n<!-- \nNOTE: these sections could stand to be organized a bit more (by year, era, whatever)\nwith sub-headers (or at least date or year) for each \"incident\" so as to put them all in context.\n-->\nPoliticians speaking before live audiences have less latitude to deal with hecklers. In one of his early political campaigns before becoming [[Premier of Ontario]], [[Mitchell Hepburn]] stood on top of a [[manure spreader]], apologizing to the crowd for speaking from a [[bullshit|Tory platform]], at which someone in the crowd shouted, \"Well, wind 'er up Mitch, she's never carried a bigger load!\"<ref>{{cite hansard |jurisdiction= Ontario|title= Orders of the Day: Animal Health Act, 2009|url= http://www.ontla.on.ca/web/house-proceedings/house_detail.do?Date=2009-11-04&Parl=39&Sess=1&locale=en|house= [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]]|date= November 4, 2009|page= |speaker= [[John Yakabuski]]|position=MPP}} at 10:00am</ref>\n\nLegally, such conduct may constitute protected [[free speech]]. Strategically, coarse or belittling retorts to hecklers entail personal risk disproportionate to any gain. Some politicians, however, have been known to improvise a relevant and witty response despite these pitfalls. One acknowledged expert at this was [[Harold Wilson]], British Prime Minister in the 1960s:\n\n:'''Heckler''': (''interrupting a passage in a Wilson speech about Labour's spending plans'') What about [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]?\n:'''Wilson''': The government has no plans to increase public expenditure in Vietnam.\n:'''Heckler''': Rubbish!\n:'''Wilson''': I'll come to your special interest in a minute, sir.<ref name=McKie/>\n\n[[Martin Luther King, Jr.|Martin Luther King]]'s [[I Have a Dream]] speech was largely a response to supporter [[Mahalia Jackson]] interrupting his prepared speech to shout \"Tell them about the dream, Martin\".<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KxlOlynG6FY Lazarus, Hayden of heckla.com (16 April 2018) : Former Martin Luther King, Jr. adviser and speechwriter Clarence B. Jones talks to WSJ's Monika Vosough about how Martin Luther King's favorite gospel singer Mahalia Jackson helped create the \"I Have a Dream\" speech]</ref> At that point, King stopped reading from his previously prepared speech and improvised the remainder of the speech - this improvised portion of the speech is the best-known part of the speech and frequently rated as one of the best of all time.\n\nDuring a campaign stop just before winning the Presidency in 1980, [[Ronald Reagan]] was heckled by an audience member who kept interrupting him during a speech. Reagan tried to go on with his speech three times, but after being interrupted yet again glared at the heckler and snapped \"Aw, shut up!\" The audience immediately gave him a standing ovation.\n\nIn 1992, then-Presidential candidate [[Bill Clinton]] was interrupted by [[Bob Rafsky]], a member of the AIDS activism group [[ACT UP]], who accused him of \"dying of ambition to be president\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Toner |first=Robin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/27/us/the-1992-campaign-aids-protester-provokes-clinton-s-anger.html |title=NY Times |work=New York Times |date=27 March 1992 |accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> during a rally. After becoming visibly agitated, Clinton took the microphone off the stand, pointed to the heckler and directly responded to him by saying, \"[...] I have treated you and all of the other people who have interrupted my rallies with a hell of a lot more respect than you treated me. And it's time to start thinking about that!\" Clinton was then met with raucous applause.<ref>{{cite web|author=30 maart 2006 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JGTQZnC-6a4 |title=Clinton's Angry Response to Heckler |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September 2009, Representative [[Joe Wilson (U.S. politician)|Joe Wilson]] (R-SC) shouted \"You lie!\" at President [[Barack Obama]] after President Obama stated that his health care plan would not subsidize coverage for illegal immigrants during a [[Barack Obama speech to joint session of Congress, September 2009|speech]] he was making to a joint session of Congress.  Wilson later apologized for his outburst.<ref>[http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/09/09/wilson-apologizes-i-let-my-emotions-get-the-best-of-me/ \"Wilson apologizes: 'I let my emotions get the best of me'\"]. Retrieved September 9, 2009.</ref>\n\nOn 25 November 2013, Ju Hong, a 24-year-old South Korean immigrant without legal documentation, shouted at Obama to use his executive power to stop deportation of illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://inagist.com/all/405077610499022849/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203164254/http://inagist.com/all/405077610499022849/ |archivedate=3 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Obama said \"If, in fact, I could solve all these problems without passing laws in Congress, then I would do so.\" \"But we're also a nation of laws, that's part of our tradition,\" he continued. \"And so the easy way out is to try to yell and pretend like I can do something by violating our laws. And what I'm proposing is the harder path, which is to use our democratic processes to achieve the same goal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/immigrationdebate/ci_24598028/obama-san-francisco-calls-immigration-reform|title=Obama\u2019s immigration speech in deep-blue San Francisco interrupted by anti-deportation hecklers|author=|date=25 November 2013|website=mercurynews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/video/heckler-obama-steals-attention-presidents-speech-21008837|title=Video: Heckler Disrupts Obama's Speech With Minute-Long Rant|first=ABC|last=News|date=|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/news/national-govt-politics/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb4qQ/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126145922/http://www.ktvu.com/news/news/national-govt-politics/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb4qQ/ |archivedate=26 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/news/national/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb494/|title=Obama addresses heckler during speech on immigration|author=|date=|website=daytondailynews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wpxi.com/news/news/national/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb494/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402144614/http://www.wpxi.com/news/news/national/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb494/ |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nOn December 29, 2014, [[New York City]] [[mayor]] [[Bill de Blasio]] was the target of this at his address to 884 [[police academy]] [[graduates]] at [[Madison Square Garden]] in the aftermath of the [[2014 killings of NYPD officers]] Wenjian Liu and Rafael Ramos.\n\n=== Audience control ===\n<!-- \nNOTE: possible use for subheader here, distinguishing the use of \"audience screening\" as a means of discouraging political heckling.\nNOTE: 'astroturfing' and 'audience screening' are arguably distinct, changed to a 'see also'\n-->\n<!-- What? -->\nOne modern political approach to discourage heckling is to ensure that major events are given before a \"tame\" audience of sympathizers, or conducted to allow restrictions on who may remain on the premises (see also, ''[[astroturfing]]''). The downside is this may make heckling incidents even more newsworthy. This happened to [[Tony Blair]] during a [[photo op]] visit to a hospital during the 2001 general election campaign, and again in 2003 during a speech.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2690549.stm \"Blair's heckler states his case\"], BBC, 24 January 2003.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, American Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] was interrupted mid-speech by Perry Patterson, a middle-aged mother in a pre-screened rally audience. After various supportive outbursts that were permitted (\"Four more years\", \"Go Bush!\"), Patterson uttered  \"No, no, no, no\" and was removed from the speech area and told to leave. She refused, and was arrested for criminal [[trespass]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eugeneweekly.com/2006/02/09/coverstory.html |title=Woman utters No |publisher=Eugeneweekly.com |accessdate=12 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025003616/http://www.eugeneweekly.com/2006/02/09/coverstory.html |archive-date=25 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nLater, in 2005, Cheney received some heckling that was broadcast during his trip to New Orleans, after [[Hurricane Katrina]] ravaged the city. The heckling occurred during a press conference in [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]], Mississippi, in an area that was cordoned off for public safety reasons, and then further secured for the press conference. Nevertheless, emergency room physician Ben Marble got close enough to the proceedings and could be heard yelling, \"Go fuck yourself, Mr. Cheney.\" Cheney laughed it off and continued speaking.<ref>June Deery: ''Consuming Reality: The Commercialization of Factual Entertainment''.  MacMillan, 2012.  Page 71.</ref>  The heckle was a reference to Cheney's use of the phrase the previous year, when during a heated exchange with Senator [[Patrick Leahy|Patrick Joseph Leahy]], Vermont, he said \"fuck yourself\" on the floor of the senate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheney Dismisses Critic With Obscenity|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A3699-2004Jun24.html|website=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 October 2005, ''[[The Scotsman]]'' reported<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=2094782005 |title=Iran denies troop attack links |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513220441/http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=2094782005 |archivedate=13 May 2007 |work=The Scotsman}}</ref> \"Iranian ambassador Dr Seyed Mohammed Hossein Adeli... speaking at the annual Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament conference...  During his speech to the CND several people were told to leave the room following protests at Iran's human rights record. Several protesters shouted \"Fascists\" at the ambassador and the organisers of the conference. Walter Wolfgang, the 82-year-old peace campaigner who was forced out of the Labour Party conference last month, was in the audience.\"\n\nSince 2005 heckling of performing artists has become more commonplace in [[Switzerland]].  Musicians of [[Basel]] and [[Zurich]] have become an increasing focus of hecklers.  This shift is primarily perpetrated by foreigners and is often met with a positive response by the non-Swiss performers who welcome the audience interaction.\n\nOn Thursday, 20 April 2006, a heckler from the [[Falun Gong]] spiritual movement entered the US [[White House]] grounds as a reporter and interrupted a formal arrival ceremony for [[President of the People's Republic of China|Chinese President]] [[Hu Jintao]].  Moments into Mr Hu's speech at the event, [[Wang Wenyi]], perched on the top tier of the stands reserved for the press, began screaming in English and Chinese: \"President [[George W. Bush|Bush]] stop him. Stop this visit. Stop the killing and torture.\"<!--  The heckler was allowed to continue for several minutes despite the heavy presence of security personnel typical of such high level meeting of officials, prompting speculation that the incident was planned with the tacit cooperation of the White House in order to embarrass the Chinese president, hence possibly making this heckling incident one which was found justified by its audience. --><ref>[http://cbs13.com/topstories/topstories_story_110093156.html \"No breakthrough in US, China talks\"]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927011756/http://cbs13.com/topstories/topstories_story_110093156.html |date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> President Bush later apologised to his guest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/frontpage/story/0,,1758305,00.html |title=Protester gatecrashes Hu visit as China and US fail to make progress |work=The Guardian |location=London |date= 21 April 2006|accessdate=12 March 2009  | first=Suzanne | last=Goldenberg}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\nHecklers can also appear at sporting events, and usually (but not always) direct their taunts at a visiting team. Fans of the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] [[American football]] team are notorious for heckling; among the most infamous incidents were [[booing]] and subsequently throwing snowballs at a performer dressed as [[Santa Claus]] in a halftime show in 1968, and cheering at the career-ending injury of visiting team player [[Michael Irvin]] in 1999.  Often, sports heckling will also involve throwing objects onto the field; this has led most sports stadiums to ban glass containers and bottlecaps. Another famous heckler is [[Robert Szasz]], who regularly attends [[Tampa Bay Rays]] baseball games and is known for loudly heckling one opposing player per game or series. Former [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] [[association football|football]] star [[Dejan Savi\u0107evi\u0107]] is involved in an infamous incident with a heckler in which during an interview, a man on the street is heard shouting off-camera: \"You're a piece of shit!\"  Dejan berated the man, and went on to finish the interview, without missing a beat.\n\nIn English and Scottish [[association football|football]], heckling and swearing from the stands, and [[football chant]]s such as [[who ate all the pies?]] are common.\n\nAustralian sporting audiences are known for creative heckling. Perhaps the most famous is [[Yabba]] who had a grandstand at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]] named after him, and now a statue.\n\nThe sport of [[cricket]] is particularly notorious for heckling between the teams themselves, which is known as [[sledging (cricket)|sledging]].\n\nAt the NBA Drafts of recent years, many fans have gone with heckling [[ESPN]] [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] analyst and host of, [[Quite Frankly with Stephen A. Smith]], [[Stephen A. Smith]]. Most notably, The Stephen A. Smith Heckling Society of Gentlemen heckles him with a sock puppet dubbed as Stephen A. himself.\n\nTennis fans are also fairly noted for heckling. Some may call out during a service point to distract either player. Another common heckle from tennis fans is cheering after a service fault, which is considered to be rude and unsporting.\n\nIn 2009, then [[Toronto Blue Jays]] outfielder [[Alex R\u00edos]] was a victim of a heckling incident outside after a fund-raising event. The incident occurred after Rios declined to sign an autograph for a young fan, the same day he went 0 for 5 with 5 [[strikeouts]] in a game against the [[Los Angeles Angels]]. An older man yelled \"The way you played today Alex, you should be lucky someone wants your autograph.\" Rios then replied with \"Who gives a fuck\", repeating it until being ushered into a vehicle. Rios did apologize the next day,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/story/2009/06/05/sp-rios-youtube.html | work=CBC News | title=Rios apologizes for YouTube tirade at abusive fan | date=5 June 2009}}</ref> but was eventually placed on waivers and claimed by the [[Chicago White Sox]] later that year.\n\n==Music==\n{{Further|Electric Dylan controversy}}\nOne of the most famous heckles in music history occurred at a [[Bob Dylan]] concert at the [[Manchester Free Trade Hall]] in 1966. During a quiet moment in between songs, an audience member shouts very loudly and clearly, \"Judas!\" referencing Dylan's so-called betrayal of folk music by \"going electric\". Dylan replied: \"I don't believe you, you're a liar!\" before telling his band to \"Play it fucking loud!\" They play an acidic version of \"[[Like a Rolling Stone]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Glover|first=Tony|title=Bob Dylan Live 1966 Liner Notes|publisher=Columbia Records|year=1998|location=New York|page=7}}</ref> This incident was captured on tape and the full concert was released as volume four of Dylan's ''Live Bootleg Series''.\n\n==Stand-up comedy==\n{{Main article|Stand-up comedy}}\nIn stand-up comedy, a heckler is anyone who interrupts a comedian's set.<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=188\n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref> Hecklers want the stand-up to break the [[fourth wall]].<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/20 20]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=An audience may imply (through heckling, interrupting, etc.) a desire for the comic to break down the fourth wall and 'join the crow,' but experienced comedians know that this would only make the room more uncomfortable.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/20\n }}</ref> Most sources claim that heckling is uncommon.<ref name=parallel/><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.sacmag.com/2018/12/12/how-about-those-hecklers/\n |title=How About Those Hecklers?\n |last=Cassinos-Carr\n |first=Cathy\n |date=12 December 2018\n |website=Sacramento Magazine\n |access-date=27 March 2019\n |quote=You see a lot of heckler videos go viral. But that\u2019s not because heckling happens a lot.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n |last= Conway\n |first= Andrew\n |date= 11 December 1995\n |others=Collected by Robert Nelson, Scott Meltzer, Ngaio Bealum and Dave Gomez\n |title= You're Ugly, Your Dick Is Small, and Everybody Fucks Your Mother\u2014The Stand-Up Comedian's Response to the Heckler\n |url= http://www.juggling.org/~conway/juggler/MAL.TXT \n |format=Text\n |journal=[[Maledicta]], The International Journal of Verbal Aggression\n |location=Santa Rosa, CA\n |publisher=Maledicta Press\n |volume= 11\n |isbn=978-0916500313\n |access-date= 15 August 2019\n |quote=In performances by comedians in the USA it is not uncommon for a member of the audience to interrupt the performance by shouting a comment.}}</ref> Heckling can occur during [[Renegade show|open stage]] performances, and/or where alcoholic beverages are being consumed; it is regarded as a sign of audience members becoming impatient with what they regard as a low-quality performance.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |page=159\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5\n |quote=[Heckling] usually only happens because of one of two reasons: either you have lost the interest of the audience or the heckler is an idiot.}}</ref> New comics are often underprepared to properly handle hecklers.<ref name=parallel>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2004/aug/16/edinburgh04.edinburghfestival3\n |title=How can he show his face?\n |last=MacInnes\n |first=Paul\n |date=15 August 2004\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |others=Logan Murray\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=For new comics, heckling is like parallel parking for new drivers, you need to know how to do it, but it doesn't happen very often.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/136 136]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=To develop this kind of heckler-deflecting skill takes years; like writing and timing, it is developed with the benefit of those lovable comic twins: time and pain.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/136\n }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, live comedy venues tend to discourage heckling via signage and admissions policy, but tend to tolerate it as it creates customer loyalty. The etiquette of exactly how much heckling is tolerated differs immensely from venue to venue, however, but is generally more likely to be tolerated in blue-collar or working-class venues.\n\nComedians generally dislike heckling.{{refn|<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Sarah Silverman (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =40:44-41:10\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =I don't like hecklers, but I\u2019m fascinated by them, and you know, I don't have like bits for hecklers, but I just love going in and talking to\u2014giving them the attention that they need so badly and talking about it, you know, and where that comes from and how can I help you. How can I make you feel good about yourself?}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = Billy Connolly (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =34:20-34:33\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =I can never hear what a heckler is saying. I just respond wildly to them. And they might be saying, oh Billy, I love you\u2014I say, shut the fuck up! I don\u2019t really like them as a species.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.pattonoswalt.com/index.cfm?page=spew&id=167\n |title=A Closed Letter to Myself About Thievery, Heckling and Rape Jokes: Heckling\n |last=Oswalt\n |first=Patton\n |date=14 June 2014\n |website=Patton Oswalt\n |publisher=Patton Oswalt\n |access-date=3 February 2019\n |quote=Hecklers don\u2019t make a show memorable.  They prevent a show from being a fucking show.  Comedians do not love hecklers.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Billy Connolly\n | year =2011\n | title =The Art of Stand-Up\n | medium =TV\n | language =English\n | location =United Kingdom\n | time = 40:18-40:44\n | publisher =BBC: One\n | quote =I loathe hecklers. I haven't one good syllable to say about hecklers. When you've come out of the club circuit and all that and you're in the concert hall...they should be gone.\n | editor=Alan Yentob}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/08/how-to-deal-with-hecklers-according-to-nine-top-st.html\n |title=How to Deal With Hecklers: Tips From Nine Top Stand-up Comics\n |last=Fernandez\n |first=Jesse\n |date=29 August 2016\n |website=Paste\n |publisher=Paste Media Group.\n |access-date=23 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://westsidetoastmasters.com/article_reference/handling_hecklers.html\n |title=Handling the Heckler\n |website=Toastmasters International\n |access-date=23 March 2019\n |quote=I asked some fellow comedians what they thought about hecklers. As you might imagine, it was tough to get a straight answer:}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |others=Pat Condell\n |page=177\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5\n |quote=I've never met a heckler I didn't want to punch in the face.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Zoglin\n |first=Richard\n |date=22 January 2008\n |title=Comedy at the Edge: How Stand-up in the 1970s Changed America\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xtCmCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46&dq=%22comedy+at+the+edge%22+%22fork%22&source=bl&ots=j61EvmQJIL&sig=ACfU3U3nJFCjoWuTfN3xWBeuDpHo26asZg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimvJzgt-viAhXQ1FkKHWPKD3cQ6AEwA3oECCAQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22comedy%20at%20the%20edge%22%20%22fork%22&f=false\n |publisher=Bloomsbury USA\n |page=46\n |isbn=978-1582346243\n |access-date=15 June 2019\n |quote=Even in the Caf\u00e9 Wha? days, Roth remembers seeing Pryor get so enraged at a heckler that he stabbed the guy with a fork.}}</ref>}} Hecklers may rarely threaten or physically assault comedians.{{refn|<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = Billy Connolly (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =38:13-38:17\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =There's a guy [who] punched me onstage.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/134 134]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Generally, however, any comic\u2019s physical encounters onstage can be counted on one hand\u2014more often, one finger\u2026Insults about appearance are almost exclusively aimed at women [comics].\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/134\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last         = Perrett\n | first        = Connor\n | date         = 22 July 2019\n | title        = Stand-Up Comedian Says He Was Punched By A Trump Supporter For Telling A Joke About The President\n | url          = https://www.inquisitr.com/5543688/stand-up-comedian-says-he-was-punched-by-a-trump-supporter-for-telling-a-joke-about-the-president/\n | work         = The Inquisitr\n | access-date  = 14 August 2019\n | quote        = Following Fontenot\u2019s quip, the man reportedly stormed the stage and punched the comedian in the face, causing him to lose consciousness.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/133 133-134]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Alan Harvey was once stabbed with a pencil by a crazed female patron. [[Tom Dreesen]] remembers, in the days when he was part of a double act with [[Tim Reid]]...\u2018One night, one drunk walked by, put a lit cigarette out in Tom\u2019s face...He says that cmics are particularly vulnerable up there because the light is directly in their faces, so they can't see where a potential attacker is coming from. Jonathan Solomon says that he was once attacked by a drunk man...and nobody came onstage to help...another time...in Washington, a man threw a drink at him onstage.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/133\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/theatreblog/2010/aug/24/heckling-comedy-goes-bad\n |title=When heckling goes bad\n |last=Kettle\n |first=James\n |date=24 August 2010\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |access-date=23 March 2019\n |quote= There are numerous stories of comics being attacked by audience members \u2013 in fact YouTube footage exists of one of the biggest draws at this year's fringe, Australian comic Jim Jeffries, being punched in the head onstage at the Manchester Comedy Store.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.courant.com/breaking-news/hc-br-manchester-heckler-arrest-20190225-kqy6c7lwmncmlcsxdfaw3t7pve-story.html\n |title=Police say heckler pulled knife, threatened comedian at Manchester club\n |last= Leavenworth\n |first=Jesse\n |date=25 February 2019\n |website=Hartford Courant\n |access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-46382267\n |title=Heckling: How to deal with it during a comedy show\n |last= McGregor\n |first=Nesta\n |date=29 November 2018\n |website=BBC News\n |publisher=BBC\n |others=Ian Smith\n |access-date=27 March 2019\n |quote=Ian says while the crowd saw the funny side of the gag, the man had to be restrained by his friends\u2014before later being escorted out of the venue.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last         = Zinoman\n | first        = Jason \n | date         = 17 July 2012\n | title        = Toe-to-Toe at the Edge of the Comedy Club Stage\n | url          = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/18/arts/television/when-the-comic-and-the-heckler-both-take-offense.html\n |url-access = limited\n | work         = The New York Times\n | publisher  = New York Times Company\n | access-date  = 15 June 2019\n |quote = [A] heckler ended an exchange with Tammy Pescatelli, a veteran comic, by tossing a wine glass at her at a club in Jacksonville, Fla., scratching her cornea.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | author       =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n | date         = 26 July 2012\n | title        = Woman May Sue Comedian Eddie Griffin Over Pleasanton Heckling\n | url          = https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2012/07/26/woman-may-sue-comedian-eddie-griffin-over-pleasanton-heckling/\n | work         = CBS SF BayArea\n |location = San Francisco\n | publisher  = CBS Broadcasting Inc.\n | access-date  = 15 June 2019\n |quote =It was a chaotic scene as a woman throws her drink at Griffin at Tommy T\u2019s. Fiona Walshe said she was taunted by Griffin for being a lesbian.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Bobby Lee (comedian), Michael Addis (director)\n | year =2007\n | title =Heckler\n | language =English\n | time =8:12-9:00\n | publisher =FilmRise\n | quote =I was onstage in New Mexico and some kid was going\u2014just halfway through a punchline I hear\u2014ching, ching, ching chong ching, ching chong ching chong, ching ching chong. This was a ''really'' dark, Mexican guy. So then I just basically went, '[variation of \u00e1ndale]\u2014hey, I'm digging a ditch,' you know (laughs to camera), 'I'm a ditch-digger.' Then, all of the sudden, through my peripheral I see him climbing onto the stage. So I keep going, then all of the sudden, like, I black out. I\u2019m literally like, on the stage, laying there. He had punched me (pause) in the face.}}</ref>}} Even more rarely, comedians may receive death threats.<ref>{{cite news\n | last         = Hofstetter\n | first        = Steve\n | date         = 18 July 2019\n | title        = A Comedian's Guide To Handling Nazi Death Threats\n | url          = https://www.cjnews.com/perspectives/opinions/a-comedians-guide-to-handling-nazi-death-threats\n | work         = The Canadian Jewish News\n | access-date  = 19 July 2019\n |quote         = I received 252 death threats, both direct and indirect [that I reported to the FBI]...I [talked] with one of the agents, who let me know that some of the folks that were threatening me were career criminals.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | author       = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n | date         = 24 March 2019\n | title        = Kathy Griffin on receiving death threats\n | url          = https://www.cbsnews.com/video/kathy-griffin-on-receiving-death-threats/\n | work         = CBS News\n | access-date  = 19 July 2019\n |quote         = On the day that I filmed...two FBI agents come in...they told me that they had [knowledge of] an imminent threat, [[October 2018 United States mail bombing attempts|Cesar Sayoc]] had shared his list with like-minded people}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n|year=2006\n|chapter=Good Advice: Dave Coulier\n|editor1-last=Shydner\n|editor1-first=Ritch\n|editor2-last=Schiff\n|editor2-first=Mark\n|title=I Killed: True Stories of the Road From America\u2019s Top Comics\n|url=http://www.standupstories.com\n|url-status=dead\n|others=[[Dave Coulier]]\n|edition=First Paperback\n|location=New York\n|publisher=Three Rivers Press\n|page=18\n|isbn=978-0-307-38229-0\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501193623/http://www.standupstories.com:80/\n|archive-date=1 May 2012\n|access-date=31 March 2020\n|quote=A heckler lost an exchange with me and threatened me with a gun. As they pulled him away he was still waving the gun and shouting,'I'm gonna shoot your ass.'}}</ref>\n\n===Countering===\nComedians counter hecklers by controlling the flow of conversation.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/136 136]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[[Adrianne Tolsch]] says that, like stand-up in general, the key to dealing with hecklers is to remember, \u2018it\u2019s all about control\u2026it\u2019s not what you say, it\u2019s how fast and forcefully you say it\u2019\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/136\n }}</ref> Some comedians ignore the heckling.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://mentalfloss.com/article/54496/11-ways-handle-heckler\n |title=11 Ways to Handle a Heckler\n |last=Patrick\n |first=Colin\n |date=13 January 2014\n |website=Mental Floss\n |publisher=minute media\n |access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-46382267\n |title=Heckling: How to deal with it during a comedy show\n |last= McGregor\n |first=Nesta\n |date=29 November 2018\n |website=BBC News\n |publisher=BBC\n |others=Ian Smith\n |access-date=27 March 2019\n |quote=I sometimes try to ignore them because it might be the attention that they're after.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/135 135]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Carol [Siskind] says, she acts as she does in any heckling episode: \u2018I try to ignore them [at first]\u2026or I state my position right away.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/135\n }}</ref> Others devise a strategy for quashing such outbursts, usually by having a repertoire of [[insult|comebacks]] for hecklers{{refn|<ref>{{cite journal\n |last= Conway\n |first= Andrew\n |date= 11 December 1995\n |others=Collected by Robert Nelson, Scott Meltzer, Ngaio Bealum and Dave Gomez\n |title= You're Ugly, Your Dick Is Small, and Everybody Fucks Your Mother\u2014The Stand-Up Comedian's Response to the Heckler\n |url= http://www.juggling.org/~conway/juggler/MAL.TXT \n |format=Text\n |journal=[[Maledicta]], The International Journal of Verbal Aggression\n |location=Santa Rosa, CA\n |publisher=Maledicta Press\n |volume= 11\n |isbn=978-0916500313\n |access-date= 15 August 2019\n |quote=The comedian's response to the heckler is called a 'heckler line'...A successful comedian will usually have a large repertoire of lines, and will attempt to choose one that fits the situation, as this will make the response appear to be improvised.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah \n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha \n |year=2016 \n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy \n |others=Jim Jefferies \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc \n |pages=230\u2013231 \n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0 \n |quote=I have a list of three or four [comebacks]...and the rest will be off the cuff}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/135 135-136]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Like all comics, [Carol Siskind\u2019s] responses to hecklers are usually not ad-libs, but cold, calculated antidotes\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/135\n }}</ref>}}\u2014known as \"heckler lines\" or \"[[wikt:squelch|squelches]]\"\u2014on hand; those who handle the moment in an off-the-cuff manner do so by giving the heckler \"enough rope to hang themselves.\"<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |page=165,174\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Apatow\n |first=Judd\n |others=Jay Leno\n |year=2016\n |title=Sick In The Head\n |location=NY\n |publisher=Random House\n |page=162\n |isbn=978-0-8129-8728-7\n |quote=[G]ive them enough rope so they hang themselves}}</ref> [[Stewart Lee]] treats heckles as genuine inquiries.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = Stewart Lee (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =41:10-41:50\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =Another...way of controlling a room, which again can lead to fantastic deaths but really enjoyable ones, is to treat abusive heckles as if they were genuine inquiries\u2026and actually to answer them at such length that the people regret having asked the question in the first place.}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n | url=https://www.comedianscomedian.com/200-stewart-lee/ \n | title=The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith: 200 Stewart Lee\n | others=Stewart Lee\n | website=The Comedian\u2019s Comedian\n | publisher=Stuart Goldsmith\n | host=Stuart Goldsmith\n | date=6 March 2017\n | time=18:30-18:55\n | access-date=13 February 2019\n | quote =I try to treat all heckles as a genuine inquiry\u2026and I know where I\u2019ve got that from. It\u2019s from one recording[, a track called ''Life on the Road'',] of [[Ted Chippington]]['s album, ''Man in a Suitcase'']}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Frances-White\n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur\n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Stewart Lee\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=160\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=I treat it [the heckle] like it's an honest inquiry.}}</ref> [[Jerry Seinfeld]] is a \"Heckle Therapist,\" who verbally sympathizes with the heckler to confuse the heckler and win the audience over.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.backstage.com/magazine/article/become-standup-comedian-2468/\n |title=How to Become a Standup Comedian\n |last= Lindsay\n |first=Benjamin\n |date=8 January 2018\n |website=backstage\n |publisher=Backstage\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=[Jerry Seinfeld is a] Heckle Therapist...when people would say something nasty...[he] would...become...sympathetic to them and try to help them with their problem...to work out what was upsetting them, and try to be...understanding with their anger\u2026[he] would counsel the heckler...'You seem so upset, and I know that's not what you wanted to have happen tonight. Let's talk about your problem,\u2019 and the audience...[found] it funny and it would [confuse the heckler]}}</ref> Some comedians will get hecklers to repeat themselves to take away the momentum and laughter from the heckle.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don\u2019t Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=57\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=[When asked to repeat what they said], the heckler will freeze up...[or if they do repeat it], it won't have as much steam.}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\n[[Bill Burr]] performed a set in Philadelphia where he reprimanded an audience of over ten thousand people.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/comedian-bill-burr-explains-his-epic-philly-rant-2006-show/\n |title=Comedian Bill Burr explains his epically profane 'Philly rant' at '06 show\n |last=Tanenbaum\n |first=Michael\n |date=30 November 2017\n |website=Philly Voice\n |publisher=WWB Holdings, LLC.\u00a0\n |access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref> [[Michael Richards]] became upset with a heckler and called them the N-word several times.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.wweek.com/bump/2016/11/29/the-day-the-clown-cried-pinpointing-the-single-destructive-moments-that-disgraced-famous-comedians-careers/\n |title=The Single Destructive Moments That Disgraced Famous Comedians' Careers\n |date=29 November 2016\n |website=Willamette Week\n |publisher=Willamette Week\n |access-date=27 March 2019\n |quote=Nov. 17, 2006: Michael Richards\u00a0goes on a racist rant at the Laugh Factory in L.A. }}</ref> When a female audience member claimed that rape jokes are never funny, [[Daniel Tosh]] allegedly made an off-the-cuff retort that it would be funny if she were to be immediately raped.<ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Holpunch\n| first        = Amanda\n| date         = 11 July 2012\n| title        = Daniel Tosh apologises for rape joke as fellow comedians defend topic\n| url          = https://www.theguardian.com/culture/us-news-blog/2012/jul/11/daniel-tosh-apologises-rape-joke\n| work         = The Guardian\n| publisher  = Guardian News & Media Limited\n| access-date  = 15 June 2019\n|quote = In a blog entry posted on Tumblr, an audience member wrote that after Tosh told a series of jokes proclaiming that rape is always funny, she called out \u2018Actually, rape jokes are never funny!' To which she claims Tosh replied: \u2018Wouldn't it be funny if that girl got raped by like, five guys right now? Like right now? What if a bunch of guys just raped her'}}</ref>\n\n==Other comedy mediums==\nThe comedy TV series ''[[The Muppet Show]]'' featured a pair of hecklers named [[Statler and Waldorf]]. These characters created a kind of meta-comedy act in which the show's official comedian, [[Fozzie Bear]], acted as their usual [[Double act|foil]], although they occasionally made jokes at other characters as well.\n\nAnother notable use of heckling in comedy is in the cult favorite series ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]''. The series involves a man (either Joel Robinson or Mike Nelson) and two robots (Tom Servo and Crow T. Robot) sitting in a theater mocking bad B-movies. This style of comedy, coined as riffing, is continued with commentary-based series such as [[Rifftrax]] and [[Cinematic Titanic]].\n\nIn one of [[Rowan Atkinson]]'s plays \"The School Master\", a heckler interrupted his play by shouting \"Here!\" after Atkinson had read out an amusing name on his register. Atkinson incorporated it into his act by saying \"I have a detention book...\"<ref>{{cite serial\n| title        = Headmaster\n| episode      = The Secret Policeman's Ball\n| url          = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uWJ7bhKYsuw\n| series       = The Secret Policeman's Balls\n| last         = Atkinson \n| first        = Rowan\n| authorlink   = Rowan Atkinson\n| date         = 27\u201330 June 1979\n| minutes      = 0:54}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Applause]]\n*[[Audience participation|Audience Participation]]\n*[[Booing]]\n*[[Heckler's veto]]\n*[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]], a TV show built on humorous heckling.\n*[[Troll (Internet)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Censorship}}\n\n[[Category:Human communication]]\n[[Category:Comedy]]\n[[Category:Show business terms]]\n[[Category:Stand-up comedy]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Redirect|Heckle}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n[[File:Heckler2.jpg|right|thumb|250px|A heckler in Washington, D.C. leans across a police line toward a demonstration of [[Iran]]ians during the [[Iran hostage crisis]], August 1980.]]\n\nA '''heckler''' is a person who harasses and tries to disconcert others with questions, challenges, or gibes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Heckler |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/heckler |publisher=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref>\nHecklers are often known to shout disparaging comments at a performance or event, or to interrupt set-piece speeches, with the intent of disturbing performers and/or participants.\n\n==Origin==\nAlthough the word ''heckler'', which originated from the textile trade, was first attested in the mid-15th century, the sense \"person who harasses\" was from 1885.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=heckler|title=heckler {{!}} Origin and history of heckler by Online Etymology Dictionary|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary|accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref> To ''heckle'' was to tease or comb out [[flax]] or [[hemp]] fibres. The additional meaning, to interrupt speakers with awkward or embarrassing questions, was added in [[Scotland]], and specifically perhaps in early nineteenth century [[Dundee]], a famously radical town where the hecklers who combed the flax had established a reputation as the most radical and belligerent element in the workforce. In the heckling factory, one heckler would read out the day's news while the others worked, to the accompaniment of interruptions and furious debate.<ref name=McKie>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/apr/28/broadcasting.comment |title=Unplotted ripostes |last1=McKie |first1=David |date=28 April 2005 |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nHeckling was a major part of the [[vaudeville]] theater. Sometimes it was incorporated into the play. [[Milton Berle]]'s weekly TV variety series in the 1960s featured a heckler named Sidney Spritzer ([[German language|German]]/[[Yiddish]] for 'squirter') played by [[Borscht Belt]] comic [[Irving Benson]]. In the 1970s and 1980s, ''[[Muppet Show|The Muppet Show]]'', which was also built around a vaudeville theme, featured two hecklers, [[Statler & Waldorf]] (two old men named after famous hotels). Heckles are now particularly likely to be heard at comedy performances, to unsettle or compete with the performer.\n\n==Politics==\n{{See also|Heckler's veto}}\n<!-- \nNOTE: these sections could stand to be organized a bit more (by year, era, whatever)\nwith sub-headers (or at least date or year) for each \"incident\" so as to put them all in context.\n-->\nPoliticians speaking before live audiences have less latitude to deal with hecklers. In one of his early political campaigns before becoming [[Premier of Ontario]], [[Mitchell Hepburn]] stood on top of a [[manure spreader]], apologizing to the crowd for speaking from a [[bullshit|Tory platform]], at which someone in the crowd shouted, \"Well, wind 'er up Mitch, she's never carried a bigger load!\"<ref>{{cite hansard |jurisdiction= Ontario|title= Orders of the Day: Animal Health Act, 2009|url= http://www.ontla.on.ca/web/house-proceedings/house_detail.do?Date=2009-11-04&Parl=39&Sess=1&locale=en|house= [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]]|date= November 4, 2009|page= |speaker= [[John Yakabuski]]|position=MPP}} at 10:00am</ref>\n\nLegally, such conduct may constitute protected [[free speech]]. Strategically, coarse or belittling retorts to hecklers entail personal risk disproportionate to any gain. Some politicians, however, have been known to improvise a relevant and witty response despite these pitfalls. One acknowledged expert at this was [[Harold Wilson]], British Prime Minister in the 1960s:\n\n:'''Heckler''': (''interrupting a passage in a Wilson speech about Labour's spending plans'') What about [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]?\n:'''Wilson''': The government has no plans to increase public expenditure in Vietnam.\n:'''Heckler''': Rubbish!\n:'''Wilson''': I'll come to your special interest in a minute, sir.<ref name=McKie/>\n\n[[Martin Luther King, Jr.|Martin Luther King]]'s [[I Have a Dream]] speech was largely a response to supporter [[Mahalia Jackson]] interrupting his prepared speech to shout \"Tell them about the dream, Martin\".<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KxlOlynG6FY Lazarus, Hayden of heckla.com (16 April 2018) : Former Martin Luther King, Jr. adviser and speechwriter Clarence B. Jones talks to WSJ's Monika Vosough about how Martin Luther King's favorite gospel singer Mahalia Jackson helped create the \"I Have a Dream\" speech]</ref> At that point, King stopped reading from his previously prepared speech and improvised the remainder of the speech - this improvised portion of the speech is the best-known part of the speech and frequently rated as one of the best of all time.\n\nDuring a campaign stop just before winning the Presidency in 1980, [[Ronald Reagan]] was heckled by an audience member who kept interrupting him during a speech. Reagan tried to go on with his speech three times, but after being interrupted yet again glared at the heckler and snapped \"Aw, shut up!\" The audience immediately gave him a standing ovation.\n\nIn 1992, then-Presidential candidate [[Bill Clinton]] was interrupted by [[Bob Rafsky]], a member of the AIDS activism group [[ACT UP]], who accused him of \"dying of ambition to be president\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Toner |first=Robin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/27/us/the-1992-campaign-aids-protester-provokes-clinton-s-anger.html |title=NY Times |work=New York Times |date=27 March 1992 |accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> during a rally. After becoming visibly agitated, Clinton took the microphone off the stand, pointed to the heckler and directly responded to him by saying, \"[...] I have treated you and all of the other people who have interrupted my rallies with a hell of a lot more respect than you treated me. And it's time to start thinking about that!\" Clinton was then met with raucous applause.<ref>{{cite web|author=30 maart 2006 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JGTQZnC-6a4 |title=Clinton's Angry Response to Heckler |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September 2009, Representative [[Joe Wilson (U.S. politician)|Joe Wilson]] (R-SC) shouted \"You lie!\" at President [[Barack Obama]] after President Obama stated that his health care plan would not subsidize coverage for illegal immigrants during a [[Barack Obama speech to joint session of Congress, September 2009|speech]] he was making to a joint session of Congress.  Wilson later apologized for his outburst.<ref>[http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/09/09/wilson-apologizes-i-let-my-emotions-get-the-best-of-me/ \"Wilson apologizes: 'I let my emotions get the best of me'\"]. Retrieved September 9, 2009.</ref>\n\nOn 25 November 2013, Ju Hong, a 24-year-old South Korean immigrant without legal documentation, shouted at Obama to use his executive power to stop deportation of illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://inagist.com/all/405077610499022849/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203164254/http://inagist.com/all/405077610499022849/ |archivedate=3 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Obama said \"If, in fact, I could solve all these problems without passing laws in Congress, then I would do so.\" \"But we're also a nation of laws, that's part of our tradition,\" he continued. \"And so the easy way out is to try to yell and pretend like I can do something by violating our laws. And what I'm proposing is the harder path, which is to use our democratic processes to achieve the same goal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/immigrationdebate/ci_24598028/obama-san-francisco-calls-immigration-reform|title=Obama\u2019s immigration speech in deep-blue San Francisco interrupted by anti-deportation hecklers|author=|date=25 November 2013|website=mercurynews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/video/heckler-obama-steals-attention-presidents-speech-21008837|title=Video: Heckler Disrupts Obama's Speech With Minute-Long Rant|first=ABC|last=News|date=|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/news/national-govt-politics/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb4qQ/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126145922/http://www.ktvu.com/news/news/national-govt-politics/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb4qQ/ |archivedate=26 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/news/national/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb494/|title=Obama addresses heckler during speech on immigration|author=|date=|website=daytondailynews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wpxi.com/news/news/national/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb494/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402144614/http://www.wpxi.com/news/news/national/obama-addresses-heckler-during-speech-immigration/nb494/ |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nOn December 29, 2014, [[New York City]] [[mayor]] [[Bill de Blasio]] was the target of this at his address to 884 [[police academy]] [[graduates]] at [[Madison Square Garden]] in the aftermath of the [[2014 killings of NYPD officers]] Wenjian Liu and Rafael Ramos.\n\n=== Audience control ===\n<!-- \nNOTE: possible use for subheader here, distinguishing the use of \"audience screening\" as a means of discouraging political heckling.\nNOTE: 'astroturfing' and 'audience screening' are arguably distinct, changed to a 'see also'\n-->\n<!-- What? -->\nOne modern political approach to discourage heckling is to ensure that major events are given before a \"tame\" audience of sympathizers, or conducted to allow restrictions on who may remain on the premises (see also, ''[[astroturfing]]''). The downside is this may make heckling incidents even more newsworthy. This happened to [[Tony Blair]] during a [[photo op]] visit to a hospital during the 2001 general election campaign, and again in 2003 during a speech.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2690549.stm \"Blair's heckler states his case\"], BBC, 24 January 2003.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, American Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] was interrupted mid-speech by Perry Patterson, a middle-aged mother in a pre-screened rally audience. After various supportive outbursts that were permitted (\"Four more years\", \"Go Bush!\"), Patterson uttered  \"No, no, no, no\" and was removed from the speech area and told to leave. She refused, and was arrested for criminal [[trespass]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eugeneweekly.com/2006/02/09/coverstory.html |title=Woman utters No |publisher=Eugeneweekly.com |accessdate=12 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025003616/http://www.eugeneweekly.com/2006/02/09/coverstory.html |archive-date=25 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nLater, in 2005, Cheney received some heckling that was broadcast during his trip to New Orleans, after [[Hurricane Katrina]] ravaged the city. The heckling occurred during a press conference in [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]], Mississippi, in an area that was cordoned off for public safety reasons, and then further secured for the press conference. Nevertheless, emergency room physician Ben Marble got close enough to the proceedings and could be heard yelling, \"Go fuck yourself, Mr. Cheney.\" Cheney laughed it off and continued speaking.<ref>June Deery: ''Consuming Reality: The Commercialization of Factual Entertainment''.  MacMillan, 2012.  Page 71.</ref>  The heckle was a reference to Cheney's use of the phrase the previous year, when during a heated exchange with Senator [[Patrick Leahy|Patrick Joseph Leahy]], Vermont, he said \"fuck yourself\" on the floor of the senate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheney Dismisses Critic With Obscenity|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A3699-2004Jun24.html|website=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 October 2005, ''[[The Scotsman]]'' reported<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=2094782005 |title=Iran denies troop attack links |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513220441/http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=2094782005 |archivedate=13 May 2007 |work=The Scotsman}}</ref> \"Iranian ambassador Dr Seyed Mohammed Hossein Adeli... speaking at the annual Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament conference...  During his speech to the CND several people were told to leave the room following protests at Iran's human rights record. Several protesters shouted \"Fascists\" at the ambassador and the organisers of the conference. Walter Wolfgang, the 82-year-old peace campaigner who was forced out of the Labour Party conference last month, was in the audience.\"\n\nSince 2005 heckling of performing artists has become more commonplace in [[Switzerland]].  Musicians of [[Basel]] and [[Zurich]] have become an increasing focus of hecklers.  This shift is primarily perpetrated by foreigners and is often met with a positive response by the non-Swiss performers who welcome the audience interaction.\n\nOn Thursday, 20 April 2006, a heckler from the [[Falun Gong]] spiritual movement entered the US [[White House]] grounds as a reporter and interrupted a formal arrival ceremony for [[President of the People's Republic of China|Chinese President]] [[Hu Jintao]].  Moments into Mr Hu's speech at the event, [[Wang Wenyi]], perched on the top tier of the stands reserved for the press, began screaming in English and Chinese: \"President [[George W. Bush|Bush]] stop him. Stop this visit. Stop the killing and torture.\"<!--  The heckler was allowed to continue for several minutes despite the heavy presence of security personnel typical of such high level meeting of officials, prompting speculation that the incident was planned with the tacit cooperation of the White House in order to embarrass the Chinese president, hence possibly making this heckling incident one which was found justified by its audience. --><ref>[http://cbs13.com/topstories/topstories_story_110093156.html \"No breakthrough in US, China talks\"]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927011756/http://cbs13.com/topstories/topstories_story_110093156.html |date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> President Bush later apologised to his guest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/frontpage/story/0,,1758305,00.html |title=Protester gatecrashes Hu visit as China and US fail to make progress |work=The Guardian |location=London |date= 21 April 2006|accessdate=12 March 2009  | first=Suzanne | last=Goldenberg}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\nHecklers can also appear at sporting events, and usually (but not always) direct their taunts at a visiting team. Fans of the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] [[American football]] team are notorious for heckling; among the most infamous incidents were [[booing]] and subsequently throwing snowballs at a performer dressed as [[Santa Claus]] in a halftime show in 1968, and cheering at the career-ending injury of visiting team player [[Michael Irvin]] in 1999.  Often, sports heckling will also involve throwing objects onto the field; this has led most sports stadiums to ban glass containers and bottlecaps. Another famous heckler is [[Robert Szasz]], who regularly attends [[Tampa Bay Rays]] baseball games and is known for loudly heckling one opposing player per game or series. Former [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] [[association football|football]] star [[Dejan Savi\u0107evi\u0107]] is involved in an infamous incident with a heckler in which during an interview, a man on the street is heard shouting off-camera: \"You're a piece of shit!\"  Dejan berated the man, and went on to finish the interview, without missing a beat.\n\nIn English and Scottish [[association football|football]], heckling and swearing from the stands, and [[football chant]]s such as [[who ate all the pies?]] are common.\n\nAustralian sporting audiences are known for creative heckling. Perhaps the most famous is [[Yabba]] who had a grandstand at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]] named after him, and now a statue.\n\nThe sport of [[cricket]] is particularly notorious for heckling between the teams themselves, which is known as [[sledging (cricket)|sledging]].\n\nAt the NBA Drafts of recent years, many fans have gone with heckling [[ESPN]] [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] analyst and host of, [[Quite Frankly with Stephen A. Smith]], [[Stephen A. Smith]]. Most notably, The Stephen A. Smith Heckling Society of Gentlemen heckles him with a sock puppet dubbed as Stephen A. himself.\n\nTennis fans are also fairly noted for heckling. Some may call out during a service point to distract either player. Another common heckle from tennis fans is cheering after a service fault, which is considered to be rude and unsporting.\n\nIn 2009, then [[Toronto Blue Jays]] outfielder [[Alex R\u00edos]] was a victim of a heckling incident outside after a fund-raising event. The incident occurred after Rios declined to sign an autograph for a young fan, the same day he went 0 for 5 with 5 [[strikeouts]] in a game against the [[Los Angeles Angels]]. An older man yelled \"The way you played today Alex, you should be lucky someone wants your autograph.\" Rios then replied with \"Who gives a fuck\", repeating it until being ushered into a vehicle. Rios did apologize the next day,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/story/2009/06/05/sp-rios-youtube.html | work=CBC News | title=Rios apologizes for YouTube tirade at abusive fan | date=5 June 2009}}</ref> but was eventually placed on waivers and claimed by the [[Chicago White Sox]] later that year.\n\n==Music==\n{{Further|Electric Dylan controversy}}\nOne of the most famous heckles in music history occurred at a [[Bob Dylan]] concert at the [[Manchester Free Trade Hall]] in 1966. During a quiet moment in between songs, an audience member shouts very loudly and clearly, \"Judas!\" referencing Dylan's so-called betrayal of folk music by \"going electric\". Dylan replied: \"I don't believe you, you're a liar!\" before telling his band to \"Play it fucking loud!\" They play an acidic version of \"[[Like a Rolling Stone]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Glover|first=Tony|title=Bob Dylan Live 1966 Liner Notes|publisher=Columbia Records|year=1998|location=New York|page=7}}</ref> This incident was captured on tape and the full concert was released as volume four of Dylan's ''Live Bootleg Series''.\n\n==Stand-up comedy==\n{{Main article|Stand-up comedy}}\nIn stand-up comedy, a heckler is anyone who interrupts a comedian's set.<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=188\n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref> Hecklers want the stand-up to break the [[fourth wall]].<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/20 20]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=An audience may imply (through heckling, interrupting, etc.) a desire for the comic to break down the fourth wall and 'join the crow,' but experienced comedians know that this would only make the room more uncomfortable.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/20\n }}</ref> Most sources claim that heckling is uncommon.<ref name=parallel/><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.sacmag.com/2018/12/12/how-about-those-hecklers/\n |title=How About Those Hecklers?\n |last=Cassinos-Carr\n |first=Cathy\n |date=12 December 2018\n |website=Sacramento Magazine\n |access-date=27 March 2019\n |quote=You see a lot of heckler videos go viral. But that\u2019s not because heckling happens a lot.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n |last= Conway\n |first= Andrew\n |date= 11 December 1995\n |others=Collected by Robert Nelson, Scott Meltzer, Ngaio Bealum and Dave Gomez\n |title= You're Ugly, Your Dick Is Small, and Everybody Fucks Your Mother\u2014The Stand-Up Comedian's Response to the Heckler\n |url= http://www.juggling.org/~conway/juggler/MAL.TXT \n |format=Text\n |journal=[[Maledicta]], The International Journal of Verbal Aggression\n |location=Santa Rosa, CA\n |publisher=Maledicta Press\n |volume= 11\n |isbn=978-0916500313\n |access-date= 15 August 2019\n |quote=In performances by comedians in the USA it is not uncommon for a member of the audience to interrupt the performance by shouting a comment.}}</ref> Heckling can occur during [[Renegade show|open stage]] performances, and/or where alcoholic beverages are being consumed; it is regarded as a sign of audience members becoming impatient with what they regard as a low-quality performance.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |page=159\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5\n |quote=[Heckling] usually only happens because of one of two reasons: either you have lost the interest of the audience or the heckler is an idiot.}}</ref> New comics are often underprepared to properly handle hecklers.<ref name=parallel>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2004/aug/16/edinburgh04.edinburghfestival3\n |title=How can he show his face?\n |last=MacInnes\n |first=Paul\n |date=15 August 2004\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |others=Logan Murray\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=For new comics, heckling is like parallel parking for new drivers, you need to know how to do it, but it doesn't happen very often.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/136 136]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=To develop this kind of heckler-deflecting skill takes years; like writing and timing, it is developed with the benefit of those lovable comic twins: time and pain.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/136\n }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, live comedy venues tend to discourage heckling via signage and admissions policy, but tend to tolerate it as it creates customer loyalty. The etiquette of exactly how much heckling is tolerated differs immensely from venue to venue, however, but is generally more likely to be tolerated in blue-collar or working-class venues.\n\nComedians generally dislike heckling.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Sarah Silverman (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =40:44-41:10\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =I don't like hecklers, but I\u2019m fascinated by them, and you know, I don't have like bits for hecklers, but I just love going in and talking to\u2014giving them the attention that they need so badly and talking about it, you know, and where that comes from and how can I help you. How can I make you feel good about yourself?}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = Billy Connolly (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =34:20-34:33\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =I can never hear what a heckler is saying. I just respond wildly to them. And they might be saying, oh Billy, I love you\u2014I say, shut the fuck up! I don\u2019t really like them as a species.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.pattonoswalt.com/index.cfm?page=spew&id=167\n |title=A Closed Letter to Myself About Thievery, Heckling and Rape Jokes: Heckling\n |last=Oswalt\n |first=Patton\n |date=14 June 2014\n |website=Patton Oswalt\n |publisher=Patton Oswalt\n |access-date=3 February 2019\n |quote=Hecklers don\u2019t make a show memorable.  They prevent a show from being a fucking show.  Comedians do not love hecklers.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Billy Connolly\n | year =2011\n | title =The Art of Stand-Up\n | medium =TV\n | language =English\n | location =United Kingdom\n | time = 40:18-40:44\n | publisher =BBC: One\n | quote =I loathe hecklers. I haven't one good syllable to say about hecklers. When you've come out of the club circuit and all that and you're in the concert hall...they should be gone.\n | editor=Alan Yentob}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/08/how-to-deal-with-hecklers-according-to-nine-top-st.html\n |title=How to Deal With Hecklers: Tips From Nine Top Stand-up Comics\n |last=Fernandez\n |first=Jesse\n |date=29 August 2016\n |website=Paste\n |publisher=Paste Media Group.\n |access-date=23 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://westsidetoastmasters.com/article_reference/handling_hecklers.html\n |title=Handling the Heckler\n |website=Toastmasters International\n |access-date=23 March 2019\n |quote=I asked some fellow comedians what they thought about hecklers. As you might imagine, it was tough to get a straight answer:}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |others=Pat Condell\n |page=177\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5\n |quote=I've never met a heckler I didn't want to punch in the face.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Zoglin\n |first=Richard\n |date=22 January 2008\n |title=Comedy at the Edge: How Stand-up in the 1970s Changed America\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xtCmCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46&dq=%22comedy+at+the+edge%22+%22fork%22&source=bl&ots=j61EvmQJIL&sig=ACfU3U3nJFCjoWuTfN3xWBeuDpHo26asZg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimvJzgt-viAhXQ1FkKHWPKD3cQ6AEwA3oECCAQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22comedy%20at%20the%20edge%22%20%22fork%22&f=false\n |publisher=Bloomsbury USA\n |page=46\n |isbn=978-1582346243\n |access-date=15 June 2019\n |quote=Even in the Caf\u00e9 Wha? days, Roth remembers seeing Pryor get so enraged at a heckler that he stabbed the guy with a fork.}}</ref> Hecklers may rarely threaten or physically assault comedians.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = Billy Connolly (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =38:13-38:17\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =There's a guy [who] punched me onstage.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/134 134]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Generally, however, any comic\u2019s physical encounters onstage can be counted on one hand\u2014more often, one finger\u2026Insults about appearance are almost exclusively aimed at women [comics].\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/134\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last         = Perrett\n | first        = Connor\n | date         = 22 July 2019\n | title        = Stand-Up Comedian Says He Was Punched By A Trump Supporter For Telling A Joke About The President\n | url          = https://www.inquisitr.com/5543688/stand-up-comedian-says-he-was-punched-by-a-trump-supporter-for-telling-a-joke-about-the-president/\n | work         = The Inquisitr\n | access-date  = 14 August 2019\n | quote        = Following Fontenot\u2019s quip, the man reportedly stormed the stage and punched the comedian in the face, causing him to lose consciousness.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/133 133-134]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Alan Harvey was once stabbed with a pencil by a crazed female patron. [[Tom Dreesen]] remembers, in the days when he was part of a double act with [[Tim Reid]]...\u2018One night, one drunk walked by, put a lit cigarette out in Tom\u2019s face...He says that cmics are particularly vulnerable up there because the light is directly in their faces, so they can't see where a potential attacker is coming from. Jonathan Solomon says that he was once attacked by a drunk man...and nobody came onstage to help...another time...in Washington, a man threw a drink at him onstage.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/133\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/theatreblog/2010/aug/24/heckling-comedy-goes-bad\n |title=When heckling goes bad\n |last=Kettle\n |first=James\n |date=24 August 2010\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |access-date=23 March 2019\n |quote= There are numerous stories of comics being attacked by audience members \u2013 in fact YouTube footage exists of one of the biggest draws at this year's fringe, Australian comic Jim Jeffries, being punched in the head onstage at the Manchester Comedy Store.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.courant.com/breaking-news/hc-br-manchester-heckler-arrest-20190225-kqy6c7lwmncmlcsxdfaw3t7pve-story.html\n |title=Police say heckler pulled knife, threatened comedian at Manchester club\n |last= Leavenworth\n |first=Jesse\n |date=25 February 2019\n |website=Hartford Courant\n |access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-46382267\n |title=Heckling: How to deal with it during a comedy show\n |last= McGregor\n |first=Nesta\n |date=29 November 2018\n |website=BBC News\n |publisher=BBC\n |others=Ian Smith\n |access-date=27 March 2019\n |quote=Ian says while the crowd saw the funny side of the gag, the man had to be restrained by his friends\u2014before later being escorted out of the venue.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last         = Zinoman\n | first        = Jason \n | date         = 17 July 2012\n | title        = Toe-to-Toe at the Edge of the Comedy Club Stage\n | url          = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/18/arts/television/when-the-comic-and-the-heckler-both-take-offense.html\n |url-access = limited\n | work         = The New York Times\n | publisher  = New York Times Company\n | access-date  = 15 June 2019\n |quote = [A] heckler ended an exchange with Tammy Pescatelli, a veteran comic, by tossing a wine glass at her at a club in Jacksonville, Fla., scratching her cornea.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | author       =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n | date         = 26 July 2012\n | title        = Woman May Sue Comedian Eddie Griffin Over Pleasanton Heckling\n | url          = https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2012/07/26/woman-may-sue-comedian-eddie-griffin-over-pleasanton-heckling/\n | work         = CBS SF BayArea\n |location = San Francisco\n | publisher  = CBS Broadcasting Inc.\n | access-date  = 15 June 2019\n |quote =It was a chaotic scene as a woman throws her drink at Griffin at Tommy T\u2019s. Fiona Walshe said she was taunted by Griffin for being a lesbian.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Bobby Lee (comedian), Michael Addis (director)\n | year =2007\n | title =Heckler\n | language =English\n | time =8:12-9:00\n | publisher =FilmRise\n | quote =I was onstage in New Mexico and some kid was going\u2014just halfway through a punchline I hear\u2014ching, ching, ching chong ching, ching chong ching chong, ching ching chong. This was a ''really'' dark, Mexican guy. So then I just basically went, '[variation of \u00e1ndale]\u2014hey, I'm digging a ditch,' you know (laughs to camera), 'I'm a ditch-digger.' Then, all of the sudden, through my peripheral I see him climbing onto the stage. So I keep going, then all of the sudden, like, I black out. I\u2019m literally like, on the stage, laying there. He had punched me (pause) in the face.}}</ref> Even more rarely, comedians may receive death threats.<ref>{{cite news\n | last         = Hofstetter\n | first        = Steve\n | date         = 18 July 2019\n | title        = A Comedian's Guide To Handling Nazi Death Threats\n | url          = https://www.cjnews.com/perspectives/opinions/a-comedians-guide-to-handling-nazi-death-threats\n | work         = The Canadian Jewish News\n | access-date  = 19 July 2019\n |quote         = I received 252 death threats, both direct and indirect [that I reported to the FBI]...I [talked] with one of the agents, who let me know that some of the folks that were threatening me were career criminals.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | author       = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n | date         = 24 March 2019\n | title        = Kathy Griffin on receiving death threats\n | url          = https://www.cbsnews.com/video/kathy-griffin-on-receiving-death-threats/\n | work         = CBS News\n | access-date  = 19 July 2019\n |quote         = On the day that I filmed...two FBI agents come in...they told me that they had [knowledge of] an imminent threat, [[October 2018 United States mail bombing attempts|Cesar Sayoc]] had shared his list with like-minded people}}</ref>\n\n===Countering===\nComedians counter hecklers by controlling the flow of conversation.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/136 136]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[[Adrianne Tolsch]] says that, like stand-up in general, the key to dealing with hecklers is to remember, \u2018it\u2019s all about control\u2026it\u2019s not what you say, it\u2019s how fast and forcefully you say it\u2019\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/136\n }}</ref> Some comedians ignore the heckling.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://mentalfloss.com/article/54496/11-ways-handle-heckler\n |title=11 Ways to Handle a Heckler\n |last=Patrick\n |first=Colin\n |date=13 January 2014\n |website=Mental Floss\n |publisher=minute media\n |access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-46382267\n |title=Heckling: How to deal with it during a comedy show\n |last= McGregor\n |first=Nesta\n |date=29 November 2018\n |website=BBC News\n |publisher=BBC\n |others=Ian Smith\n |access-date=27 March 2019\n |quote=I sometimes try to ignore them because it might be the attention that they're after.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/135 135]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Carol [Siskind] says, she acts as she does in any heckling episode: \u2018I try to ignore them [at first]\u2026or I state my position right away.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/135\n }}</ref> Others devise a strategy for quashing such outbursts, usually by having a repertoire of [[insult|comebacks]] for hecklers{{refn|<ref>{{cite journal\n |last= Conway\n |first= Andrew\n |date= 11 December 1995\n |others=Collected by Robert Nelson, Scott Meltzer, Ngaio Bealum and Dave Gomez\n |title= You're Ugly, Your Dick Is Small, and Everybody Fucks Your Mother\u2014The Stand-Up Comedian's Response to the Heckler\n |url= http://www.juggling.org/~conway/juggler/MAL.TXT \n |format=Text\n |journal=[[Maledicta]], The International Journal of Verbal Aggression\n |location=Santa Rosa, CA\n |publisher=Maledicta Press\n |volume= 11\n |isbn=978-0916500313\n |access-date= 15 August 2019\n |quote=The comedian's response to the heckler is called a 'heckler line'...A successful comedian will usually have a large repertoire of lines, and will attempt to choose one that fits the situation, as this will make the response appear to be improvised.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah \n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha \n |year=2016 \n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy \n |others=Jim Jefferies \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc \n |pages=230\u2013231 \n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0 \n |quote=I have a list of three or four [comebacks]...and the rest will be off the cuff}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/135 135-136]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Like all comics, [Carol Siskind\u2019s] responses to hecklers are usually not ad-libs, but cold, calculated antidotes\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/135\n }}</ref>}}\u2014known as \"heckler lines\" or \"[[wikt:squelch|squelches]]\"\u2014on hand; those who handle the moment in an off-the-cuff manner do so by giving the heckler \"enough rope to hang themselves.\"<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |page=165,174\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Apatow\n |first=Judd\n |others=Jay Leno\n |year=2016\n |title=Sick In The Head\n |location=NY\n |publisher=Random House\n |page=162\n |isbn=978-0-8129-8728-7\n |quote=[G]ive them enough rope so they hang themselves}}</ref> [[Stewart Lee]] treats heckles as genuine inquiries.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = Stewart Lee (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =41:10-41:50\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =Another...way of controlling a room, which again can lead to fantastic deaths but really enjoyable ones, is to treat abusive heckles as if they were genuine inquiries\u2026and actually to answer them at such length that the people regret having asked the question in the first place.}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n | url=https://www.comedianscomedian.com/200-stewart-lee/ \n | title=The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith: 200 Stewart Lee\n | others=Stewart Lee\n | website=The Comedian\u2019s Comedian\n | publisher=Stuart Goldsmith\n | host=Stuart Goldsmith\n | date=6 March 2017\n | time=18:30-18:55\n | access-date=13 February 2019\n | quote =I try to treat all heckles as a genuine inquiry\u2026and I know where I\u2019ve got that from. It\u2019s from one recording[, a track called ''Life on the Road'',] of [[Ted Chippington]]['s album, ''Man in a Suitcase'']}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Frances-White\n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur\n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Stewart Lee\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=160\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=I treat it [the heckle] like it's an honest inquiry.}}</ref> [[Jerry Seinfeld]] is a \"Heckle Therapist,\" who verbally sympathizes with the heckler to confuse the heckler and win the audience over.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.backstage.com/magazine/article/become-standup-comedian-2468/\n |title=How to Become a Standup Comedian\n |last= Lindsay\n |first=Benjamin\n |date=8 January 2018\n |website=backstage\n |publisher=Backstage\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=[Jerry Seinfeld is a] Heckle Therapist...when people would say something nasty...[he] would...become...sympathetic to them and try to help them with their problem...to work out what was upsetting them, and try to be...understanding with their anger\u2026[he] would counsel the heckler...'You seem so upset, and I know that's not what you wanted to have happen tonight. Let's talk about your problem,\u2019 and the audience...[found] it funny and it would [confuse the heckler]}}</ref> Some comedians will get hecklers to repeat themselves to take away the momentum and laughter from the heckle.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don\u2019t Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=57\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=[When asked to repeat what they said], the heckler will freeze up...[or if they do repeat it], it won't have as much steam.}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\n[[Bill Burr]] performed a set in Philadelphia where he reprimanded an audience of over ten thousand people.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/comedian-bill-burr-explains-his-epic-philly-rant-2006-show/\n |title=Comedian Bill Burr explains his epically profane 'Philly rant' at '06 show\n |last=Tanenbaum\n |first=Michael\n |date=30 November 2017\n |website=Philly Voice\n |publisher=WWB Holdings, LLC.\u00a0\n |access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref> [[Michael Richards]] became upset with a heckler and called them the N-word several times.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.wweek.com/bump/2016/11/29/the-day-the-clown-cried-pinpointing-the-single-destructive-moments-that-disgraced-famous-comedians-careers/\n |title=The Single Destructive Moments That Disgraced Famous Comedians' Careers\n |date=29 November 2016\n |website=Willamette Week\n |publisher=Willamette Week\n |access-date=27 March 2019\n |quote=Nov. 17, 2006: Michael Richards\u00a0goes on a racist rant at the Laugh Factory in L.A. }}</ref> When a female audience member claimed that rape jokes are never funny, [[Daniel Tosh]] allegedly made an off-the-cuff retort that it would be funny if she were to be immediately raped.<ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Holpunch\n| first        = Amanda\n| date         = 11 July 2012\n| title        = Daniel Tosh apologises for rape joke as fellow comedians defend topic\n| url          = https://www.theguardian.com/culture/us-news-blog/2012/jul/11/daniel-tosh-apologises-rape-joke\n| work         = The Guardian\n| publisher  = Guardian News & Media Limited\n| access-date  = 15 June 2019\n|quote = In a blog entry posted on Tumblr, an audience member wrote that after Tosh told a series of jokes proclaiming that rape is always funny, she called out \u2018Actually, rape jokes are never funny!' To which she claims Tosh replied: \u2018Wouldn't it be funny if that girl got raped by like, five guys right now? Like right now? What if a bunch of guys just raped her'}}</ref>\n\n==Other comedy mediums==\nThe comedy TV series ''[[The Muppet Show]]'' featured a pair of hecklers named [[Statler and Waldorf]]. These characters created a kind of meta-comedy act in which the show's official comedian, [[Fozzie Bear]], acted as their usual [[Double act|foil]], although they occasionally made jokes at other characters as well.\n\nAnother notable use of heckling in comedy is in the cult favorite series ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]''. The series involves a man (either Joel Robinson or Mike Nelson) and two robots (Tom Servo and Crow T. Robot) sitting in a theater mocking bad B-movies. This style of comedy, coined as riffing, is continued with commentary-based series such as [[Rifftrax]] and [[Cinematic Titanic]].\n\nIn one of [[Rowan Atkinson]]'s plays \"The School Master\", a heckler interrupted his play by shouting \"Here!\" after Atkinson had read out an amusing name on his register. Atkinson incorporated it into his act by saying \"I have a detention book...\"<ref>{{cite serial\n| title        = Headmaster\n| episode      = The Secret Policeman's Ball\n| url          = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uWJ7bhKYsuw\n| series       = The Secret Policeman's Balls\n| last         = Atkinson \n| first        = Rowan\n| authorlink   = Rowan Atkinson\n| date         = 27\u201330 June 1979\n| minutes      = 0:54}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Applause]]\n*[[Audience participation|Audience Participation]]\n*[[Booing]]\n*[[Heckler's veto]]\n*[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]], a TV show built on humorous heckling.\n*[[Troll (Internet)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Censorship}}\n\n[[Category:Human communication]]\n[[Category:Comedy]]\n[[Category:Show business terms]]\n[[Category:Stand-up comedy]]\n", "name_user": "NurishmentForThinking", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStand-up comedy:added citation; condensed two groups of citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heckler"}
{"title_page": "Waldemar Henrici", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Waldemar Henrici\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1878|02|03}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1950|02|15|1878|02|03}}\n| birth_place   = [[Bensberg]], [[Cologne]]\n| death_place   = [[Marktbreit]], [[Kitzingen (district)|Kitzingen]], [[Regierungsbezirk]] [[Unterfranken]] in [[Bavaria]]\n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    =  {{plainlist |\n* {{flag|Prussia}} (to 1918)\n* {{flag|Weimar Republic}} (to 1933)\n* {{flag|Nazi Germany}} (to 1944)\n  }}\n| branch        = [[Prussian Army]]<br />''[[Reichsheer]]''<br />[[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1896\u20131943\n| rank          = [[Lieutenant General]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = \n* '''[[World War I]]'''\n* '''[[World War II]]'''\n** [[Operation Barbarossa]]\n| battles_label = \n| awards        = \n* [[Iron Cross]] Class II and Class I\n* Prussian Service Cross\n* Bavarian Military Cross of Merit Class IV with Swords\n* Knight's Cross, First Class of the Order of Albrecht with swords \n* Knight's Cross, First Class of the Order of Frederick with swords \n* The Prince of Schaumburg-Lippe Cross for Faithful Service\n* Austrian Military Merit Cross Class III\n* Iron Crescent\n| spouse        = \n| relations     =\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = \n}}\n'''Waldemar Henrici''' (February 3, 1878 - February 15, 1950) was a [[Lieutenant General]] of the [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Wehrmacht]] who commanded a division of the [[VII Army Corps (Wehrmacht)|VII Army Corps]] in the [[4th Army (Wehrmacht)|4th Army]] during [[Operation Barbarossa]], the German invasion of [[Russia]] during the [[Second World War]], and also a leading figure in the [[Reichsarbeitsdienst]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early life and service===\nHenrici was born in [[Bensberg]], [[Cologne]], and began his military career in the [[Prussian Army]] in 1896, becoming a lieutenant in 1906 and a captain in 1911. He was attached to the [[Prussian Minister of War|Prussian War Ministry]] in 1914 before departing for the front lines as a major in 1916.\n\n===Inter-war years===\nFollowing the end of the war he worked for the Defence Ministry as a lecturer, reaching the rank of lieutenant colonel in 1921. He received a [[doctorate]] in [[political science]] in 1923 with a dissertation entitled \"The coal industry in Russia and after the war\".<ref>Waldemar Henrici: \u201eDie Kohlenwirtschaft Russlands in und nach dem Kriege\u201c, J. Springer, Berlin, 1924.</ref>\n\nHenrici commanded forces in the [[Reichswehr]] in 1932, becoming a colonel in 1925. He took command of the 2nd Prussian Infantry Regiment in [[Olsztyn]] in 1928. With the rise of [[Nazi Germany]] he became an Arbeitsgauleiters in the Reichsarbeitsdienst. In 1933 he became Secretary of State in the Ministry of Labour and later Reich Commissioner in the [[Freiwilliger Arbeitsdienst]].\n\n===World War II===\nHenrici rejoined the army in 1939, and took command of the [[555th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|555th Infantry Division]] stationed on the [[Rhine]] in 1940. He took part in the initial action against [[France]] before being sent to [[Poland]] to command the [[258th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|258th Infantry Division]]. In 1941 he led his division in [[Operation Barbarossa]], being promoted to lieutenant general in October 1941. He was wounded the following day and spent two months in hospital.<br> \nAfter his return he became ''[[Wehrmachtbefehlshaber]] Ukraine'' (military commander of [[Reichskommissariat Ukraine]]). He went into retirement in December 1943, and died in 1950 in [[Marktbreit]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bundesarchiv.de/aktenreichskanzlei/1919-1933/1000/adr/adrhl/kap1_1/para2_197.html Waldemar Henrici] from Das Bundesarchiv, Munich Historical Archives.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henrici, Waldemar}}\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1950 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Cologne]]\n[[Category:Prussian Army personnel]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:People from the Rhine Province]]\n[[Category:Major generals of the Reichswehr]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Iron Cross (1914), 1st class]]\n[[Category:Knights 1st class of the Albert Order]]\n[[Category:Knights 1st class of the Friedrich Order]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Liakat Medal]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant generals of the German Army (Wehrmacht)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Waldemar Henrici\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1878|02|03}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1950|02|15|1878|02|03}}\n| birth_place   = [[Bensberg]], [[Cologne]]\n| death_place   = [[Marktbreit]], [[Kitzingen (district)|Kitzingen]], [[Regierungsbezirk]] [[Unterfranken]] in [[Bavaria]]\n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    =  {{plainlist |\n* {{flag|Prussia}} (to 1918)\n* {{flag|Weimar Republic}} (to 1933)\n* {{flag|Nazi Germany}} (to 1944)\n  }}\n| branch        = [[Prussian Army]]<br />''[[Reichsheer]]''<br />[[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1896\u20131943\n| rank          = [[Lieutenant General]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = \n* '''[[World War I]]'''\n* '''[[World War II]]'''\n** [[Operation Barbarossa]]\n| battles_label = \n| awards        = \n* [[Iron Cross]] Class II and Class I\n* Prussian Service Cross\n* Bavarian Military Cross of Merit Class IV with Swords\n* Knight's Cross, First Class of the Order of Albrecht with swords \n* Knight's Cross, First Class of the Order of Frederick with swords \n* The Prince of Schaumburg-Lippe Cross for Faithful Service\n* Austrian Military Merit Cross Class III\n* Iron Crescent\n| spouse        = \n| relations     =\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = \n}}\n'''Waldemar Henrici''' (February 3, 1878 - February 15, 1950) was a [[Lieutenant General]] of the [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Wehrmacht]] who commanded a division of the [[VII Army Corps (Wehrmacht)|VII Army Corps]] in the [[4th Army (Wehrmacht)|4th Army]] during [[Operation Barbarossa]], the German invasion of [[Russia]] during the [[Second World War]], and also a leading figure in the [[Reichsarbeitsdienst]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early life and service===\nHenrici was born in [[Bensberg]], [[Cologne]], and began his military career in the [[Prussian Army]] in 1896, becoming a lieutenant in 1906 and a captain in 1911. He was attached to the [[Prussian Minister of War|Prussian War Ministry]] in 1914 before departing for the front lines as a major in 1916.\n\n===Inter-war years===\nFollowing the end of the war he worked for the Defence Ministry as a lecturer, reaching the rank of lieutenant colonel in 1921. He received a [[doctorate]] in [[political science]] in 1923 with a dissertation entitled \"The coal industry in Russia and after the war\".<ref>Waldemar Henrici: \u201eDie Kohlenwirtschaft Russlands in und nach dem Kriege\u201c, J. Springer, Berlin, 1924.</ref>\n\nHenrici commanded forces in the [[Reichswehr]] in 1932, becoming a colonel in 1925. He took command of the 2nd Prussian Infantry Regiment in [[Olsztyn]] in 1928. With the rise of [[Nazi Germany]] he became an Arbeitsgauleiters in the Reichsarbeitsdienst. In 1933 he became Secretary of State in the Ministry of Labour and later Reich Commissioner in the [[Freiwilliger Arbeitsdienst]].\n\n===World War II===\nHenrici rejoined the army in 1939, and took command of the [[555th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|555th Infantry Division]] stationed on the [[Rhine]] in 1940. He took part in the initial action against [[France]] before being sent to [[Poland]] to command the [[258th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|258th Infantry Division]]. In 1941 he led his division in [[Operation Barbarossa]], being promoted to lieutenant general in October 1941. He was wounded the following day and spent two months in hospital.<br> \nAfter his return he became [[Wehrmachtbefehlshaber Ukraine]] (military commander of [[Reichskommissariat Ukraine]]). He went into retirement in December 1943, and died in 1950 in [[Marktbreit]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bundesarchiv.de/aktenreichskanzlei/1919-1933/1000/adr/adrhl/kap1_1/para2_197.html Waldemar Henrici] from Das Bundesarchiv, Munich Historical Archives.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henrici, Waldemar}}\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1950 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Cologne]]\n[[Category:Prussian Army personnel]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:People from the Rhine Province]]\n[[Category:Major generals of the Reichswehr]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Iron Cross (1914), 1st class]]\n[[Category:Knights 1st class of the Albert Order]]\n[[Category:Knights 1st class of the Friedrich Order]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Liakat Medal]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant generals of the German Army (Wehrmacht)]]\n", "name_user": "Skjoldbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorld War II", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waldemar_Henrici"}
{"title_page": "2009 World Series", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox World Series Expanded\n| image = 2009 World Series logo.svg\n| country = World\n| year = 2009\n| champion = [[2009 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]&nbsp;(4)\n| champion_manager = [[Joe Girardi]]\n| champion_games = 103\u201359, {{winpct|103|59}}\n| runnerup = [[2009 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]]&nbsp;(2)\n| runnerup_manager = [[Charlie Manuel]]\n| runnerup_games = 93\u201369, {{winpct|93|69}}\n| date= October 28 \u2013 November 4\n| MVP = [[Hideki Matsui]] (Yankees)\n| television = [[Fox Major League Baseball|Fox]] ([[United States]])<br/>[[MLB International]] (International)\n| announcers = [[Joe Buck]]<!-- play-by-play --> and [[Tim McCarver]]<!-- color commentator --> ([[Fox Major League Baseball|Fox]])<br/>[[Dave O'Brien (sportscaster)|Dave O'Brien]] and [[Rick Sutcliffe]] (MLB International)\n| radio_network = [[Major League Baseball on ESPN Radio|ESPN]]<br />[[WCBS (AM)|WCBS]] (Yankees)<br/>[[WPHT]] (Phillies)\n| radio_announcers = [[Jon Miller]] and [[Joe Morgan]] (ESPN)<br />[[John Sterling (sportscaster)|John Sterling]] and [[Suzyn Waldman]] (Yankees)<br />[[Scott Franzke]], [[Tom McCarthy (broadcaster)|Tom McCarthy]], [[Chris Wheeler]], [[Larry Andersen]], and [[Gary Matthews]] (Phillies)\n| umpires = [[Gerry Davis (umpire)|Gerry Davis]] (crew chief), [[Jeff Nelson (umpire)|Jeff Nelson]], [[Brian Gorman]], [[Mike Everitt (baseball)|Mike Everitt]], [[Dana DeMuth]], [[Joe West (umpire)|Joe West]]\n| HOFers = '''Yankees:''' [[Derek Jeter]], [[Mariano Rivera]]<br />'''Phillies:''' [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]]\n| ALCS = '''[[2009 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]''' defeated [[2009 Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim season|Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]], 4\u20132\n| NLCS = '''[[2009 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]]''' defeated [[2009 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]], 4\u20131\n| image2 =\n}}\nThe '''2009 World Series''' was the [[World Series|championship series]] of [[Major League Baseball]]'s (MLB) [[2009 Major League Baseball season|2009 season]]. As the 105th<ref name=\"wshistory\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/|title=Playoff and World Series Stats and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100109123742/http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/| archivedate=January 9, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> edition of the World Series, it was a [[best-of-seven playoff]] contested between the [[2009 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]], champions of the [[National League]] (NL) and [[2008 Philadelphia Phillies season|defending World Series champions]], and the [[2009 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]], champions of the [[American League]] (AL). The Yankees defeated the Phillies, 4 games to 2, winning their 27th World Series championship. The series was played between October 28 and November 4, broadcast on [[Major League Baseball on Fox|Fox]], and watched by an average of roughly 19&nbsp;million viewers. Due to the start of the season being pushed back by the [[2009 World Baseball Classic]] in March, this was the first World Series regularly scheduled to be played into the month of November. This series was a rematch of the [[1950 World Series]].\n\n[[Home advantage|Home field advantage]] for the Series went to the AL for the eighth straight year as a result of its 4\u20133 win in the [[2009 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]]. The Phillies earned their berth into the [[2009 Major League Baseball season#Postseason|playoffs]] by winning the [[National League East]]. The Yankees won the [[American League East]] to earn their berth, posting the best record in the Major Leagues. The Phillies reached the World Series by defeating the [[2009 Colorado Rockies season|Colorado Rockies]] in the best-of-five [[2009 National League Division Series|National League Division Series]], and the [[2009 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] in the best-of-seven [[2009 National League Championship Series|NL Championship Series]] (NLCS). The Yankees defeated the [[2009 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]] in the [[2009 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] and the [[2009 Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim season|Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]] in the [[2009 American League Championship Series|AL Championship Series]] (ALCS) to advance to their first World Series since [[2003 World Series|2003]]. As a result of their loss, the Phillies became the first team since the {{wsy|2001}} Yankees to lose the World Series after winning it the previous year.\n\n[[Cliff Lee]] pitched a [[complete game]] in the Phillies' Game&nbsp;1 victory, allowing only one [[Earned run#Unearned run|unearned run]], while [[Chase Utley]] hit two home runs. In Game&nbsp;2, solo [[home run]]s by [[Mark Teixeira]] and [[Hideki Matsui]] helped the Yankees win by a score of 3\u20131. After a [[rain delay]]ed start, Game&nbsp;3 featured more offense, with a combined six home runs and thirteen total [[run (baseball)|runs]] en route to a Yankee victory. The Yankees won Game&nbsp;4 by scoring the decisive three runs in the ninth inning after an alert [[base running]] play by [[Johnny Damon]]. The Phillies avoided elimination with a win in Game&nbsp;5, aided by Utley's second two\u2013home run game of the series. The Yankees secured their World Series championship with a Game 6 victory in which Matsui hit his third home run of the series. He was named [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]] (MVP) of the series, making him the first Japanese-born player and the first full-time [[designated hitter]] to win the award. Matsui was the series' MVP despite starting only the three games that were played at Yankee Stadium, since the designated hitter position is not used in NL ballparks.\n\nSeveral records were tied, extended, or broken during this World Series, including team championships (Yankees with 27), career postseason wins ([[Andy Pettitte]] with 18), career World Series [[Save (baseball)|saves]] ([[Mariano Rivera]] with 11), home runs in a World Series (Utley with five), [[strikeout]]s by a hitter in a World Series ([[Ryan Howard]] with 13), and [[run batted in|runs batted in]] in a single World Series game (Matsui with six).\n\n==How they got there==\n\n===Philadelphia Phillies===\n{{Main|2009 Philadelphia Phillies season}}\nDuring the off-season, the Phillies promoted assistant general manager [[Rub\u00e9n Amaro Jr.]] to [[General manager (baseball)|general manager]], succeeding [[Pat Gillick]] who retired at the end of a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081103&content_id=3660782&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi&partnerId=rss_phi|title= Amaro Jr. takes over reins for Phillies|accessdate=November 3, 2008|last=Mandel|first=Ken|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 3, 2008}}</ref> Their most notable offseason player change was in [[left field]], as [[Pat Burrell]] departed due to [[Free agent|free agency]] and was replaced by free agent [[Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081216&content_id=3718927|title=Ibanez excited to join world champs|last=Gonzalez|first=Alden|date=December 16, 2008|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=March 2, 2009}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Another notable acquisition was free agent [[pitcher]] [[Chan Ho Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081215&content_id=3717580&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|first=Anthony|last=DiComo|date=December 15, 2008|accessdate=October 26, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|work=[[MLB.com]]|title=Park agrees to one-year deal with Phils|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212093738/http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081215&content_id=3717580&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|archivedate=February 12, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Park was originally signed as a backup option for the [[bullpen]], as [[relief pitcher|reliever]] [[J. C. Romero]] was assigned a 50-game suspension after violating the [[Major League Baseball drug policy]], but Park won the fifth [[Starting pitcher|starter]]'s job in [[Spring Training]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/story/11573963|title=Phillies release veteran outfielder Jenkins, name Park fifth starter|date=March 31, 2009|work=CBS Sports|accessdate=April 3, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3812334 |title=Suspended Romero 'didn't cheat' |date=January 9, 2009|first=Peter|last=Gammons|authorlink=Peter Gammons|accessdate=March 3, 2011|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2009, Phillies scouts evaluated pitcher [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]] in two simulated games against the [[Dominican Summer Phillies|Phillies DSL team]], leading to a one-year, $1-million contract.<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090714&content_id=5875102&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi Pedro signs one-year deal with Phillies]. Mlb.mlb.com. Retrieved on December 21, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4338734 Pedro Martinez throws first bullpen session since joining Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 ESPN]. Sports.espn.go.com (July 18, 2009). Retrieved on December 21, 2013.</ref> Replacing [[Jamie Moyer]] as a starter in the Phillies rotation on August 12, 2009, Philadelphia won each of Mart\u00ednez's first seven starts, the first time in franchise history that this had occurred with any debuting Phillies pitcher.<ref>{{cite web|author=ESPN.com |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/notebook?page=bbtn/090913|title=Baseball Tonight Clubhouse: Rockies search for wins, not respect|publisher=ESPN.com|date=September 13, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2010}}</ref> The Phillies made one large acquisition at the [[trade deadline]], trading four minor league players to the [[2009 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]] for pitcher [[Cliff Lee]] and [[outfielder]] [[Ben Francisco]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4363553 |title=Phillies get Lee from Indians |accessdate=January 6, 2010|first=Jayson|last=Stark|authorlink=Jayson Stark|date=August 1, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures}}</ref> Lee won seven of his twelve regular season starts for Philadelphia in 2009.<ref name=\"leebref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/l/leecl02.shtml|title=Cliff Lee Statistics and History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring the regular season, the Phillies led the [[National League East]] for most of the year, taking first place for good on May 30.<ref name=\"2009Phillies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/PHI/2009-schedule-scores.shtml|title=2009 Philadelphia Phillies Schedule, Box Scores and Splits|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=November 17, 2009}}</ref> Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez had started the year strongly, [[Batting average (baseball)|batting]] well over .300 with 17 [[home run]]s and 46 [[runs batted in]] (RBI) in the first two months of the season, which led the ''[[New York Post]]'' to call him an \"early [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] candidate\".<ref name=\"ibanezsplits\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/split.cgi?id=ibanera01&year=2009&t=b|title=Raul Ibanez 2009 Batting Splits|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/item_MbiqdejYNCrqysNXl7buVL| title=Champion Phillies Bringing Big Bats to Bronx| last=Puma | first=Mike | work= [[New York Post]]| date=May 22, 2009|accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref> He was placed on the [[disabled list]] in mid-June for a groin injury, however, and though he returned he did not bat above .260 for any other month that season.<ref name=\"ibanezsplits\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090618&content_id=5393172|first=David|last=Gurian-Peck|date=June 18, 2009|accessdate=March 1, 2011|publisher=Major League Baseball|work=[[MLB.com]]|title=Phillies' Ibanez lands on disabled list}}</ref> Although Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez did not receive MVP votes his teammates [[Ryan Howard]] and [[Chase Utley]] had successful years, finishing 3rd and 8th in the balloting respectively.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_2009.shtml#NLmvp|title=2009 Awards Voting|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref> The Phillies finished the season with a record of 93\u201369 (.574), six games above the second-place [[2009 Florida Marlins season|Florida Marlins]] in their division.<ref name=\"2009Phillies\"/>\n\nThe Phillies defeated the [[Wild card (sports)|wild card]] [[2009 Colorado Rockies season|Colorado Rockies]] in the [[2009 National League Division Series|National League Division Series]] (NLDS), three games to one, advancing to the [[2009 National League Championship Series|National League Championship Series]] (NLCS).<ref name=\"2009Phillies\"/> Facing the [[2009 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]], the Phillies won the NLCS, four games to one,<ref name=\"2009Phillies\"/> becoming the first team to repeat as [[National League]] champions since the [[1995 Atlanta Braves season|1995]]\u2013[[1996 Atlanta Braves season|96]] [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref name=\"Repeat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/|title=Major League Encyclopedia|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100109123721/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/| archivedate=January 9, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Ryan Howard won the [[League Championship Series Most Valuable Player Award|NLCS MVP]] for his strong offensive performance during the series.<ref name=\"nlcsmvp\">{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4584440 |title=Phillies' Howard takes home NLCS MVP |accessdate=February 27, 2011|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=October 22, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures}}</ref> Howard tied [[Lou Gehrig]]'s postseason record by having at least one [[Run batted in|RBI]] in eight straight games across the NLDS and NLCS.<ref name=\"nlcsmvp\"/> They became the first World Series champion to return to the World Series the following year since the [[2000 New York Yankees season|2000]]\u2013[[2001 New York Yankees season|01 New York Yankees]].<ref name=\"wshistory\"/>\n\n===New York Yankees===\n[[File:Yankees Celebrate Jeter Hit -2722.jpg|thumb|right|225px|The Yankees celebrate Derek Jeter breaking their franchise career hits record.|alt=Several men in pinstriped pants and red baseball caps, some wearing pinstriped baseball jerseys and some dark blue-hooded sweatshirts, stand in a group.]]\n{{Main|2009 New York Yankees season}}\nThe Yankees' offseason began in November 2008 with control over their organization shifting from long-time owner [[George Steinbrenner]] to his son [[Hal Steinbrenner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081120&content_id=3686135&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Control of Yankees shifts to son Hal|date=November 20, 2008|last=Bloom|first=Barry|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> Notable player departures included [[Mike Mussina]]\u2014who announced his retirement on November 20, 2008<ref>{{cite web |title=Mussina retires on a high note, with 20 wins in final season|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3715207|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=November 20, 2008|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\u2014as well as [[Bobby Abreu]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090210&content_id=3816686&vkey=hotstove2008&fext=.jsp|title=Out of left field, Abreu joins Angels|date=February 12, 2009|last=Spencer|first=Lyle|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203020042/http://www.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090210&content_id=3816686&vkey=hotstove2008&fext=.jsp|archivedate=February 3, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Jason Giambi]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090106&content_id=3735119&vkey=hotstove2008&fext=.jsp|title=Giambi 'excited to be home' with A's|date=January 7, 2009|last=Urban|first=Mychael|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> and [[Carl Pavano]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090109&content_id=3738312|title=Pavano finds right fit with Indians|date=January 9, 2009|last=Castrovince|first=Anthony|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> who all left as free agents. Notable free agent acquisitions included starting pitchers [[CC Sabathia]] and [[A. J. Burnett]], and [[first baseman]] [[Mark Teixeira]]. Another major addition was outfielder [[Nick Swisher]], acquired in a trade with the [[2008 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Yankees acquire Swisher, send Betemit and two pitchers to White Sox|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3700869|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|first=Jerry|last=Crasnick|authorlink=Jerry Crasnick|date=November 13, 2008|accessdate=November 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees played the 2009 season in [[Yankee Stadium]], their first year in that park after playing for 84 years in [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|\"Old\" Yankee Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Yankees open new stadium with blowout loss to Indians|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=290416110|work=[[ESPN.com]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=August 16, 2009|accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref> They won the [[American League East]] with an eight-game lead over [[Yankees \u2013 Red Sox rivalry|their rivals]], the [[2009 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]], compiling a record of 103\u201359.<ref name=\"2009Yankees\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/NYY/2009.shtml|title=2009 New York Yankees Batting, Pitching, & Fielding Statistics|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100104091513/http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/NYY/2009.shtml| archivedate=January 4, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Sabathia won 19 games and position players [[Alex Rodriguez]] and Teixeira both had strong seasons offensively, Rodriguez with 30 home runs and 100 RBI and Teixeira with 39 and 122 respectively.<ref name=\"2009Yankees\"/> [[Closer (baseball)|Closing pitcher]] [[Mariano Rivera]] earned his 500th [[save (baseball)|save]] against the Yankees' [[Mets\u2013Yankees rivalry|cross-town rival]] [[2009 New York Mets season|New York Mets]], becoming the second pitcher in history to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090627&content_id=5566046|title=Rivera takes place in history with No. 500|date=June 29, 2009|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> On September 11, 2009, [[shortstop]] [[Derek Jeter]] recorded his 2,722nd career hit, passing Lou Gehrig to become the all-time leader in career hits recorded as a Yankee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090911&content_id=6909874|title=Jeter passes Gehrig with 2,722nd hit|date=September 11, 2009|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees defeated the [[2009 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]] in three games in the [[2009 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] and the [[2009 Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim season|Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]] in six games in the [[2009 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]] (ALCS)<ref name=\"2009Yankees\"/> to win their first [[List of American League pennant winners|American League pennant]] since 2003.<ref name=\"Repeat\"/> Sabathia was named [[League Championship Series Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] of the ALCS with two wins in the series.<ref name=\"2009ALCS\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2009_ALCS.shtml|title=2009 League Championship Series \u2013 NYY vs. LAA|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref> The Yankees' victory in the ALCS earned them their 40th World Series appearance in franchise history, and their first since losing to the [[2003 Florida Marlins season|Florida Marlins]] in {{wsy|2003}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/NYY/|title=New York Yankees Team History & Encyclopedia|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Series preview===\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center\n|width=25%\n|align=right\n|quote=How great would that be? A World Series here, us against the Yankees? We've proved we can put on a pretty good show.\n|source=[[Jimmy Rollins]], discussing the potential of a Yankees\u2013Phillies World Series on May 24, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lisa-olson.fanhouse.com/2009/05/24/yankees-phillies-deliver-october-feel/ |title=Yankees, Phillies Deliver October Feel |last=Olson |first=Lisa |publisher=[[AOL Sports]] |date=May 24, 2009|accessdate=October 25, 2009}}</ref>\n}}\nThe two teams played a three-game [[Interleague play|interleague]] series at Yankee Stadium in May 2009, with the Phillies winning two of the three games.<ref name=\"interleague\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091027&content_id=7561434&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phillies-Yankees Interleague recap|first=Jenifer|last=Langosch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 27, 2009|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref> The series included two [[Save (baseball)|blown saves]] by Phillies' [[Closing pitcher|closer]] [[Brad Lidge]] in games 2 and 3, although the Phillies came back to win the final game in [[extra innings]].<ref name=\"interleague\"/>\n\nThe Yankees had [[Home advantage|home field advantage]] for the Series as the American League had won [[2009 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|that year's All-Star Game]].<ref name=\"allstar\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090715&content_id=5881270&vkey=allstar2009&fext=.jsp|title=AL retains World Series advantage|first=Anthony|last=Castrovince|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=July 15, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119084524/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090715&content_id=5881270&vkey=allstar2009&fext=.jsp| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> The team match-up was heavily discussed and analyzed in the media, per the east coast bias, prior to the beginning of the series. Both teams' offensive lineups were heavily touted,<ref name=\"verduccisi\"/><ref name=\"packpunch\">{{cite news |title=World Series packs punch at plate |author=Nightengale, Bob |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=October 27, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"TSNpreview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=296306 |title=2009 World Series Preview \u2013 Philadelphia vs. New York |date=October 27, 2009 |publisher=The Sports Network |accessdate=January 20, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091108041238/http://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=296306 |archive-date=November 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"offense\">{{cite news |title=The rest is hit story; Offence, offence and more offence mark these World Series contenders |last=Lott|first=John |newspaper=[[National Post]] |date=October 27, 2009}}</ref> with the Yankees and Phillies leading their respective leagues in [[Run (baseball)|runs scored]] per game.<ref name=\"mlboffense\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2009.shtml|title=2009 Major League Baseball Team Statistics and Standings|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> Yankees [[third base]]man Alex Rodriguez drew particular focus in the media for his success in earlier rounds of the 2009 playoffs in contrast to past postseason performances.<ref name=\"masslive\">{{cite web |url=http://www.masslive.com/sports/index.ssf/2009/10/post_127.html |title=Yankees slugger Alex Rodriguez deserves cheers for postseason performance |last=Chimelis|first=Ron |date=October 21, 2009|work=MassLive.com |publisher=[[The Republican (Springfield)|The Republican]] |accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"starledger\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2009/10/politi.html |title=As NY Yankees' Alex Rodriguez has postseason for the ages, it's best to appreciate, not ask why |last=Politi|first=Steve |date=October 21, 2009|work=NJ.com |publisher=[[The Star-Ledger]] |accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"dayrod\">\n{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091020&content_id=7508478 |title=Night-and-Day Rod: '09 Alex at his best |author=DiComo, Anthony |date=October 21, 2009|work=MLB.com |publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> The two lineups featured twenty former [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Stars]] and three former MVP award winners.<ref name=\"packpunch\"/> Only one regular starter between both teams, Phillies [[catcher]] [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]], did not have at least ten [[home run]]s during the 2009 regular season.<ref name=\"packpunch\"/> The two teams combined for 468 home runs during the season, more than any pair of opponents in World Series history.<ref name=\"packpunch\"/>\n\nThe pitching staffs were also the subject of significant discussion prior to the series.<ref name=\"TSNpreview\"/> The starting pitchers for Game&nbsp;1, CC Sabathia and Cliff Lee, were regarded as aces<ref name=\"offense\"/> who dominated the 2009 postseason with a 0.96 [[earned run average]] (ERA) between them.<ref name=\"clunkers\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/27/sports/baseball/27kepner.html |title=Baseball Hopes to Break a Streak of Clunker Series |last=Kepner|first=Tyler |date=October 26, 2009 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref> This matchup was of particular note, as Sabathia and Lee were former teammates from the Cleveland Indians and each had won a [[Cy Young Award]] with that franchise.<ref name=\"clunkers\"/><ref name=\"joepos\">{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/joe_posnanski/10/28/lee.sabathia/index.html |title=World Series lament for Indians fans: What might have been |last=Posnanski|first=Joe |date=October 28, 2009|work=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100104110958/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/joe_posnanski/10/28/lee.sabathia/index.html| archivedate=January 4, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/columnist/lopresti/2009-10-29-former-indians-pitchers-lopo_N.htm |title=Spurned Cleveland watches former Indians with a sigh |author=Lopresti, Mike |date=October 29, 2009|newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref> Yankees [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Joe Girardi]] had been using a three-man [[starting rotation]] during the playoffs, in contrast to the four-pitcher rotation used by the Phillies.<ref name=\"3man\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4611766 |title=Girardi may go with three-man rotation |date=October 29, 2009|author=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"usatight\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/playoffs/2009-10-27-world-series-breakdown_N.htm |title=Yankees and Phillies on track for a tight Series |date=October 28, 2009|author=Ortiz, Jorge |author2=Shandler, Ron|newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref> This difference led ''[[USA Today]]'' to give the Phillies' starting rotation the \"edge\" in the series, as the World Series had one fewer day off than previous rounds of the playoffs, making the series less conducive to using a three-man rotation.<ref name=\"usatight\"/> [[Gene Wojciechowski]] of [[ESPN]] criticized Girardi's strategy, arguing that [[Chad Gaudin]] should have pitched in Game&nbsp;5 or 6, instead of A. J. Burnett or [[Andy Pettitte]] on reduced, three days' rest.<ref name=\"woj3man\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/columns/story?columnist=wojciechowski_gene&id=4612984&sportCat=mlb |title=Girardi needs to give it a rest |date=October 31, 2009|first=Gene|last=Wojciechowski|authorlink=Gene Wojciechowski|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> Wojciechowski argued that while Sabathia had proven his ability to pitch on shorter rest, Burnett and Pettitte should have been given their regular time between starts.<ref name=\"woj3man\"/> Burnett had drawn some criticism, as he performed poorly in his last appearance before the World Series,<ref name=\"clunkers\"/> a start in Game&nbsp;5 of the ALCS in which he allowed six runs over six innings.<ref name=\"ALCSg5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ANA/ANA200910220.shtml|title=October 22, 2009 American League Championship Series (ALCS) Game&nbsp;5, Yankees at Angels|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> However, Burnett had previously been successful on short rest, going 4\u20130 with a 2.33 ERA in four career starts on short rest before this game. Some believed Girardi settled on a three-man rotation because he had limited options for a fourth starting pitcher, either Gaudin or [[Joba Chamberlain]], who had been inconsistent as starters in the regular season and had been shifted into the bullpen for the postseason.<ref name=\"woj3man\"/><ref name=\"batsblog\">{{cite news|url=http://bats.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/27/yankees-may-use-a-three-man-rotation/|title=Yankees May Use a Three-Man Rotation | last=Kepner | first=Tyler |date=October 27, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 26, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100327234601/http://bats.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/27/yankees-may-use-a-three-man-rotation/| archivedate= March 27, 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/14/sports/baseball/14yankees.html|title=Barring Rain, Yanks Consider 3-Man Rotation | last=Kepner | first=Tyler |date=October 13, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe matchup of closers, Mariano Rivera and Brad Lidge, also drew attention. Rivera and Lidge were the only closers who had not blown a save during the 2009 postseason, whereas closers on other postseason teams blew 11 saves in the 24 postseason games before the World Series in 2009.<ref name=\"closerpreview\">{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091027&content_id=7558018&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Closer matchup reflects playoff perfection |author=Langosch, Jenifer |date=October 27, 2009|work=MLB.com |publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |accessdate=March 17, 2010}}</ref> Both had performed well during the postseason, but Lidge had posted a 7.21 ERA during the 2009 regular season, in contrast to Rivera's 1.76.<ref name=\"closerpreview\"/><ref name=\"mobref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/riverma01.shtml|title=Mariano Rivera Statistics and History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 17, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100208150022/http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/riverma01.shtml| archivedate=February 8, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Lidge's 2009 numbers were in stark contrast to the previous season (41 out of 41 save opportunities, a 1.95 ERA, and 92 strikeouts in 62 games). As a result, ''USA Today'' gave the Yankees the edge, noting that Lidge had blown two saves against the Yankees during their regular season series earlier that year.<ref name=\"usatight\"/>\n\n==Background==\nThe Series started on October 28, 2009, which was the latest start in World Series history, beating the previous record held by the 2001 World Series (October 27).<ref>{{cite news |first=Bob|last=Dutton|title=World Series Buzz: Martinez ruminates on New York|work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=October 29, 2009}}</ref> Game&nbsp;4 was played on Sunday, November 1 and the series-winning Game&nbsp;6 took place on November 4. The Series was only the third to end in a month other than October. The first came in {{wsy|1918}}, which was played entirely in September after the regular season was cut short due to World War I.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/postseason/mlb_ws_recaps.jsp?feature=1918|title=World Series History|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref> The other such series was in {{wsy|2001}} when the [[September 11 attacks]] caused a delay in the baseball season that eventually forced the end of the World Series into November.<ref>{{cite video|title=Nine Innings from Ground Zero|people=Shapiro, Ouisie (writer)|medium=DVD}}</ref>\n\nEarlier in the season [[Commissioner of Baseball (MLB)|Commissioner]] [[Bud Selig]] expressed interest in scheduling a World Series game during daylight hours instead of the evening.<ref>{{cite news|title=World Series could get earlier starting times|url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/30111531/|work=[[NBC Sports]]|agency=''[[Sporting News]]''|date=April 8, 2009|accessdate=March 20, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115021237/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/30111531|archive-date=January 15, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The starting times were ultimately moved before 8&nbsp;p.m. ET for the first time in 30 years, but no day games were played.<ref>{{cite web |title= WS games to start 40 minutes earlier|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4174213|author=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=May 18, 2009|accessdate=May 18, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090520134209/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4174213| archivedate=May 20, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Larry|last=Fine|title=Selig mulls World Series changes, not to home comforts|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/12/03/us-baseball-selig-idUSTRE4B18VG20081203|work=[[Reuters]]|date=December 2, 2008|accessdate=December 3, 2008}}</ref> The [[Philadelphia Eagles]] and [[New York Giants]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) played across the street from Citizens Bank Park at [[Lincoln Financial Field]] on the day of Game&nbsp;4. The NFL moved that game's kickoff time to 1&nbsp;p.m. to avoid it ending too close to the start of Game&nbsp;4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/blogs/sports/watchdog-1.812020/giants-jets-play-at-same-time-11-1-1.1520052|title=Giants, Jets play at same time 11/1|first=Neil|last=Best|work=[[Newsday]]|date=October 13, 2009|accessdate=October 13, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091015110950/http://www.newsday.com/blogs/sports/watchdog-1.812020/giants-jets-play-at-same-time-11-1-1.1520052| archivedate=October 15, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Similarly, Game&nbsp;5 was played at Citizens Bank Park on the same day as the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] hosted the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) at the [[Wells Fargo Center (Philadelphia)|Wachovia Center]]. The opening faceoff of the hockey game was scheduled for 7&nbsp;p.m. but the NHL moved it to 5&nbsp;p.m. to avoid conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=502389|title=Flyers Change Start Time of November 2nd Game|date=October 16, 2009|accessdate=October 29, 2009|publisher=philadelphiaflyers.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091021142810/http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=502389| archivedate=October 21, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Umpire (baseball)|umpires]] for the series were [[Joe West (umpire)|Joe West]], [[Dana DeMuth]], [[Gerry Davis (umpire)|Gerry Davis]], [[Brian Gorman]], [[Jeff Nelson (umpire)|Jeff Nelson]], and [[Mike Everitt (baseball)|Mike Everitt]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the World Series umpiring crew|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4600610|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=October 27, 2009|accessdate=November 17, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091031194903/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4600610| archivedate=October 31, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> The World Series crew had included at least 1 umpire who had never worked the World Series in 24 of the past 25 series; however, following several mistakes by umpires in earlier rounds of the playoffs, this crew did not.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091022&content_id=7527964&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=MLB may use veteran umps in Fall Classic: Change would break longstanding baseball tradition |first=Adam |last=McCalvy|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 22, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091022&content_id=7524222&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Umpire's call on Damon draws attention: Yankee looked safe at first base on third-inning groundout |first=Anthony |last=Castrovince |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 23, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"wojreplay\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/columns/story?columnist=wojciechowski_gene&id=4598071&sportCat=mlb |title=Instant replay for the World Series? Yes|first=Gene|last=Wojciechowski|authorlink=Gene Wojciechowski|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |date=October 27, 2009|accessdate=November 17, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091030130026/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/columns/story?columnist=wojciechowski_gene&id=4598071&sportCat=mlb| archivedate=October 30, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe Phillies had won the [[2008 World Series|previous season's World Series]] against the [[2008 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]] for the franchise's second championship. The Yankees had lost their previous World Series appearance to the [[2003 Florida Marlins season|Florida Marlins]] in {{wsy|2003}} and had not won since {{wsy|2000}} against the [[2000 New York Mets season|New York Mets]]. This was the fifth Series played between teams from New York and Philadelphia, and was the first Yankees\u2013Phillies matchup since {{wsy|1950}}.<ref name=\"1950WS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1950_WS.shtml|title=1950 World Series \u2013 NYY vs. PHI|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref> The series also was the fourth consecutive time that the Phillies would have faced a team from the current AL East in the World Series, while the Yankees had faced a NL East opponent in four of their five most recent World Series appearances.<ref name=\"wshistory\"/>\n\nThis Series had two unofficial nicknames: \"Turnpike Series\", for the [[New Jersey Turnpike]], which connects New York to Philadelphia through the state of New Jersey,<ref name=\"verduccisi\">{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/tom_verducci/10/27/five.cuts/index.html |title=How can the Phillies beat the Yankees in the 2009 World Series? |first=Tom|last=Verducci|authorlink=Tom Verducci|date=October 28, 2009|work=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100205111403/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/tom_verducci/10/27/five.cuts/index.html| archivedate=February 5, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> and \"Liberty Series\", based on the [[Liberty Bell]] in Philadelphia and the [[Statue of Liberty]] in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091026&content_id=7549598&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title= Liberty Series: Statue, Bell Set for Clash |accessdate=October 26, 2009|last=Newman|first=Mark|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 26, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091027192133/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091026&content_id=7549598&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=October 27, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Summary==\n{{MLB Playoff Summary\n| summary =\n| winner = New York\n| leader =\n| score = 4\u20132\n| date1 = October 28\n| score1 = '''Philadelphia Phillies''' \u2013 6, New York Yankees \u2013 1\n| loc1 = [[Yankee Stadium]]\n| time1 = 3:27\n| att1 = 50,207\n| ref1 = <ref name=\"Game1\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_10/day_28/gid_2009_10_28_phimlb_nyamlb_1/boxscore_col.html|title=Philadelphia vs. NY Yankees \u2013 October 28, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date2 = October 29\n| score2 = Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 1, '''New York Yankees''' \u2212 3\n| loc2 = Yankee Stadium\n| time2 = 3:25\n| att2 = 50,181\n| ref2 = <ref name=\"Game2\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_10/day_29/gid_2009_10_29_phimlb_nyamlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=Philadelphia vs. NY Yankees \u2013 October 29, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date3 = October 31\n| score3 = '''New York Yankees''' \u2013 8, Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 5\n| loc3 = [[Citizens Bank Park]]\n| time3 = 3:25\n| att3 = 46,061\n| ref3 = <ref name=\"Game3\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_10/day_31/gid_2009_10_31_nyamlb_phimlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=NY Yankees vs. Philadelphia \u2013 October 31, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 31, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date4 = November 1\n| score4 = '''New York Yankees''' \u2013 7, Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 4\n| loc4 = Citizens Bank Park\n| time4 = 3:25\n| att4 = 46,145\n| ref4 = <ref name=\"Game4\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_11/day_01/gid_2009_11_01_nyamlb_phimlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=NY Yankees vs. Philadelphia \u2013 November 1, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=November 1, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date5 = November 2\n| score5 = New York Yankees \u2013 6, '''Philadelphia Phillies''' \u2013 8\n| loc5 = Citizens Bank Park\n| time5 = 3:26\n| att5 = 46,178\n| ref5 = <ref name=\"Game5\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_11/day_02/gid_2009_11_02_nyamlb_phimlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=NY Yankees vs. Philadelphia \u2013 November 2, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date6 = November 4\n| score6 = Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 3, '''New York Yankees''' \u2013 7\n| loc6 = Yankee Stadium\n| time6 = 3:52\n| att6 = 50,315\n| ref6 = <ref name=\"Game6\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_11/day_04/gid_2009_11_04_phimlb_nyamlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=Philadelphia vs. NY Yankees \u2013 November 4, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Matchups==\n\n===Game 1===\n[[File:Cliff Lee, philly.jpg|175px|thumb|right|alt=A man in a gray baseball uniform with red sleeves and cap throws a baseball with his left arm.|Phillies starting pitcher Cliff Lee, pictured in the 2009 regular season, became the first pitcher to ever throw a postseason series opener complete game against the Yankees without allowing an earned run.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Wednesday, October 28, 2009\n|Time=7:57{{nbsp}}pm ([[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]])\n|Location=[[Yankee Stadium]] in [[The Bronx|Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|Road='''Philadelphia'''|RoadAbr=PHI\n|R1=0|R2=0|R3=1|R4=0|R5=0|R6=1|R7=0|R8=2|R9=2|RR=6|RH=9|RE=1\n|Home=New York|HomeAbr=NYY\n|H1=0|H2=0|H3=0|H4=0|H5=0|H6=0|H7=0|H8=0|H9=1|HR=1|HH=6|HE=0\n|WP=[[Cliff Lee]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[CC Sabathia]] (0\u20131)|SV=\n|RoadHR=[[Chase Utley]] 2 (2)|HomeHR=\n}}\n[[File:2009 World Series Game 1 Ceremonial first pitch.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A man in a green military uniform prepares to throw a ball, while two women and a man on the left wearing red jackets with \"World Series\" on the chest look on.|Ceremonial first pitch of the World Series with Michelle Obama, Jill Biden, and Yogi Berra watching]]\n[[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]] and [[Wife of the Vice President of the United States|Second Lady]] [[Jill Biden]] escorted former Yankees catcher and [[World War II]] veteran [[Yogi Berra]] to the mound, where the [[ceremonial first pitch]] was thrown by a veteran of the [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091027&content_id=7558082&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=First lady, Dr. Biden on hand for Game 1 |accessdate=November 11, 2009|last=Newman|first=Mark|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091031070612/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091027&content_id=7558082&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=October 31, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> The Phillies' Ryan Howard got the first hit of the 2009 World Series by doubling in the first inning.<ref name=\"game1bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200910280.shtml|title=October 28, 2009 World Series Game 1, Phillies at Yankees|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref> Howard was stranded in the first and the game was scoreless after two innings.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> The Phillies scored first with a two-out [[home run]] by Chase Utley in the top of the third inning.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> Through the first five innings, Philadelphia starting pitcher Cliff Lee allowed no runs and three hits, striking out seven Yankees batters.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> In the top of the sixth, Utley hit another home run to give the Phillies a 2\u20130 lead.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> The starting pitchers Lee and CC Sabathia continued to pitch until the top of the eighth when Sabathia was replaced by [[Phil Hughes]].<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> Hughes walked the first two batters and was replaced by [[D\u00e1maso Marte]].<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> Marte got two quick outs and was relieved by [[David Robertson (baseball)|David Robertson]], who walked [[Jayson Werth]] and gave up a two-run single to Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> The Phillies added two more runs in the ninth with an RBI single by [[Shane Victorino]] and an RBI double by Howard.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> Lee finished with a complete game allowing one unearned run on six hits and striking out ten batters, not walking any of the hitters he faced.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/>\n\nLee's pitching performance made history in several ways:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4604436 |title=Lee takes over Yankee Stadium |first=Jayson |last=Stark|authorlink=Jayson Stark|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=October 29, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091101152743/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4604436| archivedate=November 1, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n* This was the fourth postseason start of Lee's career. In all four starts, he went at least seven innings and gave up no more than one earned run. The only other starting pitcher ever to begin his postseason career with four such starts was [[Christy Mathewson]].\n* He was also the first left-handed starter to beat the Yankees in The Bronx to open a World Series since [[Sandy Koufax]] in {{wsy|1963}}.\n* He was the first starting pitcher to throw a complete game without giving up an earned run against the Yankees in Game&nbsp;1 of a postseason series.\n* Lee was the first pitcher ever to strike out at least ten, walk no one, and give up no earned runs in a World Series start.\n\n===Game 2===\n[[File:Mariano Rivera allison 7 29 07.jpg|thumb|225px|Yankees closer Mariano Rivera, pictured during the 2007 regular season, pitched two scoreless innings in Game 2 for the save.|alt=A man in a gray baseball uniform and navy blue cap stands on a dirt mound. He is striding forward with his left leg as he clutches a baseball behind his head with his right hand and curls his left hand, wearing a baseball glove, under his outstretched arm. His uniform reads \"New York\" in navy blue letters across the chest. His face is contorted in concentration.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Thursday, October 29, 2009\n|Time=7:57{{nbsp}}pm (EDT)\n|Location=Yankee Stadium in Bronx, New York\n|Road=Philadelphia|RoadAbr=PHI\n|R1=0|R2=1|R3=0|R4=0|R5=0|R6=0|R7=0|R8=0|R9=0|RR=1|RH=6|RE=0\n|Home='''New York'''|HomeAbr=NYY\n|H1=0|H2=0|H3=0|H4=1|H5=0|H6=1|H7=1|H8=0|H9=X|HR=3|HH=8|HE=0\n|WP=[[A. J. Burnett]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]] (0\u20131)|SV= [[Mariano Rivera]] (1)\n|RoadHR=|HomeHR= [[Mark Teixeira]] (1), [[Hideki Matsui]] (1)\n|}}\n\nPrior to the game, [[Jay-Z]] and [[Alicia Keys]] performed the song \"[[Empire State of Mind]]\" for the Yankee Stadium crowd.<ref name=\"jayzkeys\">{{cite web| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1625161/20091029/keys_alicia.jhtml|title=Jay-Z And Alicia Keys Pump Up World Series Crowd In NYC|first=Jayson|last=Rodriguez|publisher=[[MTV]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009|date=October 29, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102065545/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1625161/20091029/keys_alicia.jhtml| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> This game marked the first postseason appearance of [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]] against the Yankees since the [[2004 American League Championship Series]], when he was with the [[2004 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]] and a part of the two teams' [[Yankees \u2013 Red Sox rivalry|long standing rivalry]]; it was also the second-ever World Series start that Mart\u00ednez made.<ref name=\"pedrobref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/martipe02.shtml|title=Pedro Mart\u00ednez Statistics and History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=October 30, 2009}}</ref> There was much media interest in Mart\u00ednez's \"return to Yankee Stadium\" for Game 2, as he told reporters at a pre-game press conference \"When you have 60,000 people chanting your name, waiting for you to throw the ball, you have to consider yourself someone special, someone that really has a purpose out there.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Silverman|first=Mike |url=http://news.bostonherald.com/sports/baseball/other_mlb/view.bg?articleid=1208123&srvc=sports&position=0|title='Influential' Pedro Martinez holds court|work=Boston Herald|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Phillies scored first for the second game in a row, with Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez hitting a [[ground rule double]] and then scoring on a [[Matt Stairs]] RBI single off [[A. J. Burnett]] in the second inning.<ref name=\"game2bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200910290.shtml|title=October 29, 2009 World Series Game 2, Phillies at Yankees|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=October 30, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102110038/http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200910290.shtml| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nMark Teixeira tied the game with a home run in the fourth inning, and [[Hideki Matsui]] broke the tie in the sixth with another homer.<ref name=\"game2bref\"/> Mart\u00ednez departed the game after giving up consecutive hits to [[Jerry Hairston Jr.]] and [[Melky Cabrera]] to start the seventh inning, and reliever Chan Ho Park gave up an RBI single to [[Jorge Posada]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Bryan|last=Hoch|title=Yanks take Classic duel to pull even|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091029&content_id=7572446&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=October 30, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102045339/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091029&content_id=7572446&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> With Cabrera at second base and Posada at first, [[Johnny Damon]] hit a low line drive at Phillies first baseman Ryan Howard. Howard grabbed the ball and threw to second where Posada was tagged and called out while standing on the base. First-base umpire [[Brian Gorman]] ruled that Howard had caught the ball in the air; thus, the result was an inning-ending double play. Both Posada and Joe Girardi vehemently protested the call, claiming that the batted ball had hit the ground before being caught; however, the umpires did not reverse the call. ESPN reported that Gorman blew the call.<ref>{{cite web |title=Game 2 calls draw more scrutiny|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4607883|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=December 8, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102180815/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4607883| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> This was the first of two calls made by Gorman in Game Two that were heavily criticized.<ref>{{cite news |title=Time for video replay in baseball before something really sorry happens... again |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/marinersblog/2010169691_time_for_video_replay_in_baseb.html|date=October 30, 2009|newspaper=[[Seattle Times]]|first=Geoff|last=Baker|accessdate=December 8, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104083300/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/marinersblog/2010169691_time_for_video_replay_in_baseb.html| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The time has come for MLB to implement instant replay |url=http://www.nesn.com/2009/10/the-time-has-come-for-mlb-to-implement-instant-replay.html|date=October 31, 2009|publisher=[[New England Sports Network]]|first=David|last=Heck|accessdate=December 8, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091205005355/http://www.nesn.com/2009/10/the-time-has-come-for-mlb-to-implement-instant-replay.html| archivedate=December 5, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"closecallsgame2\">{{cite news |first=David|last=Waldstein|title=In World Series, Umpires Find Themselves Back in Center of Dispute|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/30/sports/baseball/30umps.html?_r=1|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBurnett left the game after seven innings, having given up one run. He was replaced by Mariano Rivera in the eighth inning.<ref name=\"game2bref\"/> With one out in the eighth, the Phillies put two runners on with a walk to [[Jimmy Rollins]] and a single by Shane Victorino.<ref name=\"game2bref\"/> However, Chase Utley grounded into an inning-ending double play<ref name=\"game2bref\"/> ending on a close play at first base. The play was the second disputed call made by umpire Brian Gorman in Game Two. Gorman himself later admitted he missed this call, saying, \"on a freeze frame, it looks like there's a little bit of a ball outside [Teixeira's] glove when [Utley] hits the bag.\"<ref name=\"closecallsgame2\"/> Ultimately, Rivera threw 39 pitches and got six outs for his 38th postseason save, his tenth in World Series play.<ref>{{cite news |first=Erik|last=Boland|title=Rivera gets six-out save as Yankees win Game 2, 3\u20131|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/rivera-gets-six-out-save-as-yankees-win-game-2-3-1-1.1557551|newspaper=[[Newsday]]|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=October 30, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102093726/http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/rivera-gets-six-out-save-as-yankees-win-game-2-3-1-1.1557551| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= dead}}</ref> \n{{Clear}} Burnett earned the win in Game Two.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2009/10/ny_yankees_beat_philadelphia_p.html|title=NY Yankees beat Philadelphia Phillies, 3-1, in Game 2 of World Series|work=NJ.com|last=Carig|first=Marc|date=October 29, 2009|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Game 3===\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Saturday, October 31, 2009\n|Time=9:17{{nbsp}}pm (EDT)\n|Location=[[Citizens Bank Park]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n|Road='''New York'''|RoadAbr=NYY\n|R1=0|R2=0|R3=0|R4=2|R5=3|R6=1|R7=1|R8=1|R9=0|RR=8|RH=8|RE=1\n|Home=Philadelphia|HomeAbr=PHI\n|H1=0|H2=3|H3=0|H4=0|H5=0|H6=1|H7=0|H8=0|H9=1|HR=5|HH=6|HE=0\n|WP=[[Andy Pettitte]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[Cole Hamels]] (0\u20131)\n|RoadHR=[[Alex Rodriguez]] (1), [[Nick Swisher]] (1), [[Hideki Matsui]] (2) |HomeHR=[[Jayson Werth]] 2 (2), [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]] (1)\n|}}\nThe start of the game was postponed 80 minutes due to a rain delay, pushing the start time to 9:17&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/11/01/us-baseball-series-rain-idUSTRE5A000I20091101|title=World Series gets underway after rain delay|date=October 31, 2009|accessdate=December 20, 2012|work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> The cast of the television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' (with [[Amber Riley]] singing lead) performed the [[national anthem]] as part of a ceremony featuring a large American flag and several members of the armed services.<ref name=\"glee\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091031&content_id=7586030&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=MLB Stands Up to Cancer in Game 3|accessdate=March 16, 2010|last=Newman|first=Mark|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"flaggame3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.512aw.afrc.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123176480|title=Reservist takes part in opening ceremony of Game 3 of World Series|accessdate=March 16, 2010|last=Losurdo|first=Marnee|work=[[512th Airlift Wing]]|publisher=[[United States Air Force]]|date=November 6, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722180557/http://www.512aw.afrc.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123176480|archivedate=July 22, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Phillies scored first with Jayson Werth's lead-off home run, which was followed by a bases-loaded walk and a [[sacrifice fly]] to make the score 3\u20130 in the bottom of the second inning.<ref name=\"game3bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200910310.shtml|title=October 31, 2009 World Series Game 3, Yankees at Phillies|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091108163317/http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200910310.shtml| archivedate=November 8, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Following Mark Teixeira's walk in the top of the fourth inning, Alex Rodriguez hit a deep ball down the right field line. It was originally ruled a double so Teixeira held at third base. The play was reviewed using [[MLB instant replay]], which revealed that the ball had struck a camera sticking over the top of the wall, so the ball was ruled a two-run home run,<ref name=\"cameramove\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594160&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Camera moved after A-Rod homer|accessdate=November 1, 2009|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104234934/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594160&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> giving Rodriguez his first World Series hit.<ref name=\"arodbref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/rodrial01.shtml|title=Alex Rodriguez Statistics and History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> This was the first home run reviewed by instant replay in postseason play.<ref name=\"cameramove\"/> Specifically, the ball hit a camera owned by [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and MLB which extended slightly over the right field wall.<ref name=\"cameramove\"/> The camera was moved back for Game&nbsp;4 such that its lens was in line with the wall.<ref name=\"cameramove\"/> Coincidentally, Alex Rodriguez also had the first regular season home run reviewed by replay.<ref name=\"arod08replay\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080903&content_id=3412816&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title= Instant replay used for first time|accessdate=November 1, 2009|last=Chastain|first=Bill|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=September 4, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091103075313/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080903&content_id=3412816&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 3, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nick Swisher]] opened the top of the fifth inning with a double and scored on a single to center field by Andy Pettitte.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> This was Pettitte's first career postseason RBI and the first RBI by a Yankees pitcher in a World Series since [[Jim Bouton]] in [[1964 World Series|1964]].<ref name=\"bouton\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4613099|title=2009 World Series: New York Yankees' Pettitte knows his way around this stage |accessdate=November 2, 2009|date=October 31, 2009|first=Jayson|last=Stark|authorlink=Jayson Stark|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104235650/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4613099| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Derek Jeter followed Pettitte with another single, and both runners scored on a two-run double by Johnny Damon.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> [[Cole Hamels]] then walked Teixeira and was relieved by [[J. A. Happ|J.&nbsp;A. Happ]]. Happ closed out the fifth without allowing further scoring, but [[Nick Swisher]] added to the Yankees lead with a home run off of him in the sixth.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> Werth hit his second home run of the game leading off the bottom of the sixth to close the Yankees lead to 6\u20134,<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> becoming the second Phillies player to hit multiple home runs in this World Series.\n\n[[Chad Durbin]] relieved Happ in the top of the seventh. He walked Johnny Damon, who then [[Stolen base|stole]] second base. Rodriguez was then [[Hit by pitch|hit by a pitch]], and Damon scored on a single by Jorge Posada.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> Joba Chamberlain relieved Pettitte in the bottom of the seventh and retired the side in order. [[Brett Myers]] retired the first two batters in the top of the eighth, but Hideki Matsui then hit a home run [[Pinch hitter|pinch hitting]] for Chamberlain.<ref name=\"pinchhithr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7591284&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Lack of DH doesn't hinder Yankees|accessdate=November 1, 2009|last=Ghiroli|first=Brittnay|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221120621/http://mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7591284&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|archivedate=February 21, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Phil Hughes pitched a third of an inning in the bottom of the ninth and allowed a solo home run to [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]] before being relieved by Mariano Rivera.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> Rivera closed out the game, throwing just five pitches to record the final two outs.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> This game was Pettitte's 17th career postseason win, extending his MLB record.<ref name=\"bouton\"/>\n\n===Game 4===\n[[File:Brad Lidge phillies.jpg|thumb|right|150px|alt=A man in grey pants, a blue baseball jersey, and a red baseball cap with \"P\" on it jogs on a grass field while carrying a red article of clothing in his right hand.|Phillies closer Brad Lidge, pictured during the 2008 regular season, allowed three runs in the ninth inning of a tied Game 4 and took the loss.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Sunday, November 1, 2009\n|Time=8:20{{nbsp}}pm (EST)\n|Location=Citizens Bank Park in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|Road='''New York'''|RoadAbr=NYY\n|R1=2|R2=0|R3=0|R4=0|R5=2|R6=0|R7=0|R8=0|R9=3|RR=7|RH=9|RE=1\n|Home=Philadelphia|HomeAbr=PHI\n|H1=1|H2=0|H3=0|H4=1|H5=0|H6=0|H7=1|H8=1|H9=0|HR=4|HH=8|HE=1\n|WP=[[Joba Chamberlain]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[Brad Lidge]] (0\u20131)|SV=[[Mariano Rivera]] (2)\n|RoadHR=|HomeHR=[[Chase Utley]] (3), [[Pedro Feliz]] (1)\n|}}\n\nPrior to the start of the game, Derek Jeter and [[Albert Pujols]] were named winners of the [[Hank Aaron Award]] for their offensive performances in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7595224&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Pujols, Jeter winners of Aaron Award |accessdate=November 4, 2009|last=Bloom|first=Barry|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104234955/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7595224&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> This was the first game to test manager Joe Girardi's decision to use a three-man [[starting rotation]], as CC Sabathia started the game on three days rest, a shorter period than he normally got during the regular season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291031122&teams=new-york-yankees-vs-philadelphia-phillies |author=[[Associated Press]]|title=A-Rod starts rally, Pettitte hits RBI single as Yankees claim 2\u20131 lead over Phillies |date=October 31, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> Jeter led the game off with a single and advanced to third base on a double by Johnny Damon.<ref name=\"game4bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200911010.shtml|title=November 1, 2009 World Series Game 4, Yankees at Phillies|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref> Jeter scored via a Mark Teixeira ground out and Alex Rodriguez was [[Hit by pitch|hit by a pitch]].<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Rodriguez was hit twice the night before and the umpires issued warnings to both benches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594158&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Benches warned after A-Rod plunking|accessdate=November 2, 2009|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104234929/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594158&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Jorge Posada then added to the Yankees lead that inning with a [[sacrifice fly]].<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> The Phillies answered quickly, scoring a run on successive doubles by Shane Victorino and Chase Utley in the bottom of the first.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Sabathia [[Intentional walk|intentionally walked]] Jayson Werth, but escaped the inning without further scoring.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> The Phillies tied the game in the bottom of the fourth as Ryan Howard singled, [[Stolen base|stole]] second, and scored on a single by [[Pedro Feliz]].<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Although the run counted, [[instant replay]] of Howard's slide showed that he did not touch [[home plate]].  As Sabathia threw to second base, Mike Everitt signaled that Howard was safe due to the attempted play on Feliz.  Sabathia then pitched to Carlos Ruiz as part of an intentional walk, therefore losing the right to appeal that Howard missed home.<ref name=\"FOX4\">{{cite video|title=Major League Baseball on Fox: Game 4 of the 2009 World Series|medium=television|publisher=Fox|date=November 1, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7597644&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Howard scores without touching plate|accessdate=November 2, 2009|last=Langosch|first=Jennifer|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221120217/http://mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7597644&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|archivedate=February 21, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nNick Swisher walked to lead off the fifth inning and advanced to second on a Melky Cabrera single.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Swisher restored the Yankees' lead, scoring on a single by Jeter, and Cabrera added to it by scoring a run on a Damon single.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> [[Brett Gardner]] replaced Cabrera in center field as a [[defensive substitution]] in the bottom of the sixth inning after Cabrera left the game due to a hamstring injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291101122|title=New York Yankees vs. Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 Recap \u2013 November 10, 2009 \u2013 ESPN |accessdate=November 2, 2009|author=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091105033102/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291101122| archivedate=November 5, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Chan Ho Park relieved Phillies starter [[Joe Blanton]] in the seventh and held the Yankees scoreless in that inning.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Chase Utley hit his third [[home run]] of the series in the bottom of the seventh with two outs, bringing the game to 4\u20133. D\u00e1maso Marte relieved Sabathia and got the final out of the seventh without further scoring.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/>\n\n[[Ryan Madson]] relieved Park in the eighth and allowed a walk and a single but held the Yankees scoreless.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Joba Chamberlain replaced Marte in the bottom of the inning. He struck out the first two batters he faced but allowed a game-tying home run to Feliz before closing the inning.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/>\n\nBrad Lidge came into the game for the ninth inning, popping out Matsui and striking out Jeter before surrendering a two-out single to Damon\u2014after a nine-pitch at bat with two strikes and four foul balls.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4615712 | title=Damon steals the show|author=Stark, Jayson|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| date=November 2009}}</ref> Then, with Teixeira batting, Damon stole second and, on the same play, also stole third as the base was uncovered due to a [[Baseball positioning|defensive shift]] against Teixeira.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594166&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Johnny lately: Yanks' 9th makes it a 3\u20131 Series |accessdate=November 2, 2009|last=Hoch|first=Brian|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104234938/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594166&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Several news outlets referred to this as a \"mad dash\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=crasnick_jerry&id=4615700 |first=Jerry|last=Crasnick|authorlink=Jerry Crasnick|title=Phillies awoke nearly silent Rodriguez |date=November 1, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/news/sports/games/62368/ |first=Will|last=Leitch|title=No Holding Back This Holliday Season |date=November 28, 2009|work=NYmag.com|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |accessdate=March 29, 2010}}</ref> which Mike Vaccaro of the ''[[New York Post]]'' compared to [[Enos Slaughter]]'s [[Slaughter's Mad Dash|\"Mad Dash\"]] in the [[1946 World Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/this_fall_this_team_is_rod_DB5iolugqEFjDhEsdir6bJ/1|title=This fall, this team, is A-Rod's|last=Vaccaro|first=Mike|work=[[New York Post]]|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606173012/http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/this_fall_this_team_is_rod_DB5iolugqEFjDhEsdir6bJ/1|archivedate=June 6, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Some believed that Damon's play caused Lidge to avoid throwing his best pitch\u2014a [[Slider (baseball)|slider]] with sharp downward movement\u2014for the rest of the inning, as it risked a [[wild pitch]] that would have allowed Damon to score from third base.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/extras/extra_bases/2009/11/hes_no_idiot_af.html|title=He's no idiot after all |last=Abraham|first=Peter|work=[[Boston Globe]]|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/playoffs/2009-11-02-series-breakdown_N.htm|title=Series breakdown: Veteran Damon makes grand theft|last=White|first=Paul|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> Teixeira was then hit by a pitch and Rodriguez put the Yankees ahead with a double, scoring Damon.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Posada added to that lead with a single that scored Teixeira and Rodriguez, but was thrown out at second to end the inning.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Mariano Rivera entered in the bottom of the ninth and [[Save (baseball)|saved]] the game for the Yankees on eight pitches for his second save of the series.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/>\n\n===Game 5===\n[[File:Chase Utley on March 11, 2007.jpg|thumb|right|200px|alt=A man in white pants, a red baseball jersey with \"Phillies\" on the chest, and a red batting helmet with \"P\" on it runs on a dirt surface.|Phillies second baseman Chase Utley, pictured during spring training in 2007, tied a World Series record with five home runs in the series.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Monday, November 2, 2009\n|Time=7:57{{nbsp}}pm (EST)\n|Location=Citizens Bank Park in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|Road=New York|RoadAbr=NYY\n|R1=1|R2=0|R3=0|R4=0|R5=1|R6=0|R7=0|R8=3|R9=1|RR=6|RH=10|RE=0\n|Home='''Philadelphia'''|HomeAbr=PHI\n|H1=3|H2=0|H3=3|H4=0|H5=0|H6=0|H7=2|H8=0|H9=X|HR=8|HH=9|HE=0\n|WP=[[Cliff Lee]] (2\u20130)|LP=[[A. J. Burnett]] (1\u20131)|SV=[[Ryan Madson]] (1)\n|RoadHR=|HomeHR=[[Chase Utley]] 2 (5), [[Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez]] (1)\n|}}\nThe Yankees replaced Melky Cabrera on their postseason roster with [[Ramiro Pe\u00f1a]] due to his injury in Game&nbsp;4, while Brett Gardner took Cabrera's place in [[center fielder|center field]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091102&content_id=7602252&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Yanks' Pena spells injured Melky on roster |accessdate=November 2, 2009|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 2, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104235029/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091102&content_id=7602252&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> A. J. Burnett, the Yankees' Game&nbsp;2 starter, started Game&nbsp;5 on three days rest, one less than the Phillies' Cliff Lee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291102122&teams=new-york-yankees-vs-philadelphia-phillies |author=[[Associated Press]]|title=Utley's record-tying 5th World Series HR helps Phils cut Yanks lead to 3\u20132 |date=November 2, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> The Yankees scored first in the first inning, with Johnny Damon reaching base with a single and then scoring on a two-out double by Alex Rodriguez.<ref name=\"game5bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200911020.shtml|title=November 2, 2009 World Series Game 5, Yankees at Phillies|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies responded in the bottom of the inning with a single by Jimmy Rollins, Shane Victorino reaching after being [[Hit by pitch|hit by a pitch]], and finally a three-run [[home run]] by Chase Utley to take the lead.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> The Phillies added to their lead in the third inning with Utley and Ryan Howard drawing walks followed by [[runs batted in|RBI]] singles by Jayson Werth and Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> With no outs in the inning, Burnett was relieved by David Robertson, who allowed another run to score on a Carlos Ruiz ground out.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/>\n\nRobertson held the Phillies scoreless for a second inning in the fourth.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Jorge Posada entered as a [[pinch hitter]] in the fifth inning for [[Jos\u00e9 Molina (baseball)|Jos\u00e9 Molina]] and grounded out.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> [[Eric Hinske]] then pinch hit for Robertson and walked, advanced to third on a [[Derek Jeter]] single, and scored on a ground out by Damon.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> [[Alfredo Aceves]] entered as the new Yankee pitcher in the bottom of the fifth.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> The first batter he faced, Jayson Werth, hit a deep drive to center field but it was caught for an out by Gardner, who collided with the outfield wall to complete the play.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Aceves completed the inning without a run scoring, inducing ground outs from Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez and Ruiz.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> [[Phil Coke]] relieved Aceves in the seventh inning and allowed two Phillies players to tie World Series records.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> First, Utley tied [[Reggie Jackson]]'s record for most home runs in a World Series with a home run, his fifth of the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4618248 |title=Utley ties Jackson with 5th HR |accessdate=November 12, 2009|author=[[Associated Press]]|date=November 3, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091106235928/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4618248| archivedate=November 6, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Coke then [[Strikeout|struck out]] Howard, Howard's 12th strikeout in the series, tying [[Willie Wilson (baseball)|Willie Wilson]]'s record for most strikeouts in a World Series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/2009/11/04/2009-11-04_ryan_howard.html|title=Philadelphia Phillies hoping Ryan Howard can shake slump, pound New York Yankees |accessdate=November 5, 2009|last=Red|first=Christian|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=November 4, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091105105711/http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/2009/11/04/2009-11-04_ryan_howard.html| archivedate=November 5, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Finally, Coke was driven from the game after allowing another home run, this time to Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez, and was relieved by Phil Hughes.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/>\n\nVictorino was [[Defensive substitution|replaced defensively]] in the eighth inning by [[Ben Francisco]].<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Lee was driven from the game after allowing a single to Damon, followed by a double by Mark Teixeira, and then a double by Rodriguez that scored both runners.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Chan Ho Park relieved Lee and induced a ground out from Nick Swisher, which advanced Rodriguez to third base. Rodriguez scored on a [[sacrifice fly]] by [[Robinson Can\u00f3]].<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Ryan Madson entered in the ninth to close the game, allowing a double to Posada and a single to Hideki Matsui without recording an out.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Batting with men on first and third base, Jeter grounded into a [[double play]], allowing Posada to score but emptying the bases.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Damon singled to bring Teixeira to bat as the potential tying run, but Madson struck him out to record his first World Series [[Save (baseball)|save]].<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Members of the news media, such as [[Gene Wojciechowski]], were critical of the three-man [[starting rotation]] strategy following Game&nbsp;3,<ref name=\"woj3man\"/> and contended that Burnett's poor performance was caused by insufficient rest in between starts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/columns/story?columnist=wojciechowski_gene&id=4618452&sportCat=mlb |title=Short rest leads to Burnett's short start |date=November 3, 2009|first=Gene|last=Wojciechowski|authorlink=Gene Wojciechowski|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> However, Burnett had been successful up to this point in such situations, going 4\u20130 with a 2.33 ERA in four career starts on short rest (less than the normal four days between starts) before this game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=4614592&type=story|title=Burnett to face Lee on short rest |date=November 2, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|author=Associated Press |accessdate=July 30, 2010}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Game 6===\n[[File:Hideki Matsui in USA-7.jpg|right|upright|thumb|alt=A man in a grey baseball uniform and blue batting helmet looks to the right as he clenches a swung baseball bat behind him.|Yankees designated hitter Hideki Matsui, pictured here in the 2007 regular season, tied a World Series record for most RBIs in a single game and won the World Series MVP award.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Wednesday, November 4, 2009\n|Time=7:57{{nbsp}}pm (EST)\n|Location=Yankee Stadium in Bronx, New York\n|Road=Philadelphia|RoadAbr=PHI\n|R1=0|R2=0|R3=1|R4=0|R5=0|R6=2|R7=0|R8=0|R9=0|RR=3|RH=6|RE=0\n|Home='''New York'''|HomeAbr=NYY\n|H1=0|H2=2|H3=2|H4=0|H5=3|H6=0|H7=0|H8=0|H9=X|HR=7|HH=8|HE=0\n|WP=[[Andy Pettitte]] (2\u20130)|LP=[[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]] (0\u20132) |SV=\n|RoadHR=[[Ryan Howard]] (1)|HomeHR=[[Hideki Matsui]] (3)\n|}}\nThis game was the first Game&nbsp;6 in a World Series since the [[2003 World Series]] six years earlier, the longest such gap in the history of the World Series.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mark|last=Newman|title=Six in the City: Where will this one rank?|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091103&content_id=7615844&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=November 4, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091107091303/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091103&content_id=7615844&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 7, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> [[Mary J. Blige]], a Bronx native, performed \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Brittany|last=Ghiroli|title=New York's Blige entertains with anthem|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620350&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=November 4, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091108214141/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620350&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 8, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Andy Pettitte started on three days rest, the third straight game in which the Yankees fielded a pitcher on short rest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291104110&teams=philadelphia-phillies-vs-new-york-yankees |author=[[Associated Press]]|title=Matsui's bat drives Yankees to 27th World Series crown |date=October 31, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> The Phillies started Pedro Mart\u00ednez, who called himself and opposing pitcher [[Andy Pettitte]] \"old goats\" and acknowledged that Red Sox fans were rooting for him: \"I know that they don't like the Yankees to win, not even in Nintendo games.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fullcount.weei.com/sports/boston/baseball/red-sox/2009/11/03/pedro-i-consider-myself-a-bostonian/|title=Pedro: 'I consider myself a Bostonian'|publisher=WEEI.com|date=November 3, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees scored first with an Alex Rodriguez walk opening the bottom of the second inning followed by a two-run home run by [[designated hitter]] Hideki Matsui.<ref name=\"game6bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200911040.shtml|title=November 4, 2009 World Series Game 6, Phillies at Yankees|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies quickly responded with a [[Triple (baseball)|triple]] by Carlos Ruiz who then scored on a [[sacrifice fly]] from Jimmy Rollins in the top of the third.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Matsui answered back, adding to the Yankees lead again with a single with the [[bases loaded]] in the bottom of the third, scoring Derek Jeter and Johnny Damon.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Damon, injured running the bases while scoring, was [[Defensive substitution|replaced defensively]] in the top of the fourth by [[Jerry Hairston Jr.]]<ref name=\"game6bref\"/>\n\n[[File:New York Yankees 2009 World Series Champions.jpg|thumb|left|225px|The Yankees celebrate their 7\u20133 win and the franchise's 27th World Series championship.|alt=Many men in white baseball uniforms and blue caps, some wearing blue jackets, stand near a dirt mound. Some are hugging each other.]]\nPhillies starter Pedro Mart\u00ednez was removed after allowing four runs in four innings, relieved in the fifth by Chad Durbin.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Durbin allowed a [[ground rule double]] to Jeter, who advanced to third on a [[sacrifice bunt]] by Hairston and scored on a single by Mark Teixeira.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Durbin then hit Rodriguez with a pitch and was relieved by J.&nbsp;A. Happ after recording just one out.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Happ allowed a two-run double to Matsui, his fifth and sixth [[Runs batted in|RBI]] of the game, which tied a World Series record for most RBI in a single game set by [[Bobby Richardson]] in the [[1960 World Series]].<ref name=\"statsui\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620234&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Statsui: MVP delivers jaw-dropping numbers|first=Anthony|last=DiComo|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=January 12, 2010|date=November 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Phillies made the game closer in the top of the sixth inning, as Chase Utley drew a walk and Ryan Howard followed him with a two-run home run, bringing the score to 7\u20133.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> After Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez hit a double into right field, Joba Chamberlain relieved Andy Pettitte and closed the sixth without allowing the Phillies to score.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Chan Ho Park came in for Happ, ending any Yankees threat that inning.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Chamberlain was relieved by D\u00e1maso Marte in the top of the seventh after allowing two baserunners, but Marte struck out Utley to end the inning scoreless.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> After Park allowed a single to Rodriguez, [[Scott Eyre]] replaced him. Eyre allowed Rodriguez to steal second and [[Intentional walk|intentionally walked]] Jorge Posada but escaped the inning without allowing a run.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/>\n\nMarte recorded one out, a strikeout of Howard, in the top of the eighth inning.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> With it Howard set a new World Series record for most strikeouts by a hitter in a single series with a total of 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7616316&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Howard sets Series record for strikeouts |accessdate=November 5, 2009|last=Bowman|first=Mark|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091108104133/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7616316&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 8, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> After the out, Marte was relieved by Yankees [[Closing pitcher|closer]] Mariano Rivera in a non-[[Save (baseball)|save]] situation.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Rivera allowed a double to Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez, but no runs, in the eighth.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> After retiring the first two batters in the eighth, Eyre gave way to Ryan Madson, who allowed a single to Jeter before ending the bottom of the eighth inning.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Matt Stairs led off the ninth as a [[pinch hitter]], but lined out. Ruiz worked a walk from Rivera, but successive outs by Rollins and Victorino ended the game 7\u20133 to clinch the World Series for the Yankees.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Pettitte added to his own record for most playoff wins, bringing his career total to 18.<ref name=\"APYankswin\">{{cite web | author = [[Associated Press]] | work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| title = Matsui's bat drives Yankees to 27th World Series crown | date =November 5, 2009| url = http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291104110| accessdate =December 28, 2009}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Composite line score==\n2009 World Series '''(4\u20132)''': '''[[2009 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] (AL)''' beat [[2009 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]] (NL).\n{{Linescore\n|Road=Philadelphia Phillies\n|R1=4|R2=4|R3=5|R4=1|R5=0|R6=4|R7=3|R8=3|R9=3|RR=27|RH=44|RE=2\n|Home='''New York Yankees'''\n|H1=3|H2=2|H3=2|H4=3|H5=9|H6=2|H7=2|H8=4|H9=5|HR=32|HH=49|HE=2\n|TotalAttendance=289,087 |AveAttendance=48,181\n|WinPlayerShare=$350,029.99<ref name=\"wssharesrevised\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4960581|title=Yanks rank behind '08 Phillies|work=Associated Press|date=March 2, 2010|accessdate=November 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"wssharesrevisedtsn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2010-03-03/list-2009-world-series-shares|title=List of 2009 World Series shares|work=Associated Press|date=March 3, 2010|accessdate=November 8, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101110064433/http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2010-03-03/list-2009-world-series-shares|archivedate=November 10, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|LosePlayerShare=$265,357.50<ref name=\"wsshares\">{{cite news|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091130&content_id=7730198&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp|title=Yanks awarded record postseason shares|last=Gonzalez|first=Alden|work=MLB.com|date=November 30, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Broadcasting==\nFor the tenth consecutive year in the United States, [[Major League Baseball on Fox|Fox Sports]] televised the Series. [[Joe Buck]] called [[sports commentary|play-by-play]] and [[Tim McCarver]] provided [[Color commentator|analysis]]. The Series was also broadcast on [[Major League Baseball on ESPN Radio|ESPN Radio]], with [[Jon Miller]] and [[Joe Morgan]] calling the action. [[Fox Sports en Espa\u00f1ol]] also broadcast the Series for the US [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking audience.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/fox-sports-en-espanol-announces-exclusive-spanish-language-programming-for-the-2009-world-series-with-pre---postgame-analysis-by-chicago-white-sox-manager-ozzie-guillen-66403607.html|title=Fox Sports en Espanol Announces Exclusive Spanish-Language Programming For The 2009 World Series|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> The [[flagship station|flagship]] radio stations of the respective teams broadcast all Series games with their local announcers. In Philadelphia, [[WPHT]] carried the Phillies' English-language broadcasts, with [[Scott Franzke]], [[Larry Andersen]], [[Tom McCarthy (broadcaster)|Tom McCarthy]], [[Gary Matthews]], and [[Chris Wheeler]] announcing, while [[WDAS (AM)|WUBA]] aired the team's Spanish broadcasts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.philly.com/2009-11-04/sports/24987832_1_ryan-howard-hideki-matsui-johnny-damon|title=Phillies\u2013Yankees: World Series Game 6 preview|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=November 4, 2009|first=Marcus|last=Hayes|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> In New York, [[WCBS-AM]] carried the Yankees' English broadcasts with [[John Sterling (sportscaster)|John Sterling]] and [[Suzyn Waldman]] announcing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20091028/SPORTS/910280350/-1/rss02|title=World Series: How to follow the Yankees on TV, radio|work=[[Times Herald-Record]]|date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> This broadcast made Waldman the first woman to announce a World Series game on radio.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4604021&campaign=rss&source=MLBHeadlines | title=Yankees honor Waldman before Game 1 | author=[[Associated Press]] | work=[[ESPN.com]] | publisher = ESPN Internet Ventures |date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> [[XM Satellite Radio]] offered multiple feeds of each game to its subscribers.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://investor.sirius.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=414472|title=SIRIUS XM Radio Announces Extensive MLB Postseason Coverage|publisher=[[PR Newswire]] via xmradio.com|date=October 7, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720065449/http://investor.sirius.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=414472|archivedate=July 20, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Ratings==\nTelevision ratings for the 2009 World Series were excellent. Game 1 attracted 19.5 million viewers, second only to the opening of the [[2004 World Series]] for a series opener since 2000 and 29% higher than 2008's opening game.<ref name=\"game1ratingsa\">{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091030&content_id=7580380&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy&partnerId=rss_nyy |title=Buzz growing as Series has classic feel |work=[[MLB.com]] |publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|last=Newman |first=Mark |date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"game1tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/10/29/world-series-game-1-up-29-over-2008-second-highest-game-1-of-decade/32013 |title=World Series Game 1 up 29% over 2008; Second highest game 1 of decade|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref> Game 4 produced the highest total viewership of the series with 22.8 million viewers, the highest for any World Series game since 2004 and the highest for a \"non-decisive Game 4\" since 2001.<ref name=\"game4tratings\"/> At 11.7 overall, the 2009 World Series was at the time the highest rated World Series since 2004 and the one of the only World Series to average double digits since 2007, the other being the [[2016 World Series]].<ref>[[World Series television ratings]]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Game !! [[Nielsen ratings|Ratings]]<br/>(households) !! [[Share (television)|Share]]<br/>(households) !! American audience<br/>(in millions)\n|-\n! 1<ref name=\"game1tratings\"/>\n| 11.9 || 19 || 19.5\n|-\n! 2<ref name=\"game2tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/10/30/world-series-game-2-dominates-prime-time-audience-48-better-than-08-gm-2/32108 |title=World Series Game 2 Dominates Prime Time; Audience +48% Better than '08 Gm. 2|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 11.7 || 19 || 18.9\n|-\n! 3<ref name=\"game3tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/11/01/world-series-game-3-averages-15-4-million-viewers-after-80-minute-halloween-rain-delay/32211 |title=World Series game 3 averages 15.4 million viewers after 80 minute Halloween rain delay|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=November 1, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 9.1 || 18 || 15.4\n|-\n! 4<ref name=\"game4tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/11/02/world-series-game-four-nielsen-ratings-2009-world-series-remains-dominant-force-in-prime-time/32326 |title=World Series Game Four Nielsen Ratings: 2009 World Series Remains Dominant Force in Prime Time|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 13.5 || 22 || 22.8\n|-\n! 5<ref name=\"game5tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/11/03/world-series-game-5-delivers-another-home-run-for-fox/32563 |title=World Series Game 5 Delivers Another Home Run For FOX|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=November 3, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 10.6 || 16 || 17.1\n|-\n! 6<ref name=\"game6tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/11/05/2009-world-series-posts-biggest-year-to-year-growth-in-history/32759 |title=2009 World Series posts biggest year-to-year growth in history|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 13.4 || 22 || 22.3\n|}\n\n==Impact and aftermath==\nMany players with both teams won awards for their performances during the 2009 season. Teixeira and Jeter each won a [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]] and [[Silver Slugger Award]]; Jimmy Rollins and Shane Victorino won Gold Gloves, as well; and Chase Utley won a Silver Slugger Award.<ref name=\"09awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/awards/y2009/index.jsp|title=2009 MLB Awards|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=January 12, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119050111/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/awards/y2009/index.jsp| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Rivera was named the 2009 [[DHL Delivery Man of the Year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091014&content_id=7455952&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy|title=Mariano wins Delivery Man of Year Award|first=Anthony|last=DiComo|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 14, 2009|accessdate=January 12, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119061808/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091014&content_id=7455952&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> as well as ''[[Sporting News]]''{{'}} [[Sporting News#Pro Athlete of the Year|Pro Athlete of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2009-12-17/2009-sporting-news-pro-athlete-year-mariano-rivera-yankees-closer | title = 2009 Sporting News Pro Athlete of the Year: Mariano Rivera, Yankees closer | work = [[Sporting News]] | first = Ken | last = Bradley | date = December 17, 2009 | accessdate = December 17, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131005011451/http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2009-12-17/2009-sporting-news-pro-athlete-year-mariano-rivera-yankees-closer | archive-date = October 5, 2013 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Along with the [[Hank Aaron Award]] announced before Game&nbsp;4, Jeter won the [[Roberto Clemente Award]] and was named ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''{{'}}s [[Sportsman of the Year]] for 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091029&content_id=7573566&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Jeter takes home Clemente Award|first=Mark|last=Newman|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=January 12, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119120504/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091029&content_id=7573566&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/magazine/specials/sportsman/2009/11/25/derek.jeter/index.html |title=Sports Illustrated names Derek Jeter Sportsman of the Year |work=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=November 30, 2009 |accessdate=January 12, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104232602/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/magazine/specials/sportsman/2009/11/25/derek.jeter/index.html |archivedate=January 4, 2010 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Matsui won the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP]] for his play, becoming the first Japanese player and first full-time [[designated hitter]] to win the award.<ref name=\"statsui\"/><ref>{{cite news| author = [[Associated Press]] | title = Matsui Becomes 1st Japanese-Born World Series MVP | work=[[The New York Times]] | date =November 5, 2009 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2009/11/05/sports/AP-BBO-World-Series-MVP.html | accessdate =November 5, 2009}}</ref> Several items related to the series were sent to the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]] including bats from Jeter and Matsui; caps from Rivera, Lee, and Pettitte; and Johnny Damon's [[Cleat (shoe)|cleats]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7621018&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Cooperstown to capture Series relics|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=March 16, 2010|date=November 5, 2009|first=Tim|last=Britton}}</ref>\n\nMatsui also joined [[Minnesota Twins]] radio analyst [[Dan Gladden]] as members from the [[1994 Japan Series|1994 world championship]] [[Yomiuri Giants]] team as players who have won championships in North America and Japan.\nThis World Series title for the Yankees was their second one during the 2000s decade. Even though the Boston Red Sox had also won the World Series twice in this decade, the Yankees were the only team to have appeared in the World Series four (4) times during the 2000s. Therefore, the Yankees can be referred to as the \"Team of 2000s\". \n\n===Yankees===\n[[File:CC Sabathia Mark Teixeira World Series parade 2009.jpg|thumb|CC Sabathia and Mark Teixeira during the victory parade|alt=A black man on the left wearing a white T-shirt and dark jacket smiles holding a sign, while a white man on the right wearing a blue sweatshirt which reads \"Champions\" points upwards. White streamers hang from a building in the background.]]\n[[File:US Navy 091106-N-6525D-001 Musician 3rd Class Laura Carey sings the National Anthem at the conclusion of the New York Yankees ticker-tape parade at New York City Hall.jpg|thumb|left|Ticker-tape parade at [[New York City Hall]]|alt=A woman in an American Navy uniform stands before a microphone with several people behind her on stage. The stage is in front of a building with a sign that reads \"#27!\".]]\n[[File:2009 World Series Champions and Barack Obama.jpg|thumb|President [[Barack Obama]] meets with the 2009 World Series champion New York Yankees at the White House.|alt=Two men in dark suits stand in front of a crowd in the background and behind a podium in the foreground with the Seal of the President of the United States on it. The two men are holding a white jersey with pinstripes and the number 27 on it.]]\nThe series win brought the Yankees' franchise championship total to 27,<ref name=\"APYankswin\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/05/sports/baseball/05series.html?_r=1&ref=global|title=Back on Top, Yankees Add a 27th Title | last=Kepner | first=Tyler |date=November 5, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=November 5, 2009}}</ref> more than any other North American professional sports franchise. This championship came in the Yankees' first year in their new stadium. They had also won the [[1923 World Series]], the opening year of the previous Yankee Stadium.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/news?slug=ge-yankeesclinch110409|title=Yankees christen new stadium with a title|date=November 4, 2009|first=Gordon|last=Edes|publisher=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> The victory was noted by some sportswriters as a personal success for Alex Rodriguez, winning his first championship and succeeding in the playoffs where some had previously claimed he was a \"choker and a loser\".<ref name=\"bryantarod\">{{cite web|title=Postseason had many defining moments |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=bryant_howard&id=4628594 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |first=Howard |last=Bryant |date=November 6, 2009 |accessdate=December 28, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118154227/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=bryant_howard&id=4628594 |archivedate=November 18, 2009 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"caplearod\">{{cite web |title=A-Rod finally wins that elusive title|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=caple_jim&id=4624978|work=[[ESPN.com]]|first=Jim|last=Caple|date=November 4, 2009|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"DiComoARod\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091105&content_id=7624852&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Humbled A-Rod soaks in first championship|first=Anthony|last=DiComo|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=December 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119132950/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091105&content_id=7624852&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Prior to this series, Rodriguez had appeared in 2,166 regular season games without a World Series appearance, then the second-most among active players to [[Ken Griffey Jr.]]<ref name=\"bryantarod\"/><ref name=\"DiComoARod\"/>\n\nThe Yankees' victory was credited to a number of different sources.<ref name=\"spreadclues\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7621016&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Start spreadin' the clues: Why Yanks won|first=Jenifer|last=Langosch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref> Many players drew praise for their performances, including Series MVP Hideki Matsui;<ref name=\"statsui\"/> free agents signed the previous offseason including Mark Teixeira, CC Sabathia, and A. J. Burnett;<ref name=\"huffingtonafter\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/11/04/yankees-win-world-series_n_346445.html|title=Yankees Win World Series: New York Beats Phillies For Record 27th Championship|first=Mike|last=Fitzpatrick|work=The Huffington Post|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref> and the so-called \"[[Core Four]]\" of Derek Jeter, Mariano Rivera, Andy Pettitte, and Jorge Posada, who had all played a large role in the Yankees' past success in the 1990s.<ref name=\"sixfivefour\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620796&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Six games, five rings, four Yankees|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"timescore\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/26/sports/26anderson.html|title=Sports of the Times; From Yanks' Core To Pacquiao, Plenty of Cheers|first=Dave|last=Anderson|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 29, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"pettitefive\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620800&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Pettitte relishes fifth championship ring|first=Thomas|last=Boorstein|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119133049/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620800&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Manager Joe Girardi was also credited for his management of the team,<ref name=\"girardi\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091105&content_id=7625028&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Girardi leads Yankees to ultimate goal|first=Thomas|last=Boorstein|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119132936/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091105&content_id=7625028&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> particularly in his decision to use only three starting pitchers in the Yankees postseason [[starting rotation]].<ref name=\"3manpt2\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7621188&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|title=In the end, Girardi's pitching plan pays off|first=Jennifer|last=Langosch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119085954/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7621188&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> The Yankees were the first team to use only three starters in a World Series since the [[1998 San Diego Padres season|San Diego Padres]] in the [[1998 World Series|1998 Series]].<ref name=\"batsblog\"/>\n\nSeveral members of the Yankees franchise dedicated the World Series in part to team owner George Steinbrenner, who had recently stepped back from his once prominent position with the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7616200&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=George, this one is for you|first=Barry|last=Bloom|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 12, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119132735/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7616200&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate= January 19, 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Steinbrenner died on the day of the [[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] the following season at the age of 80.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/14/sports/baseball/14steinbrenner.html?_r=2&sq=steinbrenner&st=cse&scp=2&pagewanted=print|title=GEORGE STEINBRENNER, 1930\u20132010; A Legacy of Championships From the Man Who Hated to Lose|first=Richard|last=Goldstein|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|page=A1 | date=July 13, 2010|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> On November 6, a victory parade took place for the Yankees in the \"[[Canyon of Heroes]]\" in [[Manhattan]], New York City.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/idCATRE5A556L20091106|title=NY Yankees victory parade draws thousands of fans|date=November 6, 2009|agency=Reuters|accessdate=November 21, 2009|first=Michelle|last=Nicholls}}</ref> The Yankees sent a group of players, coach [[Tony Pe\u00f1a]], and team Senior Vice President [[Felix Lopez (businessman)|Felix Lopez]] with the Commissioner's Trophy to the [[Dominican Republic]] in early January 2010 to meet with President [[Leonel Fern\u00e1ndez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidencia.gob.do/app/article.aspx?id=11838|title=Presidente Fern\u00e1ndez recibe a ejecutivos y jugadores de los Yankees de Nueva York|language=Spanish|publisher=Presidency of the Dominican Republic|date=January 8, 2010|accessdate=January 11, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725193507/http://www.presidencia.gob.do/app/article.aspx?id=11838|archivedate=July 25, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100108&content_id=7892702&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Yanks, trophy tour Dominican Republic|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=January 7, 2010|accessdate=January 11, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100115113930/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100108&content_id=7892702&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 15, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Most of the 2009 Yankees received their [[championship rings]] on Opening Day the next season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-04-13/sports/27061526_1_rings-balfour-college-style|title=New York Yankees set for 2010 Opening Day with World Series rings in hand |accessdate=February 27, 2011|last=Bondy|first=Filip|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=April 13, 2010}}</ref> Matsui was on the Angels in 2010 and when the Angels played their first series of the season in the Bronx, the Yankees home opener, they presented him with his ring.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeter plays ring prank on Matsui|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/los-angeles/mlb/news/story?id=5083131|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 13, 2010|accessdate=February 27, 2011}}</ref> They also visited U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] in the [[White House]] in April 2010, presenting him with a signed jersey.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama hosts Yankees at White House|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/news/story?id=5137815|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 26, 2010|accessdate=February 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees returned to the playoffs the following season, as the [[Major League Baseball wild card|wild card]]. They lost to the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in the [[2010 American League Championship Series|2010 ALCS]]; which included an 8-0 shutout in Yankee Stadium by former Phillie ace Cliff Lee; it was Lee's seventh straight postseason win which included three victories against the Yankees (two as a Phillie in the 2009 World Series, and in 2010 during the ALCS).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/recap?gid=301022113&print=1|title=Rangers headed to World Series for first time|date=October 22, 2010|first=Stephen|last=Hawkins|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Phillies===\nFollowing Game&nbsp;4, after the Yankees took a 3\u20131 series lead, ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' accidentally printed a three-quarters-page [[Macy's]] advertisement congratulating the Phillies for winning the World Series, along with a picture of a Phillies championship T-shirt. The newspaper subsequently apologized for the mistake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=4616770&type=story|title = Newspaper apologizes for incorrect ad|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|author=Associated Press|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=March 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nLee Jenkins of ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' attributed Philadelphia's loss to a lack of pitching depth, noting that three different Yankees starters managed to win games in the series, while only Cliff Lee won games for the Phillies. The Phillies' 2008 postseason star pitchers, starter Cole Hamels and closer Brad Lidge, struggled in their only appearances of the 2009 World Series. The Phillies bullpen which did well in the NLCS performed poorly in the World Series, allowing seven runs in just 11 2/3 innings with a 5.40 ERA.<ref name=\"phildepth\">{{cite news|url=http://si.printthis.clickability.com/pt/cpt?action=cpt&title=Lack+of+starting+pitching+depth+doomed+Philadelphia+Phillies+-+Lee+Jenkins+-+SI.com&expire=&urlID=414147432&fb=Y&url=http%3A%2F%2Fsportsillustrated.cnn.com%2F2009%2Fwriters%2Flee_jenkins%2F11%2F05%2Fpedro.martinez%2Findex.html&partnerID=2356|title=Lack of pitching depth cost Phillies |last=Jenkins|first=Lee |date=November 5, 2009|work=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref> Jorge Arangure Jr. of ESPN partially attributed the Phillies' loss to their lack of offensive production, citing the team's .227 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] in the World Series. Only Chase Utley performed well with 5 home runs and 22 of the Phillies' 90 bases, while Shane Victorino and Jimmy Rollins struggled at the plate, and Ryan Howard struck out a record 13 times in the World Series after his NLCS MVP performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=4624839&type=story|title=Five reasons the Phillies didn't repeat|last=Arangure|first=Jorge Jr.|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBefore the start of the 2010 season, the Phillies traded away their 2009 postseason ace pitcher Cliff Lee. The Phillies posted the league's best record in 2010, and returned to the playoffs where they lost to the eventual champions the [[2010 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]] in the [[2010 National League Championship Series|NLCS]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Giants Punch Out Phillies, Looking|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/24/sports/baseball/24nlcs.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print|date=October 24, 2010|first=David|last=Waldstein|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=January 23, 2011|page=SP1}}</ref>\n\n===David Paterson ticket scandal===\nAmong those in attendance during Game&nbsp;1 was [[List of Governors of New York|New York Governor]] [[David Paterson]], whose party had five tickets behind home plate.  On March 3, 2010, the New York Commission on Public Integrity found that Paterson had violated state laws concerning gifts to public officials, and that he [[perjury|lied under oath]] to the commission about his intent to pay for the tickets.<ref name=\"WSJSaul\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703862704575099663280532160?mod=WSJ_hpp_MIDDLENexttoWhatsNewsThird|title=Paterson Faulted For Ethics Slip |last=Saul|first=Michael Howard|date=March 4, 2010|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=March 4, 2010}}</ref> The commission further found that Paterson used his position to solicit and receive the five tickets\u2014valued at US$425 each\u2014free of charge from the Yankees,<ref name=\"NYTPeters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/04/nyregion/04paterson.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print|title=Paterson's Ethics Breach Is Turned Over to Prosecutors|last=Confessore|first=Nicholas|last2=Peters|first2=Jeremy W.|date=March 3, 2010|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 4, 2010}}</ref> that he had never intended to pay for the tickets despite testimony to the contrary, and that he or a person acting on his behalf wrote a backdated check to pay for them only after scrutiny in the case arose.<ref name=\"WSJSaul\" /><ref name=\"NYTPeters\" /> The Commission ultimately fined Paterson $62,125 for his actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/20/gov-paterson-fined-62125-for-taking-world-series-tickets/|title=Governor Paterson Fined Over World Series Tickets|last=Halbfinger|first=David|date=December 20, 2010|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 2, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110112093921/http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/20/gov-paterson-fined-62125-for-taking-world-series-tickets/| archivedate=January 12, 2011<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n* [[2009 Asia Series]]\n* [[2009 Japan Series]]\n* [[2009 Korean Series]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|2009 World Series}}\n{{WSExtLinks|year=2009}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100119032943/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/ps/y2009]\n* [http://espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/matchup/_/teams/phillies-yankees 2009 World Series] at ''[http://espn.go.com/ ESPN.com]''\n* [http://mlb.mlb.com/nyy/history/championship09.jsp New York Yankees championship page]\n\n{{2009 MLB Playoffs navbox}}\n{{World Series}}\n{{2009 MLB season by team}}\n{{Major League Baseball on Fox}}\n{{Major League Baseball on ESPN Radio}}\n{{2009 New York Yankees}}\n{{New York Yankees}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2009 World Series}}\n[[Category:World Series]]\n[[Category:2009 Major League Baseball season|World Series]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies postseason]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees postseason]]\n[[Category:2009 in sports in New York City|World Series]]\n[[Category:2009 in sports in Pennsylvania|World Series]]\n[[Category:2009 in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:October 2009 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:November 2009 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox World Series Expanded\n| image = 2009 World Series logo.svg\n| country = World\n| year = 2009\n| champion = [[2009 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]&nbsp;(4)\n| champion_manager = [[Joe Girardi]]\n| champion_games = 103\u201359, {{winpct|103|59}}\n| runnerup = [[2009 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]]&nbsp;(2)\n| runnerup_manager = [[Charlie Manuel]]\n| runnerup_games = 93\u201369, {{winpct|93|69}}\n| date= October 28 \u2013 November 4\n| MVP = [[Hideki Matsui]] (Yankees)\n| television = [[Fox Major League Baseball|Fox]] ([[United States]])<br/>[[MLB International]] (International)\n| announcers = [[Joe Buck]]<!-- play-by-play --> and [[Tim McCarver]]<!-- color commentator --> ([[Fox Major League Baseball|Fox]])<br/>[[Dave O'Brien (sportscaster)|Dave O'Brien]] and [[Rick Sutcliffe]] (MLB International)\n| radio_network = [[Major League Baseball on ESPN Radio|ESPN]]<br />[[WCBS (AM)|WCBS]] (Yankees)<br/>[[WPHT]] (Phillies)\n| radio_announcers = [[Jon Miller]] and [[Joe Morgan]] (ESPN)<br />[[John Sterling (sportscaster)|John Sterling]] and [[Suzyn Waldman]] (Yankees)<br />[[Scott Franzke]], [[Tom McCarthy (broadcaster)|Tom McCarthy]], [[Chris Wheeler]], [[Larry Andersen]], and [[Gary Matthews]] (Phillies)\n| umpires = [[Gerry Davis (umpire)|Gerry Davis]] (crew chief), [[Jeff Nelson (umpire)|Jeff Nelson]], [[Brian Gorman]], [[Mike Everitt (baseball)|Mike Everitt]], [[Dana DeMuth]], [[Joe West (umpire)|Joe West]]\n| HOFers = '''Yankees:''' [[Derek Jeter]], [[Mariano Rivera]]<br />'''Phillies:''' [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]]\n| ALCS = '''[[2009 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]''' defeated [[2009 Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim season|Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]], 4\u20132\n| NLCS = '''[[2009 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]]''' defeated [[2009 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]], 4\u20131\n| image2 =\n}}\nThe '''2009 World Series''' was the [[World Series|championship series]] of [[Major League Baseball]]'s (MLB) [[2009 Major League Baseball season|2009 season]]. As the 105th<ref name=\"wshistory\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/|title=Playoff and World Series Stats and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100109123742/http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/| archivedate=January 9, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> edition of the World Series, it was a [[best-of-seven playoff]] contested between the [[2009 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]], champions of the [[National League]] (NL) and [[2008 Philadelphia Phillies season|defending World Series champions]], and the [[2009 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]], champions of the [[American League]] (AL). The Yankees defeated the Phillies, 4 games to 2, winning their 27th World Series championship. The series was played between October 28 and November 4, broadcast on [[Major League Baseball on Fox|Fox]], and watched by an average of roughly 19&nbsp;million viewers. Due to the start of the season being pushed back by the [[2009 World Baseball Classic]] in March, this was the first World Series regularly scheduled to be played into the month of November. This series was a rematch of the [[1950 World Series]].\n\n[[Home advantage|Home field advantage]] for the Series went to the AL for the eighth straight year as a result of its 4\u20133 win in the [[2009 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]]. The Phillies earned their berth into the [[2009 Major League Baseball season#Postseason|playoffs]] by winning the [[National League East]]. The Yankees won the [[American League East]] to earn their berth, posting the best record in the Major Leagues. The Phillies reached the World Series by defeating the [[2009 Colorado Rockies season|Colorado Rockies]] in the best-of-five [[2009 National League Division Series|National League Division Series]], and the [[2009 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] in the best-of-seven [[2009 National League Championship Series|NL Championship Series]] (NLCS). The Yankees defeated the [[2009 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]] in the [[2009 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] and the [[2009 Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim season|Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]] in the [[2009 American League Championship Series|AL Championship Series]] (ALCS) to advance to their first World Series since [[2003 World Series|2003]]. As a result of their loss, the Phillies became the first team since the {{wsy|2001}} Yankees to lose the World Series after winning it the previous year.\n\n[[Cliff Lee]] pitched a [[complete game]] in the Phillies' Game&nbsp;1 victory, allowing only one [[Earned run#Unearned run|unearned run]], while [[Chase Utley]] hit two home runs. In Game&nbsp;2, solo [[home run]]s by [[Mark Teixeira]] and [[Hideki Matsui]] helped the Yankees win by a score of 3\u20131. After a [[rain delay]]ed start, Game&nbsp;3 featured more offense, with a combined six home runs and thirteen total [[run (baseball)|runs]] en route to a Yankee victory. The Yankees won Game&nbsp;4 by scoring the decisive three runs in the ninth inning after an alert [[base running]] play by [[Johnny Damon]]. The Phillies avoided elimination with a win in Game&nbsp;5, aided by Utley's second two\u2013home run game of the series. The Yankees secured their World Series championship with a Game 6 victory in which Matsui hit his third home run of the series. He was named [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]] (MVP) of the series, making him the first Japanese-born player and the first full-time [[designated hitter]] to win the award. Matsui was the series' MVP despite starting only the three games that were played at Yankee Stadium, since the designated hitter position is not used in NL ballparks.\n\nSeveral records were tied, extended, or broken during this World Series, including team championships (Yankees with 27), career postseason wins ([[Andy Pettitte]] with 18), career World Series [[Save (baseball)|saves]] ([[Mariano Rivera]] with 11), home runs in a World Series (Utley with five), [[strikeout]]s by a hitter in a World Series ([[Ryan Howard]] with 13), and [[run batted in|runs batted in]] in a single World Series game (Matsui with six).\n\n==How they got there==\n\n===Philadelphia Phillies===\n{{Main|2009 Philadelphia Phillies season}}\nDuring the off-season, the Phillies promoted assistant general manager [[Rub\u00e9n Amaro Jr.]] to [[General manager (baseball)|general manager]], succeeding [[Pat Gillick]] who retired at the end of a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081103&content_id=3660782&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi&partnerId=rss_phi|title= Amaro Jr. takes over reins for Phillies|accessdate=November 3, 2008|last=Mandel|first=Ken|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 3, 2008}}</ref> Their most notable offseason player change was in [[left field]], as [[Pat Burrell]] departed due to [[Free agent|free agency]] and was replaced by free agent [[Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081216&content_id=3718927|title=Ibanez excited to join world champs|last=Gonzalez|first=Alden|date=December 16, 2008|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=March 2, 2009}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Another notable acquisition was free agent [[pitcher]] [[Chan Ho Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081215&content_id=3717580&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|first=Anthony|last=DiComo|date=December 15, 2008|accessdate=October 26, 2009|publisher=Major League Baseball|work=[[MLB.com]]|title=Park agrees to one-year deal with Phils|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212093738/http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081215&content_id=3717580&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|archivedate=February 12, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Park was originally signed as a backup option for the [[bullpen]], as [[relief pitcher|reliever]] [[J. C. Romero]] was assigned a 50-game suspension after violating the [[Major League Baseball drug policy]], but Park won the fifth [[Starting pitcher|starter]]'s job in [[Spring Training]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/story/11573963|title=Phillies release veteran outfielder Jenkins, name Park fifth starter|date=March 31, 2009|work=CBS Sports|accessdate=April 3, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3812334 |title=Suspended Romero 'didn't cheat' |date=January 9, 2009|first=Peter|last=Gammons|authorlink=Peter Gammons|accessdate=March 3, 2011|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2009, Phillies scouts evaluated pitcher [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]] in two simulated games against the [[Dominican Summer Phillies|Phillies DSL team]], leading to a one-year, $1-million contract.<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090714&content_id=5875102&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi Pedro signs one-year deal with Phillies]. Mlb.mlb.com. Retrieved on December 21, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4338734 Pedro Martinez throws first bullpen session since joining Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 ESPN]. Sports.espn.go.com (July 18, 2009). Retrieved on December 21, 2013.</ref> Replacing [[Jamie Moyer]] as a starter in the Phillies rotation on August 12, 2009, Philadelphia won each of Mart\u00ednez's first seven starts, the first time in franchise history that this had occurred with any debuting Phillies pitcher.<ref>{{cite web|author=ESPN.com |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/notebook?page=bbtn/090913|title=Baseball Tonight Clubhouse: Rockies search for wins, not respect|publisher=ESPN.com|date=September 13, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2010}}</ref> The Phillies made one large acquisition at the [[trade deadline]], trading four minor league players to the [[2009 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]] for pitcher [[Cliff Lee]] and [[outfielder]] [[Ben Francisco]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4363553 |title=Phillies get Lee from Indians |accessdate=January 6, 2010|first=Jayson|last=Stark|authorlink=Jayson Stark|date=August 1, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures}}</ref> Lee won seven of his twelve regular season starts for Philadelphia in 2009.<ref name=\"leebref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/l/leecl02.shtml|title=Cliff Lee Statistics and History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring the regular season, the Phillies led the [[National League East]] for most of the year, taking first place for good on May 30.<ref name=\"2009Phillies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/PHI/2009-schedule-scores.shtml|title=2009 Philadelphia Phillies Schedule, Box Scores and Splits|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=November 17, 2009}}</ref> Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez had started the year strongly, [[Batting average (baseball)|batting]] well over .300 with 17 [[home run]]s and 46 [[runs batted in]] (RBI) in the first two months of the season, which led the ''[[New York Post]]'' to call him an \"early [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] candidate\".<ref name=\"ibanezsplits\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/split.cgi?id=ibanera01&year=2009&t=b|title=Raul Ibanez 2009 Batting Splits|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/item_MbiqdejYNCrqysNXl7buVL| title=Champion Phillies Bringing Big Bats to Bronx| last=Puma | first=Mike | work= [[New York Post]]| date=May 22, 2009|accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref> He was placed on the [[disabled list]] in mid-June for a groin injury, however, and though he returned he did not bat above .260 for any other month that season.<ref name=\"ibanezsplits\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090618&content_id=5393172|first=David|last=Gurian-Peck|date=June 18, 2009|accessdate=March 1, 2011|publisher=Major League Baseball|work=[[MLB.com]]|title=Phillies' Ibanez lands on disabled list}}</ref> Although Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez did not receive MVP votes his teammates [[Ryan Howard]] and [[Chase Utley]] had successful years, finishing 3rd and 8th in the balloting respectively.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_2009.shtml#NLmvp|title=2009 Awards Voting|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref> The Phillies finished the season with a record of 93\u201369 (.574), six games above the second-place [[2009 Florida Marlins season|Florida Marlins]] in their division.<ref name=\"2009Phillies\"/>\n\nThe Phillies defeated the [[Wild card (sports)|wild card]] [[2009 Colorado Rockies season|Colorado Rockies]] in the [[2009 National League Division Series|National League Division Series]] (NLDS), three games to one, advancing to the [[2009 National League Championship Series|National League Championship Series]] (NLCS).<ref name=\"2009Phillies\"/> Facing the [[2009 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]], the Phillies won the NLCS, four games to one,<ref name=\"2009Phillies\"/> becoming the first team to repeat as [[National League]] champions since the [[1995 Atlanta Braves season|1995]]\u2013[[1996 Atlanta Braves season|96]] [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref name=\"Repeat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/|title=Major League Encyclopedia|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100109123721/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/| archivedate=January 9, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Ryan Howard won the [[League Championship Series Most Valuable Player Award|NLCS MVP]] for his strong offensive performance during the series.<ref name=\"nlcsmvp\">{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4584440 |title=Phillies' Howard takes home NLCS MVP |accessdate=February 27, 2011|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=October 22, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures}}</ref> Howard tied [[Lou Gehrig]]'s postseason record by having at least one [[Run batted in|RBI]] in eight straight games across the NLDS and NLCS.<ref name=\"nlcsmvp\"/> They became the first World Series champion to return to the World Series the following year since the [[2000 New York Yankees season|2000]]\u2013[[2001 New York Yankees season|01 New York Yankees]].<ref name=\"wshistory\"/>\n\n===New York Yankees===\n[[File:Yankees Celebrate Jeter Hit -2722.jpg|thumb|right|225px|The Yankees celebrate Derek Jeter breaking their franchise career hits record.|alt=Several men in pinstriped pants and red baseball caps, some wearing pinstriped baseball jerseys and some dark blue-hooded sweatshirts, stand in a group.]]\n{{Main|2009 New York Yankees season}}\nThe Yankees' offseason began in November 2008 with control over their organization shifting from long-time owner [[George Steinbrenner]] to his son [[Hal Steinbrenner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081120&content_id=3686135&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Control of Yankees shifts to son Hal|date=November 20, 2008|last=Bloom|first=Barry|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> Notable player departures included [[Mike Mussina]]\u2014who announced his retirement on November 20, 2008<ref>{{cite web |title=Mussina retires on a high note, with 20 wins in final season|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3715207|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=November 20, 2008|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\u2014as well as [[Bobby Abreu]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090210&content_id=3816686&vkey=hotstove2008&fext=.jsp|title=Out of left field, Abreu joins Angels|date=February 12, 2009|last=Spencer|first=Lyle|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203020042/http://www.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090210&content_id=3816686&vkey=hotstove2008&fext=.jsp|archivedate=February 3, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Jason Giambi]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090106&content_id=3735119&vkey=hotstove2008&fext=.jsp|title=Giambi 'excited to be home' with A's|date=January 7, 2009|last=Urban|first=Mychael|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> and [[Carl Pavano]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090109&content_id=3738312|title=Pavano finds right fit with Indians|date=January 9, 2009|last=Castrovince|first=Anthony|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> who all left as free agents. Notable free agent acquisitions included starting pitchers [[CC Sabathia]] and [[A. J. Burnett]], and [[first baseman]] [[Mark Teixeira]]. Another major addition was outfielder [[Nick Swisher]], acquired in a trade with the [[2008 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Yankees acquire Swisher, send Betemit and two pitchers to White Sox|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3700869|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|first=Jerry|last=Crasnick|authorlink=Jerry Crasnick|date=November 13, 2008|accessdate=November 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees played the 2009 season in [[Yankee Stadium]], their first year in that park after playing for 84 years in [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|\"Old\" Yankee Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Yankees open new stadium with blowout loss to Indians|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=290416110|work=[[ESPN.com]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=August 16, 2009|accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref> They won the [[American League East]] with an eight-game lead over [[Yankees \u2013 Red Sox rivalry|their rivals]], the [[2009 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]], compiling a record of 103\u201359.<ref name=\"2009Yankees\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/NYY/2009.shtml|title=2009 New York Yankees Batting, Pitching, & Fielding Statistics|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100104091513/http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/NYY/2009.shtml| archivedate=January 4, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Sabathia won 19 games and position players [[Alex Rodriguez]] and Teixeira both had strong seasons offensively, Rodriguez with 30 home runs and 100 RBI and Teixeira with 39 and 122 respectively.<ref name=\"2009Yankees\"/> [[Closer (baseball)|Closing pitcher]] [[Mariano Rivera]] earned his 500th [[save (baseball)|save]] against the Yankees' [[Mets\u2013Yankees rivalry|cross-town rival]] [[2009 New York Mets season|New York Mets]], becoming the second pitcher in history to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090627&content_id=5566046|title=Rivera takes place in history with No. 500|date=June 29, 2009|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> On September 11, 2009, [[shortstop]] [[Derek Jeter]] recorded his 2,722nd career hit, passing Lou Gehrig to become the all-time leader in career hits recorded as a Yankee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090911&content_id=6909874|title=Jeter passes Gehrig with 2,722nd hit|date=September 11, 2009|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees defeated the [[2009 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]] in three games in the [[2009 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] and the [[2009 Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim season|Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]] in six games in the [[2009 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]] (ALCS)<ref name=\"2009Yankees\"/> to win their first [[List of American League pennant winners|American League pennant]] since 2003.<ref name=\"Repeat\"/> Sabathia was named [[League Championship Series Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] of the ALCS with two wins in the series.<ref name=\"2009ALCS\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2009_ALCS.shtml|title=2009 League Championship Series \u2013 NYY vs. LAA|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref> The Yankees' victory in the ALCS earned them their 40th World Series appearance in franchise history, and their first since losing to the [[2003 Florida Marlins season|Florida Marlins]] in {{wsy|2003}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/NYY/|title=New York Yankees Team History & Encyclopedia|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Series preview===\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center\n|width=25%\n|align=right\n|quote=How great would that be? A World Series here, us against the Yankees? We've proved we can put on a pretty good show.\n|source=[[Jimmy Rollins]], discussing the potential of a Yankees\u2013Phillies World Series on May 24, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lisa-olson.fanhouse.com/2009/05/24/yankees-phillies-deliver-october-feel/ |title=Yankees, Phillies Deliver October Feel |last=Olson |first=Lisa |publisher=[[AOL Sports]] |date=May 24, 2009|accessdate=October 25, 2009}}</ref>\n}}\nThe two teams played a three-game [[Interleague play|interleague]] series at Yankee Stadium in May 2009, with the Phillies winning two of the three games.<ref name=\"interleague\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091027&content_id=7561434&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Phillies-Yankees Interleague recap|first=Jenifer|last=Langosch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 27, 2009|accessdate=March 1, 2011}}</ref> The series included two [[Save (baseball)|blown saves]] by Phillies' [[Closing pitcher|closer]] [[Brad Lidge]] in games 2 and 3, although the Phillies came back to win the final game in [[extra innings]].<ref name=\"interleague\"/>\n\nThe Yankees had [[Home advantage|home field advantage]] for the Series as the American League had won [[2009 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|that year's All-Star Game]].<ref name=\"allstar\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090715&content_id=5881270&vkey=allstar2009&fext=.jsp|title=AL retains World Series advantage|first=Anthony|last=Castrovince|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=July 15, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119084524/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090715&content_id=5881270&vkey=allstar2009&fext=.jsp| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> The team match-up was heavily discussed and analyzed in the media, per the east coast bias, prior to the beginning of the series. Both teams' offensive lineups were heavily touted,<ref name=\"verduccisi\"/><ref name=\"packpunch\">{{cite news |title=World Series packs punch at plate |author=Nightengale, Bob |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=October 27, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"TSNpreview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=296306 |title=2009 World Series Preview \u2013 Philadelphia vs. New York |date=October 27, 2009 |publisher=The Sports Network |accessdate=January 20, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091108041238/http://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=296306 |archive-date=November 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"offense\">{{cite news |title=The rest is hit story; Offence, offence and more offence mark these World Series contenders |last=Lott|first=John |newspaper=[[National Post]] |date=October 27, 2009}}</ref> with the Yankees and Phillies leading their respective leagues in [[Run (baseball)|runs scored]] per game.<ref name=\"mlboffense\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2009.shtml|title=2009 Major League Baseball Team Statistics and Standings|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> Yankees [[third base]]man Alex Rodriguez drew particular focus in the media for his success in earlier rounds of the 2009 playoffs in contrast to past postseason performances.<ref name=\"masslive\">{{cite web |url=http://www.masslive.com/sports/index.ssf/2009/10/post_127.html |title=Yankees slugger Alex Rodriguez deserves cheers for postseason performance |last=Chimelis|first=Ron |date=October 21, 2009|work=MassLive.com |publisher=[[The Republican (Springfield)|The Republican]] |accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"starledger\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2009/10/politi.html |title=As NY Yankees' Alex Rodriguez has postseason for the ages, it's best to appreciate, not ask why |last=Politi|first=Steve |date=October 21, 2009|work=NJ.com |publisher=[[The Star-Ledger]] |accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"dayrod\">\n{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091020&content_id=7508478 |title=Night-and-Day Rod: '09 Alex at his best |author=DiComo, Anthony |date=October 21, 2009|work=MLB.com |publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> The two lineups featured twenty former [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Stars]] and three former MVP award winners.<ref name=\"packpunch\"/> Only one regular starter between both teams, Phillies [[catcher]] [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]], did not have at least ten [[home run]]s during the 2009 regular season.<ref name=\"packpunch\"/> The two teams combined for 468 home runs during the season, more than any pair of opponents in World Series history.<ref name=\"packpunch\"/>\n\nThe pitching staffs were also the subject of significant discussion prior to the series.<ref name=\"TSNpreview\"/> The starting pitchers for Game&nbsp;1, CC Sabathia and Cliff Lee, were regarded as aces<ref name=\"offense\"/> who dominated the 2009 postseason with a 0.96 [[earned run average]] (ERA) between them.<ref name=\"clunkers\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/27/sports/baseball/27kepner.html |title=Baseball Hopes to Break a Streak of Clunker Series |last=Kepner|first=Tyler |date=October 26, 2009 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref> This matchup was of particular note, as Sabathia and Lee were former teammates from the Cleveland Indians and each had won a [[Cy Young Award]] with that franchise.<ref name=\"clunkers\"/><ref name=\"joepos\">{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/joe_posnanski/10/28/lee.sabathia/index.html |title=World Series lament for Indians fans: What might have been |last=Posnanski|first=Joe |date=October 28, 2009|work=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100104110958/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/joe_posnanski/10/28/lee.sabathia/index.html| archivedate=January 4, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/columnist/lopresti/2009-10-29-former-indians-pitchers-lopo_N.htm |title=Spurned Cleveland watches former Indians with a sigh |author=Lopresti, Mike |date=October 29, 2009|newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref> Yankees [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Joe Girardi]] had been using a three-man [[starting rotation]] during the playoffs, in contrast to the four-pitcher rotation used by the Phillies.<ref name=\"3man\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4611766 |title=Girardi may go with three-man rotation |date=October 29, 2009|author=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"usatight\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/playoffs/2009-10-27-world-series-breakdown_N.htm |title=Yankees and Phillies on track for a tight Series |date=October 28, 2009|author=Ortiz, Jorge |author2=Shandler, Ron|newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref> This difference led ''[[USA Today]]'' to give the Phillies' starting rotation the \"edge\" in the series, as the World Series had one fewer day off than previous rounds of the playoffs, making the series less conducive to using a three-man rotation.<ref name=\"usatight\"/> [[Gene Wojciechowski]] of [[ESPN]] criticized Girardi's strategy, arguing that [[Chad Gaudin]] should have pitched in Game&nbsp;5 or 6, instead of A. J. Burnett or [[Andy Pettitte]] on reduced, three days' rest.<ref name=\"woj3man\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/columns/story?columnist=wojciechowski_gene&id=4612984&sportCat=mlb |title=Girardi needs to give it a rest |date=October 31, 2009|first=Gene|last=Wojciechowski|authorlink=Gene Wojciechowski|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> Wojciechowski argued that while Sabathia had proven his ability to pitch on shorter rest, Burnett and Pettitte should have been given their regular time between starts.<ref name=\"woj3man\"/> Burnett had drawn some criticism, as he performed poorly in his last appearance before the World Series,<ref name=\"clunkers\"/> a start in Game&nbsp;5 of the ALCS in which he allowed six runs over six innings.<ref name=\"ALCSg5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ANA/ANA200910220.shtml|title=October 22, 2009 American League Championship Series (ALCS) Game&nbsp;5, Yankees at Angels|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> However, Burnett had previously been successful on short rest, going 4\u20130 with a 2.33 ERA in four career starts on short rest before this game. Some believed Girardi settled on a three-man rotation because he had limited options for a fourth starting pitcher, either Gaudin or [[Joba Chamberlain]], who had been inconsistent as starters in the regular season and had been shifted into the bullpen for the postseason.<ref name=\"woj3man\"/><ref name=\"batsblog\">{{cite news|url=http://bats.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/27/yankees-may-use-a-three-man-rotation/|title=Yankees May Use a Three-Man Rotation | last=Kepner | first=Tyler |date=October 27, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 26, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100327234601/http://bats.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/27/yankees-may-use-a-three-man-rotation/| archivedate= March 27, 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/14/sports/baseball/14yankees.html|title=Barring Rain, Yanks Consider 3-Man Rotation | last=Kepner | first=Tyler |date=October 13, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe matchup of closers, Mariano Rivera and Brad Lidge, also drew attention. Rivera and Lidge were the only closers who had not blown a save during the 2009 postseason, whereas closers on other postseason teams blew 11 saves in the 24 postseason games before the World Series in 2009.<ref name=\"closerpreview\">{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091027&content_id=7558018&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Closer matchup reflects playoff perfection |author=Langosch, Jenifer |date=October 27, 2009|work=MLB.com |publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |accessdate=March 17, 2010}}</ref> Both had performed well during the postseason, but Lidge had posted a 7.21 ERA during the 2009 regular season, in contrast to Rivera's 1.76.<ref name=\"closerpreview\"/><ref name=\"mobref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/riverma01.shtml|title=Mariano Rivera Statistics and History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=March 17, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100208150022/http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/riverma01.shtml| archivedate=February 8, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Lidge's 2009 numbers were in stark contrast to the previous season (41 out of 41 save opportunities, a 1.95 ERA, and 92 strikeouts in 62 games). As a result, ''USA Today'' gave the Yankees the edge, noting that Lidge had blown two saves against the Yankees during their regular season series earlier that year.<ref name=\"usatight\"/>\n\n==Background==\nThe Series started on October 28, 2009, which was the latest start in World Series history, beating the previous record held by the 2001 World Series (October 27).<ref>{{cite news |first=Bob|last=Dutton|title=World Series Buzz: Martinez ruminates on New York|work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=October 29, 2009}}</ref> Game&nbsp;4 was played on Sunday, November 1 and the series-winning Game&nbsp;6 took place on November 4. The Series was only the third to end in a month other than October. The first came in {{wsy|1918}}, which was played entirely in September after the regular season was cut short due to World War I.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/postseason/mlb_ws_recaps.jsp?feature=1918|title=World Series History|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref> The other such series was in {{wsy|2001}} when the [[September 11 attacks]] caused a delay in the baseball season that eventually forced the end of the World Series into November.<ref>{{cite video|title=Nine Innings from Ground Zero|people=Shapiro, Ouisie (writer)|medium=DVD}}</ref>\n\nEarlier in the season [[Commissioner of Baseball (MLB)|Commissioner]] [[Bud Selig]] expressed interest in scheduling a World Series game during daylight hours instead of the evening.<ref>{{cite news|title=World Series could get earlier starting times|url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/30111531/|work=[[NBC Sports]]|agency=''[[Sporting News]]''|date=April 8, 2009|accessdate=March 20, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115021237/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/30111531|archive-date=January 15, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The starting times were ultimately moved before 8&nbsp;p.m. ET for the first time in 30 years, but no day games were played.<ref>{{cite web |title= WS games to start 40 minutes earlier|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4174213|author=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=May 18, 2009|accessdate=May 18, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090520134209/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4174213| archivedate=May 20, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Larry|last=Fine|title=Selig mulls World Series changes, not to home comforts|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/12/03/us-baseball-selig-idUSTRE4B18VG20081203|work=[[Reuters]]|date=December 2, 2008|accessdate=December 3, 2008}}</ref> The [[Philadelphia Eagles]] and [[New York Giants]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) played across the street from Citizens Bank Park at [[Lincoln Financial Field]] on the day of Game&nbsp;4. The NFL moved that game's kickoff time to 1&nbsp;p.m. to avoid it ending too close to the start of Game&nbsp;4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/blogs/sports/watchdog-1.812020/giants-jets-play-at-same-time-11-1-1.1520052|title=Giants, Jets play at same time 11/1|first=Neil|last=Best|work=[[Newsday]]|date=October 13, 2009|accessdate=October 13, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091015110950/http://www.newsday.com/blogs/sports/watchdog-1.812020/giants-jets-play-at-same-time-11-1-1.1520052| archivedate=October 15, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Similarly, Game&nbsp;5 was played at Citizens Bank Park on the same day as the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] hosted the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) at the [[Wells Fargo Center (Philadelphia)|Wachovia Center]]. The opening faceoff of the hockey game was scheduled for 7&nbsp;p.m. but the NHL moved it to 5&nbsp;p.m. to avoid conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=502389|title=Flyers Change Start Time of November 2nd Game|date=October 16, 2009|accessdate=October 29, 2009|publisher=philadelphiaflyers.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091021142810/http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=502389| archivedate=October 21, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Umpire (baseball)|umpires]] for the series were [[Joe West (umpire)|Joe West]], [[Dana DeMuth]], [[Gerry Davis (umpire)|Gerry Davis]], [[Brian Gorman]], [[Jeff Nelson (umpire)|Jeff Nelson]], and [[Mike Everitt (baseball)|Mike Everitt]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the World Series umpiring crew|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4600610|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=October 27, 2009|accessdate=November 17, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091031194903/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4600610| archivedate=October 31, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> The World Series crew had included at least 1 umpire who had never worked the World Series in 24 of the past 25 series; however, following several mistakes by umpires in earlier rounds of the playoffs, this crew did not.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091022&content_id=7527964&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=MLB may use veteran umps in Fall Classic: Change would break longstanding baseball tradition |first=Adam |last=McCalvy|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 22, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091022&content_id=7524222&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Umpire's call on Damon draws attention: Yankee looked safe at first base on third-inning groundout |first=Anthony |last=Castrovince |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 23, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"wojreplay\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/columns/story?columnist=wojciechowski_gene&id=4598071&sportCat=mlb |title=Instant replay for the World Series? Yes|first=Gene|last=Wojciechowski|authorlink=Gene Wojciechowski|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |date=October 27, 2009|accessdate=November 17, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091030130026/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/columns/story?columnist=wojciechowski_gene&id=4598071&sportCat=mlb| archivedate=October 30, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe Phillies had won the [[2008 World Series|previous season's World Series]] against the [[2008 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]] for the franchise's second championship. The Yankees had lost their previous World Series appearance to the [[2003 Florida Marlins season|Florida Marlins]] in {{wsy|2003}} and had not won since {{wsy|2000}} against the [[2000 New York Mets season|New York Mets]]. This was the fifth Series played between teams from New York and Philadelphia, and was the first Yankees\u2013Phillies matchup since {{wsy|1950}}.<ref name=\"1950WS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1950_WS.shtml|title=1950 World Series \u2013 NYY vs. PHI|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref> The series also was the fourth consecutive time that the Phillies would have faced a team from the current AL East in the World Series, while the Yankees had faced a NL East opponent in four of their five most recent World Series appearances.<ref name=\"wshistory\"/>\n\nThis Series had two unofficial nicknames: \"Turnpike Series\", for the [[New Jersey Turnpike]], which connects New York to Philadelphia through the state of New Jersey,<ref name=\"verduccisi\">{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/tom_verducci/10/27/five.cuts/index.html |title=How can the Phillies beat the Yankees in the 2009 World Series? |first=Tom|last=Verducci|authorlink=Tom Verducci|date=October 28, 2009|work=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100205111403/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/tom_verducci/10/27/five.cuts/index.html| archivedate=February 5, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> and \"Liberty Series\", based on the [[Liberty Bell]] in Philadelphia and the [[Statue of Liberty]] in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091026&content_id=7549598&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title= Liberty Series: Statue, Bell Set for Clash |accessdate=October 26, 2009|last=Newman|first=Mark|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 26, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091027192133/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091026&content_id=7549598&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=October 27, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Summary==\n{{MLB Playoff Summary\n| summary =\n| winner = New York\n| leader =\n| score = 4\u20132\n| date1 = October 28\n| score1 = '''Philadelphia Phillies''' \u2013 6, New York Yankees \u2013 1\n| loc1 = [[Yankee Stadium]]\n| time1 = 3:27\n| att1 = 50,207\n| ref1 = <ref name=\"Game1\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_10/day_28/gid_2009_10_28_phimlb_nyamlb_1/boxscore_col.html|title=Philadelphia vs. NY Yankees \u2013 October 28, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date2 = October 29\n| score2 = Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 1, '''New York Yankees''' \u2212 3\n| loc2 = Yankee Stadium\n| time2 = 3:25\n| att2 = 50,181\n| ref2 = <ref name=\"Game2\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_10/day_29/gid_2009_10_29_phimlb_nyamlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=Philadelphia vs. NY Yankees \u2013 October 29, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date3 = October 31\n| score3 = '''New York Yankees''' \u2013 8, Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 5\n| loc3 = [[Citizens Bank Park]]\n| time3 = 3:25\n| att3 = 46,061\n| ref3 = <ref name=\"Game3\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_10/day_31/gid_2009_10_31_nyamlb_phimlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=NY Yankees vs. Philadelphia \u2013 October 31, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=October 31, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date4 = November 1\n| score4 = '''New York Yankees''' \u2013 7, Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 4\n| loc4 = Citizens Bank Park\n| time4 = 3:25\n| att4 = 46,145\n| ref4 = <ref name=\"Game4\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_11/day_01/gid_2009_11_01_nyamlb_phimlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=NY Yankees vs. Philadelphia \u2013 November 1, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=November 1, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date5 = November 2\n| score5 = New York Yankees \u2013 6, '''Philadelphia Phillies''' \u2013 8\n| loc5 = Citizens Bank Park\n| time5 = 3:26\n| att5 = 46,178\n| ref5 = <ref name=\"Game5\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_11/day_02/gid_2009_11_02_nyamlb_phimlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=NY Yankees vs. Philadelphia \u2013 November 2, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n| date6 = November 4\n| score6 = Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 3, '''New York Yankees''' \u2013 7\n| loc6 = Yankee Stadium\n| time6 = 3:52\n| att6 = 50,315\n| ref6 = <ref name=\"Game6\">{{cite web |url=http://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2009/month_11/day_04/gid_2009_11_04_phimlb_nyamlb_1/boxscore_col.html |title=Philadelphia vs. NY Yankees \u2013 November 4, 2009 |work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Matchups==\n\n===Game 1===\n[[File:Cliff Lee, philly.jpg|175px|thumb|right|alt=A man in a gray baseball uniform with red sleeves and cap throws a baseball with his left arm.|Phillies starting pitcher Cliff Lee, pictured in the 2009 regular season, became the first pitcher to ever throw a postseason series opener complete game against the Yankees without allowing an earned run.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Wednesday, October 28, 2009\n|Time=7:57{{nbsp}}pm ([[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]])\n|Location=[[Yankee Stadium]] in [[The Bronx|Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|Road='''Philadelphia'''|RoadAbr=PHI\n|R1=0|R2=0|R3=1|R4=0|R5=0|R6=1|R7=0|R8=2|R9=2|RR=6|RH=9|RE=1\n|Home=New York|HomeAbr=NYY\n|H1=0|H2=0|H3=0|H4=0|H5=0|H6=0|H7=0|H8=0|H9=1|HR=1|HH=6|HE=0\n|WP=[[Cliff Lee]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[CC Sabathia]] (0\u20131)|SV=\n|RoadHR=[[Chase Utley]] 2 (2)|HomeHR=\n}}\n[[File:2009 World Series Game 1 Ceremonial first pitch.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A man in a green military uniform prepares to throw a ball, while two women and a man on the left wearing red jackets with \"World Series\" on the chest look on.|Ceremonial first pitch of the World Series with Michelle Obama, Jill Biden, and Yogi Berra watching]]\n[[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]] and [[Wife of the Vice President of the United States|Second Lady]] [[Jill Biden]] escorted former Yankees catcher and [[World War II]] veteran [[Yogi Berra]] to the mound, where the [[ceremonial first pitch]] was thrown by a veteran of the [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091027&content_id=7558082&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=First lady, Dr. Biden on hand for Game 1 |accessdate=November 11, 2009|last=Newman|first=Mark|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091031070612/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091027&content_id=7558082&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=October 31, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> The Phillies' Ryan Howard got the first hit of the 2009 World Series by doubling in the first inning.<ref name=\"game1bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200910280.shtml|title=October 28, 2009 World Series Game 1, Phillies at Yankees|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref> Howard was stranded in the first and the game was scoreless after two innings.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> The Phillies scored first with a two-out [[home run]] by Chase Utley in the top of the third inning.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> Through the first five innings, Philadelphia starting pitcher Cliff Lee allowed no runs and three hits, striking out seven Yankees batters.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> In the top of the sixth, Utley hit another home run to give the Phillies a 2\u20130 lead.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> The starting pitchers Lee and CC Sabathia continued to pitch until the top of the eighth when Sabathia was replaced by [[Phil Hughes]].<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> Hughes walked the first two batters and was replaced by [[D\u00e1maso Marte]].<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> Marte got two quick outs and was relieved by [[David Robertson (baseball)|David Robertson]], who walked [[Jayson Werth]] and gave up a two-run single to Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> The Phillies added two more runs in the ninth with an RBI single by [[Shane Victorino]] and an RBI double by Howard.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/> Lee finished with a complete game allowing one unearned run on six hits and striking out ten batters, not walking any of the hitters he faced.<ref name=\"game1bref\"/>\n\nLee's pitching performance made history in several ways:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4604436 |title=Lee takes over Yankee Stadium |first=Jayson |last=Stark|authorlink=Jayson Stark|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=October 29, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091101152743/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4604436| archivedate=November 1, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n* This was the fourth postseason start of Lee's career. In all four starts, he went at least seven innings and gave up no more than one earned run. The only other starting pitcher ever to begin his postseason career with four such starts was [[Christy Mathewson]].\n* He was also the first left-handed starter to beat the Yankees in The Bronx to open a World Series since [[Sandy Koufax]] in {{wsy|1963}}.\n* He was the first starting pitcher to throw a complete game without giving up an earned run against the Yankees in Game&nbsp;1 of a postseason series.\n* Lee was the first pitcher ever to strike out at least ten, walk no one, and give up no earned runs in a World Series start.\n\n===Game 2===\n[[File:Mariano Rivera allison 7 29 07.jpg|thumb|225px|Yankees closer Mariano Rivera, pictured during the 2007 regular season, pitched two scoreless innings in Game 2 for the save.|alt=A man in a gray baseball uniform and navy blue cap stands on a dirt mound. He is striding forward with his left leg as he clutches a baseball behind his head with his right hand and curls his left hand, wearing a baseball glove, under his outstretched arm. His uniform reads \"New York\" in navy blue letters across the chest. His face is contorted in concentration.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Thursday, October 29, 2009\n|Time=7:57{{nbsp}}pm (EDT)\n|Location=Yankee Stadium in Bronx, New York\n|Road=Philadelphia|RoadAbr=PHI\n|R1=0|R2=1|R3=0|R4=0|R5=0|R6=0|R7=0|R8=0|R9=0|RR=1|RH=6|RE=0\n|Home='''New York'''|HomeAbr=NYY\n|H1=0|H2=0|H3=0|H4=1|H5=0|H6=1|H7=1|H8=0|H9=X|HR=3|HH=8|HE=0\n|WP=[[A. J. Burnett]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]] (0\u20131)|SV= [[Mariano Rivera]] (1)\n|RoadHR=|HomeHR= [[Mark Teixeira]] (1), [[Hideki Matsui]] (1)\n|}}\n\nPrior to the game, [[Jay-Z]] and [[Alicia Keys]] performed the song \"[[Empire State of Mind]]\" for the Yankee Stadium crowd.<ref name=\"jayzkeys\">{{cite web| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1625161/20091029/keys_alicia.jhtml|title=Jay-Z And Alicia Keys Pump Up World Series Crowd In NYC|first=Jayson|last=Rodriguez|publisher=[[MTV]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009|date=October 29, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102065545/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1625161/20091029/keys_alicia.jhtml| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> This game marked the first postseason appearance of [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]] against the Yankees since the [[2004 American League Championship Series]], when he was with the [[2004 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]] and a part of the two teams' [[Yankees \u2013 Red Sox rivalry|long standing rivalry]]; it was also the second-ever World Series start that Mart\u00ednez made.<ref name=\"pedrobref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/martipe02.shtml|title=Pedro Mart\u00ednez Statistics and History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=October 30, 2009}}</ref> There was much media interest in Mart\u00ednez's \"return to Yankee Stadium\" for Game 2, as he told reporters at a pre-game press conference \"When you have 60,000 people chanting your name, waiting for you to throw the ball, you have to consider yourself someone special, someone that really has a purpose out there.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Silverman|first=Mike |url=http://news.bostonherald.com/sports/baseball/other_mlb/view.bg?articleid=1208123&srvc=sports&position=0|title='Influential' Pedro Martinez holds court|work=Boston Herald|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Phillies scored first for the second game in a row, with Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez hitting a [[ground rule double]] and then scoring on a [[Matt Stairs]] RBI single off [[A. J. Burnett]] in the second inning.<ref name=\"game2bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200910290.shtml|title=October 29, 2009 World Series Game 2, Phillies at Yankees|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=October 30, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102110038/http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200910290.shtml| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nMark Teixeira tied the game with a home run in the fourth inning, and [[Hideki Matsui]] broke the tie in the sixth with another homer.<ref name=\"game2bref\"/> Mart\u00ednez departed the game after giving up consecutive hits to [[Jerry Hairston Jr.]] and [[Melky Cabrera]] to start the seventh inning, and reliever Chan Ho Park gave up an RBI single to [[Jorge Posada]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Bryan|last=Hoch|title=Yanks take Classic duel to pull even|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091029&content_id=7572446&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=October 30, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102045339/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091029&content_id=7572446&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> With Cabrera at second base and Posada at first, [[Johnny Damon]] hit a low line drive at Phillies first baseman Ryan Howard. Howard grabbed the ball and threw to second where Posada was tagged and called out while standing on the base. First-base umpire [[Brian Gorman]] ruled that Howard had caught the ball in the air; thus, the result was an inning-ending double play. Both Posada and Joe Girardi vehemently protested the call, claiming that the batted ball had hit the ground before being caught; however, the umpires did not reverse the call. ESPN reported that Gorman blew the call.<ref>{{cite web |title=Game 2 calls draw more scrutiny|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4607883|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=December 8, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102180815/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4607883| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> This was the first of two calls made by Gorman in Game Two that were heavily criticized.<ref>{{cite news |title=Time for video replay in baseball before something really sorry happens... again |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/marinersblog/2010169691_time_for_video_replay_in_baseb.html|date=October 30, 2009|newspaper=[[Seattle Times]]|first=Geoff|last=Baker|accessdate=December 8, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104083300/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/marinersblog/2010169691_time_for_video_replay_in_baseb.html| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The time has come for MLB to implement instant replay |url=http://www.nesn.com/2009/10/the-time-has-come-for-mlb-to-implement-instant-replay.html|date=October 31, 2009|publisher=[[New England Sports Network]]|first=David|last=Heck|accessdate=December 8, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091205005355/http://www.nesn.com/2009/10/the-time-has-come-for-mlb-to-implement-instant-replay.html| archivedate=December 5, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"closecallsgame2\">{{cite news |first=David|last=Waldstein|title=In World Series, Umpires Find Themselves Back in Center of Dispute|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/30/sports/baseball/30umps.html?_r=1|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBurnett left the game after seven innings, having given up one run. He was replaced by Mariano Rivera in the eighth inning.<ref name=\"game2bref\"/> With one out in the eighth, the Phillies put two runners on with a walk to [[Jimmy Rollins]] and a single by Shane Victorino.<ref name=\"game2bref\"/> However, Chase Utley grounded into an inning-ending double play<ref name=\"game2bref\"/> ending on a close play at first base. The play was the second disputed call made by umpire Brian Gorman in Game Two. Gorman himself later admitted he missed this call, saying, \"on a freeze frame, it looks like there's a little bit of a ball outside [Teixeira's] glove when [Utley] hits the bag.\"<ref name=\"closecallsgame2\"/> Ultimately, Rivera threw 39 pitches and got six outs for his 38th postseason save, his tenth in World Series play.<ref>{{cite news |first=Erik|last=Boland|title=Rivera gets six-out save as Yankees win Game 2, 3\u20131|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/rivera-gets-six-out-save-as-yankees-win-game-2-3-1-1.1557551|newspaper=[[Newsday]]|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=October 30, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091102093726/http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/rivera-gets-six-out-save-as-yankees-win-game-2-3-1-1.1557551| archivedate=November 2, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= dead}}</ref> \n{{Clear}} Burnett earned the win in Game Two.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2009/10/ny_yankees_beat_philadelphia_p.html|title=NY Yankees beat Philadelphia Phillies, 3-1, in Game 2 of World Series|work=NJ.com|last=Carig|first=Marc|date=October 29, 2009|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Game 3===\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Saturday, October 31, 2009\n|Time=9:17{{nbsp}}pm (EDT)\n|Location=[[Citizens Bank Park]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n|Road='''New York'''|RoadAbr=NYY\n|R1=0|R2=0|R3=0|R4=2|R5=3|R6=1|R7=1|R8=1|R9=0|RR=8|RH=8|RE=1\n|Home=Philadelphia|HomeAbr=PHI\n|H1=0|H2=3|H3=0|H4=0|H5=0|H6=1|H7=0|H8=0|H9=1|HR=5|HH=6|HE=0\n|WP=[[Andy Pettitte]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[Cole Hamels]] (0\u20131)\n|RoadHR=[[Alex Rodriguez]] (1), [[Nick Swisher]] (1), [[Hideki Matsui]] (2) |HomeHR=[[Jayson Werth]] 2 (2), [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]] (1)\n|}}\nThe start of the game was postponed 80 minutes due to a rain delay, pushing the start time to 9:17&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/11/01/us-baseball-series-rain-idUSTRE5A000I20091101|title=World Series gets underway after rain delay|date=October 31, 2009|accessdate=December 20, 2012|work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> The cast of the television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' (with [[Amber Riley]] singing lead) performed the [[national anthem]] as part of a ceremony featuring a large American flag and several members of the armed services.<ref name=\"glee\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091031&content_id=7586030&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=MLB Stands Up to Cancer in Game 3|accessdate=March 16, 2010|last=Newman|first=Mark|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"flaggame3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.512aw.afrc.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123176480|title=Reservist takes part in opening ceremony of Game 3 of World Series|accessdate=March 16, 2010|last=Losurdo|first=Marnee|work=[[512th Airlift Wing]]|publisher=[[United States Air Force]]|date=November 6, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722180557/http://www.512aw.afrc.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123176480|archivedate=July 22, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Phillies scored first with Jayson Werth's lead-off home run, which was followed by a bases-loaded walk and a [[sacrifice fly]] to make the score 3\u20130 in the bottom of the second inning.<ref name=\"game3bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200910310.shtml|title=October 31, 2009 World Series Game 3, Yankees at Phillies|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091108163317/http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200910310.shtml| archivedate=November 8, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Following Mark Teixeira's walk in the top of the fourth inning, Alex Rodriguez hit a deep ball down the right field line. It was originally ruled a double so Teixeira held at third base. The play was reviewed using [[MLB instant replay]], which revealed that the ball had struck a camera sticking over the top of the wall, so the ball was ruled a two-run home run,<ref name=\"cameramove\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594160&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Camera moved after A-Rod homer|accessdate=November 1, 2009|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104234934/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594160&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> giving Rodriguez his first World Series hit.<ref name=\"arodbref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/rodrial01.shtml|title=Alex Rodriguez Statistics and History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> This was the first home run reviewed by instant replay in postseason play.<ref name=\"cameramove\"/> Specifically, the ball hit a camera owned by [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and MLB which extended slightly over the right field wall.<ref name=\"cameramove\"/> The camera was moved back for Game&nbsp;4 such that its lens was in line with the wall.<ref name=\"cameramove\"/> Coincidentally, Alex Rodriguez also had the first regular season home run reviewed by replay.<ref name=\"arod08replay\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080903&content_id=3412816&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title= Instant replay used for first time|accessdate=November 1, 2009|last=Chastain|first=Bill|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=September 4, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091103075313/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080903&content_id=3412816&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 3, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nick Swisher]] opened the top of the fifth inning with a double and scored on a single to center field by Andy Pettitte.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> This was Pettitte's first career postseason RBI and the first RBI by a Yankees pitcher in a World Series since [[Jim Bouton]] in [[1964 World Series|1964]].<ref name=\"bouton\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4613099|title=2009 World Series: New York Yankees' Pettitte knows his way around this stage |accessdate=November 2, 2009|date=October 31, 2009|first=Jayson|last=Stark|authorlink=Jayson Stark|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104235650/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4613099| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Derek Jeter followed Pettitte with another single, and both runners scored on a two-run double by Johnny Damon.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> [[Cole Hamels]] then walked Teixeira and was relieved by [[J. A. Happ|J.&nbsp;A. Happ]]. Happ closed out the fifth without allowing further scoring, but [[Nick Swisher]] added to the Yankees lead with a home run off of him in the sixth.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> Werth hit his second home run of the game leading off the bottom of the sixth to close the Yankees lead to 6\u20134,<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> becoming the second Phillies player to hit multiple home runs in this World Series.\n\n[[Chad Durbin]] relieved Happ in the top of the seventh. He walked Johnny Damon, who then [[Stolen base|stole]] second base. Rodriguez was then [[Hit by pitch|hit by a pitch]], and Damon scored on a single by Jorge Posada.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> Joba Chamberlain relieved Pettitte in the bottom of the seventh and retired the side in order. [[Brett Myers]] retired the first two batters in the top of the eighth, but Hideki Matsui then hit a home run [[Pinch hitter|pinch hitting]] for Chamberlain.<ref name=\"pinchhithr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7591284&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Lack of DH doesn't hinder Yankees|accessdate=November 1, 2009|last=Ghiroli|first=Brittnay|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221120621/http://mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7591284&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|archivedate=February 21, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Phil Hughes pitched a third of an inning in the bottom of the ninth and allowed a solo home run to [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]] before being relieved by Mariano Rivera.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> Rivera closed out the game, throwing just five pitches to record the final two outs.<ref name=\"game3bref\"/> This game was Pettitte's 17th career postseason win, extending his MLB record.<ref name=\"bouton\"/>\n\n===Game 4===\n[[File:Brad Lidge phillies.jpg|thumb|right|150px|alt=A man in grey pants, a blue baseball jersey, and a red baseball cap with \"P\" on it jogs on a grass field while carrying a red article of clothing in his right hand.|Phillies closer Brad Lidge, pictured during the 2008 regular season, allowed three runs in the ninth inning of a tied Game 4 and took the loss.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Sunday, November 1, 2009\n|Time=8:20{{nbsp}}pm (EST)\n|Location=Citizens Bank Park in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|Road='''New York'''|RoadAbr=NYY\n|R1=2|R2=0|R3=0|R4=0|R5=2|R6=0|R7=0|R8=0|R9=3|RR=7|RH=9|RE=1\n|Home=Philadelphia|HomeAbr=PHI\n|H1=1|H2=0|H3=0|H4=1|H5=0|H6=0|H7=1|H8=1|H9=0|HR=4|HH=8|HE=1\n|WP=[[Joba Chamberlain]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[Brad Lidge]] (0\u20131)|SV=[[Mariano Rivera]] (2)\n|RoadHR=|HomeHR=[[Chase Utley]] (3), [[Pedro Feliz]] (1)\n|}}\n\nPrior to the start of the game, Derek Jeter and [[Albert Pujols]] were named winners of the [[Hank Aaron Award]] for their offensive performances in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7595224&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Pujols, Jeter winners of Aaron Award |accessdate=November 4, 2009|last=Bloom|first=Barry|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104234955/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7595224&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> This was the first game to test manager Joe Girardi's decision to use a three-man [[starting rotation]], as CC Sabathia started the game on three days rest, a shorter period than he normally got during the regular season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291031122&teams=new-york-yankees-vs-philadelphia-phillies |author=[[Associated Press]]|title=A-Rod starts rally, Pettitte hits RBI single as Yankees claim 2\u20131 lead over Phillies |date=October 31, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> Jeter led the game off with a single and advanced to third base on a double by Johnny Damon.<ref name=\"game4bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200911010.shtml|title=November 1, 2009 World Series Game 4, Yankees at Phillies|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref> Jeter scored via a Mark Teixeira ground out and Alex Rodriguez was [[Hit by pitch|hit by a pitch]].<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Rodriguez was hit twice the night before and the umpires issued warnings to both benches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594158&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Benches warned after A-Rod plunking|accessdate=November 2, 2009|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104234929/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594158&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Jorge Posada then added to the Yankees lead that inning with a [[sacrifice fly]].<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> The Phillies answered quickly, scoring a run on successive doubles by Shane Victorino and Chase Utley in the bottom of the first.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Sabathia [[Intentional walk|intentionally walked]] Jayson Werth, but escaped the inning without further scoring.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> The Phillies tied the game in the bottom of the fourth as Ryan Howard singled, [[Stolen base|stole]] second, and scored on a single by [[Pedro Feliz]].<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Although the run counted, [[instant replay]] of Howard's slide showed that he did not touch [[home plate]].  As Sabathia threw to second base, Mike Everitt signaled that Howard was safe due to the attempted play on Feliz.  Sabathia then pitched to Carlos Ruiz as part of an intentional walk, therefore losing the right to appeal that Howard missed home.<ref name=\"FOX4\">{{cite video|title=Major League Baseball on Fox: Game 4 of the 2009 World Series|medium=television|publisher=Fox|date=November 1, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7597644&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Howard scores without touching plate|accessdate=November 2, 2009|last=Langosch|first=Jennifer|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221120217/http://mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7597644&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|archivedate=February 21, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nNick Swisher walked to lead off the fifth inning and advanced to second on a Melky Cabrera single.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Swisher restored the Yankees' lead, scoring on a single by Jeter, and Cabrera added to it by scoring a run on a Damon single.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> [[Brett Gardner]] replaced Cabrera in center field as a [[defensive substitution]] in the bottom of the sixth inning after Cabrera left the game due to a hamstring injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291101122|title=New York Yankees vs. Philadelphia Phillies \u2013 Recap \u2013 November 10, 2009 \u2013 ESPN |accessdate=November 2, 2009|author=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091105033102/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291101122| archivedate=November 5, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Chan Ho Park relieved Phillies starter [[Joe Blanton]] in the seventh and held the Yankees scoreless in that inning.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Chase Utley hit his third [[home run]] of the series in the bottom of the seventh with two outs, bringing the game to 4\u20133. D\u00e1maso Marte relieved Sabathia and got the final out of the seventh without further scoring.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/>\n\n[[Ryan Madson]] relieved Park in the eighth and allowed a walk and a single but held the Yankees scoreless.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Joba Chamberlain replaced Marte in the bottom of the inning. He struck out the first two batters he faced but allowed a game-tying home run to Feliz before closing the inning.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/>\n\nBrad Lidge came into the game for the ninth inning, popping out Matsui and striking out Jeter before surrendering a two-out single to Damon\u2014after a nine-pitch at bat with two strikes and four foul balls.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=stark_jayson&id=4615712 | title=Damon steals the show|author=Stark, Jayson|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| date=November 2009}}</ref> Then, with Teixeira batting, Damon stole second and, on the same play, also stole third as the base was uncovered due to a [[Baseball positioning|defensive shift]] against Teixeira.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594166&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Johnny lately: Yanks' 9th makes it a 3\u20131 Series |accessdate=November 2, 2009|last=Hoch|first=Brian|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 1, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104234938/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091101&content_id=7594166&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Several news outlets referred to this as a \"mad dash\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=crasnick_jerry&id=4615700 |first=Jerry|last=Crasnick|authorlink=Jerry Crasnick|title=Phillies awoke nearly silent Rodriguez |date=November 1, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/news/sports/games/62368/ |first=Will|last=Leitch|title=No Holding Back This Holliday Season |date=November 28, 2009|work=NYmag.com|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |accessdate=March 29, 2010}}</ref> which Mike Vaccaro of the ''[[New York Post]]'' compared to [[Enos Slaughter]]'s [[Slaughter's Mad Dash|\"Mad Dash\"]] in the [[1946 World Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/this_fall_this_team_is_rod_DB5iolugqEFjDhEsdir6bJ/1|title=This fall, this team, is A-Rod's|last=Vaccaro|first=Mike|work=[[New York Post]]|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606173012/http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/this_fall_this_team_is_rod_DB5iolugqEFjDhEsdir6bJ/1|archivedate=June 6, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Some believed that Damon's play caused Lidge to avoid throwing his best pitch\u2014a [[Slider (baseball)|slider]] with sharp downward movement\u2014for the rest of the inning, as it risked a [[wild pitch]] that would have allowed Damon to score from third base.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/extras/extra_bases/2009/11/hes_no_idiot_af.html|title=He's no idiot after all |last=Abraham|first=Peter|work=[[Boston Globe]]|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/playoffs/2009-11-02-series-breakdown_N.htm|title=Series breakdown: Veteran Damon makes grand theft|last=White|first=Paul|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> Teixeira was then hit by a pitch and Rodriguez put the Yankees ahead with a double, scoring Damon.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Posada added to that lead with a single that scored Teixeira and Rodriguez, but was thrown out at second to end the inning.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/> Mariano Rivera entered in the bottom of the ninth and [[Save (baseball)|saved]] the game for the Yankees on eight pitches for his second save of the series.<ref name=\"game4bref\"/>\n\n===Game 5===\n[[File:Chase Utley on March 11, 2007.jpg|thumb|right|200px|alt=A man in white pants, a red baseball jersey with \"Phillies\" on the chest, and a red batting helmet with \"P\" on it runs on a dirt surface.|Phillies second baseman Chase Utley, pictured during spring training in 2007, tied a World Series record with five home runs in the series.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Monday, November 2, 2009\n|Time=7:57{{nbsp}}pm (EST)\n|Location=Citizens Bank Park in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|Road=New York|RoadAbr=NYY\n|R1=1|R2=0|R3=0|R4=0|R5=1|R6=0|R7=0|R8=3|R9=1|RR=6|RH=10|RE=0\n|Home='''Philadelphia'''|HomeAbr=PHI\n|H1=3|H2=0|H3=3|H4=0|H5=0|H6=0|H7=2|H8=0|H9=X|HR=8|HH=9|HE=0\n|WP=[[Cliff Lee]] (2\u20130)|LP=[[A. J. Burnett]] (1\u20131)|SV=[[Ryan Madson]] (1)\n|RoadHR=|HomeHR=[[Chase Utley]] 2 (5), [[Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez]] (1)\n|}}\nThe Yankees replaced Melky Cabrera on their postseason roster with [[Ramiro Pe\u00f1a]] due to his injury in Game&nbsp;4, while Brett Gardner took Cabrera's place in [[center fielder|center field]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091102&content_id=7602252&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Yanks' Pena spells injured Melky on roster |accessdate=November 2, 2009|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 2, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091104235029/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091102&content_id=7602252&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 4, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> A. J. Burnett, the Yankees' Game&nbsp;2 starter, started Game&nbsp;5 on three days rest, one less than the Phillies' Cliff Lee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291102122&teams=new-york-yankees-vs-philadelphia-phillies |author=[[Associated Press]]|title=Utley's record-tying 5th World Series HR helps Phils cut Yanks lead to 3\u20132 |date=November 2, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> The Yankees scored first in the first inning, with Johnny Damon reaching base with a single and then scoring on a two-out double by Alex Rodriguez.<ref name=\"game5bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI200911020.shtml|title=November 2, 2009 World Series Game 5, Yankees at Phillies|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies responded in the bottom of the inning with a single by Jimmy Rollins, Shane Victorino reaching after being [[Hit by pitch|hit by a pitch]], and finally a three-run [[home run]] by Chase Utley to take the lead.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> The Phillies added to their lead in the third inning with Utley and Ryan Howard drawing walks followed by [[runs batted in|RBI]] singles by Jayson Werth and Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> With no outs in the inning, Burnett was relieved by David Robertson, who allowed another run to score on a Carlos Ruiz ground out.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/>\n\nRobertson held the Phillies scoreless for a second inning in the fourth.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Jorge Posada entered as a [[pinch hitter]] in the fifth inning for [[Jos\u00e9 Molina (baseball)|Jos\u00e9 Molina]] and grounded out.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> [[Eric Hinske]] then pinch hit for Robertson and walked, advanced to third on a [[Derek Jeter]] single, and scored on a ground out by Damon.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> [[Alfredo Aceves]] entered as the new Yankee pitcher in the bottom of the fifth.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> The first batter he faced, Jayson Werth, hit a deep drive to center field but it was caught for an out by Gardner, who collided with the outfield wall to complete the play.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Aceves completed the inning without a run scoring, inducing ground outs from Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez and Ruiz.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> [[Phil Coke]] relieved Aceves in the seventh inning and allowed two Phillies players to tie World Series records.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> First, Utley tied [[Reggie Jackson]]'s record for most home runs in a World Series with a home run, his fifth of the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4618248 |title=Utley ties Jackson with 5th HR |accessdate=November 12, 2009|author=[[Associated Press]]|date=November 3, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091106235928/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/news/story?id=4618248| archivedate=November 6, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Coke then [[Strikeout|struck out]] Howard, Howard's 12th strikeout in the series, tying [[Willie Wilson (baseball)|Willie Wilson]]'s record for most strikeouts in a World Series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/2009/11/04/2009-11-04_ryan_howard.html|title=Philadelphia Phillies hoping Ryan Howard can shake slump, pound New York Yankees |accessdate=November 5, 2009|last=Red|first=Christian|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=November 4, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091105105711/http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/2009/11/04/2009-11-04_ryan_howard.html| archivedate=November 5, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Finally, Coke was driven from the game after allowing another home run, this time to Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez, and was relieved by Phil Hughes.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/>\n\nVictorino was [[Defensive substitution|replaced defensively]] in the eighth inning by [[Ben Francisco]].<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Lee was driven from the game after allowing a single to Damon, followed by a double by Mark Teixeira, and then a double by Rodriguez that scored both runners.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Chan Ho Park relieved Lee and induced a ground out from Nick Swisher, which advanced Rodriguez to third base. Rodriguez scored on a [[sacrifice fly]] by [[Robinson Can\u00f3]].<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Ryan Madson entered in the ninth to close the game, allowing a double to Posada and a single to Hideki Matsui without recording an out.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Batting with men on first and third base, Jeter grounded into a [[double play]], allowing Posada to score but emptying the bases.<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Damon singled to bring Teixeira to bat as the potential tying run, but Madson struck him out to record his first World Series [[Save (baseball)|save]].<ref name=\"game5bref\"/> Members of the news media, such as [[Gene Wojciechowski]], were critical of the three-man [[starting rotation]] strategy following Game&nbsp;3,<ref name=\"woj3man\"/> and contended that Burnett's poor performance was caused by insufficient rest in between starts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/columns/story?columnist=wojciechowski_gene&id=4618452&sportCat=mlb |title=Short rest leads to Burnett's short start |date=November 3, 2009|first=Gene|last=Wojciechowski|authorlink=Gene Wojciechowski|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> However, Burnett had been successful up to this point in such situations, going 4\u20130 with a 2.33 ERA in four career starts on short rest (less than the normal four days between starts) before this game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=4614592&type=story|title=Burnett to face Lee on short rest |date=November 2, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|author=Associated Press |accessdate=July 30, 2010}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Game 6===\n[[File:Hideki Matsui in USA-7.jpg|right|upright|thumb|alt=A man in a grey baseball uniform and blue batting helmet looks to the right as he clenches a swung baseball bat behind him.|Yankees designated hitter Hideki Matsui, pictured here in the 2007 regular season, tied a World Series record for most RBIs in a single game and won the World Series MVP award.]]\n{{Linescore\n|Date=Wednesday, November 4, 2009\n|Time=7:57{{nbsp}}pm (EST)\n|Location=Yankee Stadium in Bronx, New York\n|Road=Philadelphia|RoadAbr=PHI\n|R1=0|R2=0|R3=1|R4=0|R5=0|R6=2|R7=0|R8=0|R9=0|RR=3|RH=6|RE=0\n|Home='''New York'''|HomeAbr=NYY\n|H1=0|H2=2|H3=2|H4=0|H5=3|H6=0|H7=0|H8=0|H9=X|HR=7|HH=8|HE=0\n|WP=[[Andy Pettitte]] (2\u20130)|LP=[[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]] (0\u20132) |SV=\n|RoadHR=[[Ryan Howard]] (1)|HomeHR=[[Hideki Matsui]] (3)\n|}}\nThis game was the first Game&nbsp;6 in a World Series since the [[2003 World Series]] six years earlier, the longest such gap in the history of the World Series.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mark|last=Newman|title=Six in the City: Where will this one rank?|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091103&content_id=7615844&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=November 4, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091107091303/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091103&content_id=7615844&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 7, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> [[Mary J. Blige]], a Bronx native, performed \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Brittany|last=Ghiroli|title=New York's Blige entertains with anthem|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620350&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=November 4, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091108214141/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620350&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 8, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Andy Pettitte started on three days rest, the third straight game in which the Yankees fielded a pitcher on short rest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291104110&teams=philadelphia-phillies-vs-new-york-yankees |author=[[Associated Press]]|title=Matsui's bat drives Yankees to 27th World Series crown |date=October 31, 2009|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> The Phillies started Pedro Mart\u00ednez, who called himself and opposing pitcher [[Andy Pettitte]] \"old goats\" and acknowledged that Red Sox fans were rooting for him: \"I know that they don't like the Yankees to win, not even in Nintendo games.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fullcount.weei.com/sports/boston/baseball/red-sox/2009/11/03/pedro-i-consider-myself-a-bostonian/|title=Pedro: 'I consider myself a Bostonian'|publisher=WEEI.com|date=November 3, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees scored first with an Alex Rodriguez walk opening the bottom of the second inning followed by a two-run home run by [[designated hitter]] Hideki Matsui.<ref name=\"game6bref\">{{cite web| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA200911040.shtml|title=November 4, 2009 World Series Game 6, Phillies at Yankees|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref> The Phillies quickly responded with a [[Triple (baseball)|triple]] by Carlos Ruiz who then scored on a [[sacrifice fly]] from Jimmy Rollins in the top of the third.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Matsui answered back, adding to the Yankees lead again with a single with the [[bases loaded]] in the bottom of the third, scoring Derek Jeter and Johnny Damon.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Damon, injured running the bases while scoring, was [[Defensive substitution|replaced defensively]] in the top of the fourth by [[Jerry Hairston Jr.]]<ref name=\"game6bref\"/>\n\n[[File:New York Yankees 2009 World Series Champions.jpg|thumb|left|225px|The Yankees celebrate their 7\u20133 win and the franchise's 27th World Series championship.|alt=Many men in white baseball uniforms and blue caps, some wearing blue jackets, stand near a dirt mound. Some are hugging each other.]]\nPhillies starter Pedro Mart\u00ednez was removed after allowing four runs in four innings, relieved in the fifth by Chad Durbin.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Durbin allowed a [[ground rule double]] to Jeter, who advanced to third on a [[sacrifice bunt]] by Hairston and scored on a single by Mark Teixeira.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Durbin then hit Rodriguez with a pitch and was relieved by J.&nbsp;A. Happ after recording just one out.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Happ allowed a two-run double to Matsui, his fifth and sixth [[Runs batted in|RBI]] of the game, which tied a World Series record for most RBI in a single game set by [[Bobby Richardson]] in the [[1960 World Series]].<ref name=\"statsui\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620234&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Statsui: MVP delivers jaw-dropping numbers|first=Anthony|last=DiComo|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=January 12, 2010|date=November 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Phillies made the game closer in the top of the sixth inning, as Chase Utley drew a walk and Ryan Howard followed him with a two-run home run, bringing the score to 7\u20133.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> After Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez hit a double into right field, Joba Chamberlain relieved Andy Pettitte and closed the sixth without allowing the Phillies to score.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Chan Ho Park came in for Happ, ending any Yankees threat that inning.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Chamberlain was relieved by D\u00e1maso Marte in the top of the seventh after allowing two baserunners, but Marte struck out Utley to end the inning scoreless.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> After Park allowed a single to Rodriguez, [[Scott Eyre]] replaced him. Eyre allowed Rodriguez to steal second and [[Intentional walk|intentionally walked]] Jorge Posada but escaped the inning without allowing a run.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/>\n\nMarte recorded one out, a strikeout of Howard, in the top of the eighth inning.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> With it Howard set a new World Series record for most strikeouts by a hitter in a single series with a total of 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7616316&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Howard sets Series record for strikeouts |accessdate=November 5, 2009|last=Bowman|first=Mark|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091108104133/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7616316&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=November 8, 2009<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> After the out, Marte was relieved by Yankees [[Closing pitcher|closer]] Mariano Rivera in a non-[[Save (baseball)|save]] situation.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Rivera allowed a double to Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez, but no runs, in the eighth.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> After retiring the first two batters in the eighth, Eyre gave way to Ryan Madson, who allowed a single to Jeter before ending the bottom of the eighth inning.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Matt Stairs led off the ninth as a [[pinch hitter]], but lined out. Ruiz worked a walk from Rivera, but successive outs by Rollins and Victorino ended the game 7\u20133 to clinch the World Series for the Yankees.<ref name=\"game6bref\"/> Pettitte added to his own record for most playoff wins, bringing his career total to 18.<ref name=\"APYankswin\">{{cite web | author = [[Associated Press]] | work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures| title = Matsui's bat drives Yankees to 27th World Series crown | date =November 5, 2009| url = http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=291104110| accessdate =December 28, 2009}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Composite line score==\n2009 World Series '''(4\u20132)''': '''[[2009 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] (AL)''' beat [[2009 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]] (NL).\n{{Linescore\n|Road=Philadelphia Phillies\n|R1=4|R2=4|R3=5|R4=1|R5=0|R6=4|R7=3|R8=3|R9=3|RR=27|RH=44|RE=2\n|Home='''New York Yankees'''\n|H1=3|H2=2|H3=2|H4=3|H5=9|H6=2|H7=2|H8=4|H9=5|HR=32|HH=49|HE=2\n|TotalAttendance=289,087 |AveAttendance=48,181\n|WinPlayerShare=$350,029.99<ref name=\"wssharesrevised\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4960581|title=Yanks rank behind '08 Phillies|work=Associated Press|date=March 2, 2010|accessdate=November 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"wssharesrevisedtsn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2010-03-03/list-2009-world-series-shares|title=List of 2009 World Series shares|work=Associated Press|date=March 3, 2010|accessdate=November 8, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101110064433/http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2010-03-03/list-2009-world-series-shares|archivedate=November 10, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|LosePlayerShare=$265,357.50<ref name=\"wsshares\">{{cite news|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091130&content_id=7730198&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp|title=Yanks awarded record postseason shares|last=Gonzalez|first=Alden|work=MLB.com|date=November 30, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Broadcasting==\nFor the tenth consecutive year in the United States, [[Major League Baseball on Fox|Fox Sports]] televised the Series. [[Joe Buck]] called [[sports commentary|play-by-play]] and [[Tim McCarver]] provided [[Color commentator|analysis]]. The Series was also broadcast on [[Major League Baseball on ESPN Radio|ESPN Radio]], with [[Jon Miller]] and [[Joe Morgan]] calling the action. [[Fox Sports en Espa\u00f1ol]] also broadcast the Series for the US [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking audience.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/fox-sports-en-espanol-announces-exclusive-spanish-language-programming-for-the-2009-world-series-with-pre---postgame-analysis-by-chicago-white-sox-manager-ozzie-guillen-66403607.html|title=Fox Sports en Espanol Announces Exclusive Spanish-Language Programming For The 2009 World Series|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> The [[flagship station|flagship]] radio stations of the respective teams broadcast all Series games with their local announcers. In Philadelphia, [[WPHT]] carried the Phillies' English-language broadcasts, with [[Scott Franzke]], [[Larry Andersen]], [[Tom McCarthy (broadcaster)|Tom McCarthy]], [[Gary Matthews]], and [[Chris Wheeler]] announcing, while [[WDAS (AM)|WUBA]] aired the team's Spanish broadcasts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.philly.com/2009-11-04/sports/24987832_1_ryan-howard-hideki-matsui-johnny-damon|title=Phillies\u2013Yankees: World Series Game 6 preview|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=November 4, 2009|first=Marcus|last=Hayes|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> In New York, [[WCBS-AM]] carried the Yankees' English broadcasts with [[John Sterling (sportscaster)|John Sterling]] and [[Suzyn Waldman]] announcing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20091028/SPORTS/910280350/-1/rss02|title=World Series: How to follow the Yankees on TV, radio|work=[[Times Herald-Record]]|date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> This broadcast made Waldman the first woman to announce a World Series game on radio.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4604021&campaign=rss&source=MLBHeadlines | title=Yankees honor Waldman before Game 1 | author=[[Associated Press]] | work=[[ESPN.com]] | publisher = ESPN Internet Ventures |date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> [[XM Satellite Radio]] offered multiple feeds of each game to its subscribers.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://investor.sirius.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=414472|title=SIRIUS XM Radio Announces Extensive MLB Postseason Coverage|publisher=[[PR Newswire]] via xmradio.com|date=October 7, 2009|accessdate=February 24, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720065449/http://investor.sirius.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=414472|archivedate=July 20, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Ratings==\nTelevision ratings for the 2009 World Series were excellent. Game 1 attracted 19.5 million viewers, second only to the opening of the [[2004 World Series]] for a series opener since 2000 and 29% higher than 2008's opening game.<ref name=\"game1ratingsa\">{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091030&content_id=7580380&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy&partnerId=rss_nyy |title=Buzz growing as Series has classic feel |work=[[MLB.com]] |publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|last=Newman |first=Mark |date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"game1tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/10/29/world-series-game-1-up-29-over-2008-second-highest-game-1-of-decade/32013 |title=World Series Game 1 up 29% over 2008; Second highest game 1 of decade|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref> Game 4 produced the highest total viewership of the series with 22.8 million viewers, the highest for any World Series game since 2004 and the highest for a \"non-decisive Game 4\" since 2001.<ref name=\"game4tratings\"/> At 11.7 overall, the 2009 World Series was at the time the highest rated World Series since 2004 and the one of the only World Series to average double digits since 2007, the other being the [[2016 World Series]].<ref>[[World Series television ratings]]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Game !! [[Nielsen ratings|Ratings]]<br/>(households) !! [[Share (television)|Share]]<br/>(households) !! American audience<br/>(in millions)\n|-\n! 1<ref name=\"game1tratings\"/>\n| 11.9 || 19 || 19.5\n|-\n! 2<ref name=\"game2tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/10/30/world-series-game-2-dominates-prime-time-audience-48-better-than-08-gm-2/32108 |title=World Series Game 2 Dominates Prime Time; Audience +48% Better than '08 Gm. 2|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 11.7 || 19 || 18.9\n|-\n! 3<ref name=\"game3tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/11/01/world-series-game-3-averages-15-4-million-viewers-after-80-minute-halloween-rain-delay/32211 |title=World Series game 3 averages 15.4 million viewers after 80 minute Halloween rain delay|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=November 1, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 9.1 || 18 || 15.4\n|-\n! 4<ref name=\"game4tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/11/02/world-series-game-four-nielsen-ratings-2009-world-series-remains-dominant-force-in-prime-time/32326 |title=World Series Game Four Nielsen Ratings: 2009 World Series Remains Dominant Force in Prime Time|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 13.5 || 22 || 22.8\n|-\n! 5<ref name=\"game5tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/11/03/world-series-game-5-delivers-another-home-run-for-fox/32563 |title=World Series Game 5 Delivers Another Home Run For FOX|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=November 3, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 10.6 || 16 || 17.1\n|-\n! 6<ref name=\"game6tratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/11/05/2009-world-series-posts-biggest-year-to-year-growth-in-history/32759 |title=2009 World Series posts biggest year-to-year growth in history|work=Fox Sports|publisher=TV By the Numbers |date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n| 13.4 || 22 || 22.3\n|}\n\n==Impact and aftermath==\nMany players with both teams won awards for their performances during the 2009 season. Teixeira and Jeter each won a [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]] and [[Silver Slugger Award]]; Jimmy Rollins and Shane Victorino won Gold Gloves, as well; and Chase Utley won a Silver Slugger Award.<ref name=\"09awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/awards/y2009/index.jsp|title=2009 MLB Awards|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=January 12, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119050111/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/awards/y2009/index.jsp| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Rivera was named the 2009 [[DHL Delivery Man of the Year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091014&content_id=7455952&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy|title=Mariano wins Delivery Man of Year Award|first=Anthony|last=DiComo|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 14, 2009|accessdate=January 12, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119061808/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091014&content_id=7455952&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> as well as ''[[Sporting News]]''{{'}} [[Sporting News#Pro Athlete of the Year|Pro Athlete of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2009-12-17/2009-sporting-news-pro-athlete-year-mariano-rivera-yankees-closer | title = 2009 Sporting News Pro Athlete of the Year: Mariano Rivera, Yankees closer | work = [[Sporting News]] | first = Ken | last = Bradley | date = December 17, 2009 | accessdate = December 17, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131005011451/http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2009-12-17/2009-sporting-news-pro-athlete-year-mariano-rivera-yankees-closer | archive-date = October 5, 2013 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Along with the [[Hank Aaron Award]] announced before Game&nbsp;4, Jeter won the [[Roberto Clemente Award]] and was named ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''{{'}}s [[Sportsman of the Year]] for 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091029&content_id=7573566&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Jeter takes home Clemente Award|first=Mark|last=Newman|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=January 12, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119120504/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091029&content_id=7573566&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/magazine/specials/sportsman/2009/11/25/derek.jeter/index.html |title=Sports Illustrated names Derek Jeter Sportsman of the Year |work=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=November 30, 2009 |accessdate=January 12, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104232602/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/magazine/specials/sportsman/2009/11/25/derek.jeter/index.html |archivedate=January 4, 2010 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Matsui won the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP]] for his play, becoming the first Japanese player and first full-time [[designated hitter]] to win the award.<ref name=\"statsui\"/><ref>{{cite news| author = [[Associated Press]] | title = Matsui Becomes 1st Japanese-Born World Series MVP | work=[[The New York Times]] | date =November 5, 2009 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2009/11/05/sports/AP-BBO-World-Series-MVP.html | accessdate =November 5, 2009}}</ref> Several items related to the series were sent to the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]] including bats from Jeter and Matsui; caps from Rivera, Lee, and Pettitte; and Johnny Damon's [[Cleat (shoe)|cleats]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7621018&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Cooperstown to capture Series relics|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=March 16, 2010|date=November 5, 2009|first=Tim|last=Britton}}</ref>\n\nMatsui also joined [[Minnesota Twins]] radio analyst [[Dan Gladden]] as members from the [[1994 Japan Series|1994 world championship]] [[Yomiuri Giants]] team as players who have won championships in North America and Japan.\nThis World Series title for the Yankees was their second one during the 2000's decade. Even though the Boston Red Sox had also won the World Series twice in this decade, the Yankees were the only team to have appeared in the World Series four (4) times during the 2000's. Therefore, the Yankees can be referred to as the \"Team of 2000's\". \n\n===Yankees===\n[[File:CC Sabathia Mark Teixeira World Series parade 2009.jpg|thumb|CC Sabathia and Mark Teixeira during the victory parade|alt=A black man on the left wearing a white T-shirt and dark jacket smiles holding a sign, while a white man on the right wearing a blue sweatshirt which reads \"Champions\" points upwards. White streamers hang from a building in the background.]]\n[[File:US Navy 091106-N-6525D-001 Musician 3rd Class Laura Carey sings the National Anthem at the conclusion of the New York Yankees ticker-tape parade at New York City Hall.jpg|thumb|left|Ticker-tape parade at [[New York City Hall]]|alt=A woman in an American Navy uniform stands before a microphone with several people behind her on stage. The stage is in front of a building with a sign that reads \"#27!\".]]\n[[File:2009 World Series Champions and Barack Obama.jpg|thumb|President [[Barack Obama]] meets with the 2009 World Series champion New York Yankees at the White House.|alt=Two men in dark suits stand in front of a crowd in the background and behind a podium in the foreground with the Seal of the President of the United States on it. The two men are holding a white jersey with pinstripes and the number 27 on it.]]\nThe series win brought the Yankees' franchise championship total to 27,<ref name=\"APYankswin\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/05/sports/baseball/05series.html?_r=1&ref=global|title=Back on Top, Yankees Add a 27th Title | last=Kepner | first=Tyler |date=November 5, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=November 5, 2009}}</ref> more than any other North American professional sports franchise. This championship came in the Yankees' first year in their new stadium. They had also won the [[1923 World Series]], the opening year of the previous Yankee Stadium.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/news?slug=ge-yankeesclinch110409|title=Yankees christen new stadium with a title|date=November 4, 2009|first=Gordon|last=Edes|publisher=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> The victory was noted by some sportswriters as a personal success for Alex Rodriguez, winning his first championship and succeeding in the playoffs where some had previously claimed he was a \"choker and a loser\".<ref name=\"bryantarod\">{{cite web|title=Postseason had many defining moments |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=bryant_howard&id=4628594 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |first=Howard |last=Bryant |date=November 6, 2009 |accessdate=December 28, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118154227/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=bryant_howard&id=4628594 |archivedate=November 18, 2009 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"caplearod\">{{cite web |title=A-Rod finally wins that elusive title|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/columns/story?columnist=caple_jim&id=4624978|work=[[ESPN.com]]|first=Jim|last=Caple|date=November 4, 2009|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"DiComoARod\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091105&content_id=7624852&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Humbled A-Rod soaks in first championship|first=Anthony|last=DiComo|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=December 28, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119132950/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091105&content_id=7624852&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Prior to this series, Rodriguez had appeared in 2,166 regular season games without a World Series appearance, then the second-most among active players to [[Ken Griffey Jr.]]<ref name=\"bryantarod\"/><ref name=\"DiComoARod\"/>\n\nThe Yankees' victory was credited to a number of different sources.<ref name=\"spreadclues\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7621016&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Start spreadin' the clues: Why Yanks won|first=Jenifer|last=Langosch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref> Many players drew praise for their performances, including Series MVP Hideki Matsui;<ref name=\"statsui\"/> free agents signed the previous offseason including Mark Teixeira, CC Sabathia, and A. J. Burnett;<ref name=\"huffingtonafter\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/11/04/yankees-win-world-series_n_346445.html|title=Yankees Win World Series: New York Beats Phillies For Record 27th Championship|first=Mike|last=Fitzpatrick|work=The Huffington Post|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref> and the so-called \"[[Core Four]]\" of Derek Jeter, Mariano Rivera, Andy Pettitte, and Jorge Posada, who had all played a large role in the Yankees' past success in the 1990s.<ref name=\"sixfivefour\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620796&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Six games, five rings, four Yankees|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"timescore\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/26/sports/26anderson.html|title=Sports of the Times; From Yanks' Core To Pacquiao, Plenty of Cheers|first=Dave|last=Anderson|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 29, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"pettitefive\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620800&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Pettitte relishes fifth championship ring|first=Thomas|last=Boorstein|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119133049/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7620800&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Manager Joe Girardi was also credited for his management of the team,<ref name=\"girardi\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091105&content_id=7625028&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Girardi leads Yankees to ultimate goal|first=Thomas|last=Boorstein|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119132936/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091105&content_id=7625028&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> particularly in his decision to use only three starting pitchers in the Yankees postseason [[starting rotation]].<ref name=\"3manpt2\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7621188&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|title=In the end, Girardi's pitching plan pays off|first=Jennifer|last=Langosch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119085954/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7621188&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy| archivedate=January 19, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> The Yankees were the first team to use only three starters in a World Series since the [[1998 San Diego Padres season|San Diego Padres]] in the [[1998 World Series|1998 Series]].<ref name=\"batsblog\"/>\n\nSeveral members of the Yankees franchise dedicated the World Series in part to team owner George Steinbrenner, who had recently stepped back from his once prominent position with the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7616200&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=George, this one is for you|first=Barry|last=Bloom|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=January 12, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100119132735/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091104&content_id=7616200&vkey=ps2009news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate= January 19, 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Steinbrenner died on the day of the [[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] the following season at the age of 80.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/14/sports/baseball/14steinbrenner.html?_r=2&sq=steinbrenner&st=cse&scp=2&pagewanted=print|title=GEORGE STEINBRENNER, 1930\u20132010; A Legacy of Championships From the Man Who Hated to Lose|first=Richard|last=Goldstein|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|page=A1 | date=July 13, 2010|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> On November 6, a victory parade took place for the Yankees in the \"[[Canyon of Heroes]]\" in [[Manhattan]], New York City.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/idCATRE5A556L20091106|title=NY Yankees victory parade draws thousands of fans|date=November 6, 2009|agency=Reuters|accessdate=November 21, 2009|first=Michelle|last=Nicholls}}</ref> The Yankees sent a group of players, coach [[Tony Pe\u00f1a]], and team Senior Vice President [[Felix Lopez (businessman)|Felix Lopez]] with the Commissioner's Trophy to the [[Dominican Republic]] in early January 2010 to meet with President [[Leonel Fern\u00e1ndez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidencia.gob.do/app/article.aspx?id=11838|title=Presidente Fern\u00e1ndez recibe a ejecutivos y jugadores de los Yankees de Nueva York|language=Spanish|publisher=Presidency of the Dominican Republic|date=January 8, 2010|accessdate=January 11, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725193507/http://www.presidencia.gob.do/app/article.aspx?id=11838|archivedate=July 25, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100108&content_id=7892702&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Yanks, trophy tour Dominican Republic|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|date=January 7, 2010|accessdate=January 11, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100115113930/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100108&content_id=7892702&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| archivedate=January 15, 2010<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref> Most of the 2009 Yankees received their [[championship rings]] on Opening Day the next season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-04-13/sports/27061526_1_rings-balfour-college-style|title=New York Yankees set for 2010 Opening Day with World Series rings in hand |accessdate=February 27, 2011|last=Bondy|first=Filip|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=April 13, 2010}}</ref> Matsui was on the Angels in 2010 and when the Angels played their first series of the season in the Bronx, the Yankees home opener, they presented him with his ring.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeter plays ring prank on Matsui|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/los-angeles/mlb/news/story?id=5083131|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 13, 2010|accessdate=February 27, 2011}}</ref> They also visited U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] in the [[White House]] in April 2010, presenting him with a signed jersey.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama hosts Yankees at White House|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/news/story?id=5137815|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 26, 2010|accessdate=February 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees returned to the playoffs the following season, as the [[Major League Baseball wild card|wild card]]. They lost to the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in the [[2010 American League Championship Series|2010 ALCS]]; which included an 8-0 shutout in Yankee Stadium by former Phillie ace Cliff Lee; it was Lee's seventh straight postseason win which included three victories against the Yankees (two as a Phillie in the 2009 World Series, and in 2010 during the ALCS).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/recap?gid=301022113&print=1|title=Rangers headed to World Series for first time|date=October 22, 2010|first=Stephen|last=Hawkins|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Phillies===\nFollowing Game&nbsp;4, after the Yankees took a 3\u20131 series lead, ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' accidentally printed a three-quarters-page [[Macy's]] advertisement congratulating the Phillies for winning the World Series, along with a picture of a Phillies championship T-shirt. The newspaper subsequently apologized for the mistake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=4616770&type=story|title = Newspaper apologizes for incorrect ad|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|author=Associated Press|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=March 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nLee Jenkins of ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' attributed Philadelphia's loss to a lack of pitching depth, noting that three different Yankees starters managed to win games in the series, while only Cliff Lee won games for the Phillies. The Phillies' 2008 postseason star pitchers, starter Cole Hamels and closer Brad Lidge, struggled in their only appearances of the 2009 World Series. The Phillies bullpen which did well in the NLCS performed poorly in the World Series, allowing seven runs in just 11 2/3 innings with a 5.40 ERA.<ref name=\"phildepth\">{{cite news|url=http://si.printthis.clickability.com/pt/cpt?action=cpt&title=Lack+of+starting+pitching+depth+doomed+Philadelphia+Phillies+-+Lee+Jenkins+-+SI.com&expire=&urlID=414147432&fb=Y&url=http%3A%2F%2Fsportsillustrated.cnn.com%2F2009%2Fwriters%2Flee_jenkins%2F11%2F05%2Fpedro.martinez%2Findex.html&partnerID=2356|title=Lack of pitching depth cost Phillies |last=Jenkins|first=Lee |date=November 5, 2009|work=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref> Jorge Arangure Jr. of ESPN partially attributed the Phillies' loss to their lack of offensive production, citing the team's .227 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] in the World Series. Only Chase Utley performed well with 5 home runs and 22 of the Phillies' 90 bases, while Shane Victorino and Jimmy Rollins struggled at the plate, and Ryan Howard struck out a record 13 times in the World Series after his NLCS MVP performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=4624839&type=story|title=Five reasons the Phillies didn't repeat|last=Arangure|first=Jorge Jr.|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBefore the start of the 2010 season, the Phillies traded away their 2009 postseason ace pitcher Cliff Lee. The Phillies posted the league's best record in 2010, and returned to the playoffs where they lost to the eventual champions the [[2010 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]] in the [[2010 National League Championship Series|NLCS]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Giants Punch Out Phillies, Looking|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/24/sports/baseball/24nlcs.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print|date=October 24, 2010|first=David|last=Waldstein|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=January 23, 2011|page=SP1}}</ref>\n\n===David Paterson ticket scandal===\nAmong those in attendance during Game&nbsp;1 was [[List of Governors of New York|New York Governor]] [[David Paterson]], whose party had five tickets behind home plate.  On March 3, 2010, the New York Commission on Public Integrity found that Paterson had violated state laws concerning gifts to public officials, and that he [[perjury|lied under oath]] to the commission about his intent to pay for the tickets.<ref name=\"WSJSaul\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703862704575099663280532160?mod=WSJ_hpp_MIDDLENexttoWhatsNewsThird|title=Paterson Faulted For Ethics Slip |last=Saul|first=Michael Howard|date=March 4, 2010|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=March 4, 2010}}</ref> The commission further found that Paterson used his position to solicit and receive the five tickets\u2014valued at US$425 each\u2014free of charge from the Yankees,<ref name=\"NYTPeters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/04/nyregion/04paterson.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print|title=Paterson's Ethics Breach Is Turned Over to Prosecutors|last=Confessore|first=Nicholas|last2=Peters|first2=Jeremy W.|date=March 3, 2010|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 4, 2010}}</ref> that he had never intended to pay for the tickets despite testimony to the contrary, and that he or a person acting on his behalf wrote a backdated check to pay for them only after scrutiny in the case arose.<ref name=\"WSJSaul\" /><ref name=\"NYTPeters\" /> The Commission ultimately fined Paterson $62,125 for his actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/20/gov-paterson-fined-62125-for-taking-world-series-tickets/|title=Governor Paterson Fined Over World Series Tickets|last=Halbfinger|first=David|date=December 20, 2010|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 2, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110112093921/http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/20/gov-paterson-fined-62125-for-taking-world-series-tickets/| archivedate=January 12, 2011<!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n* [[2009 Asia Series]]\n* [[2009 Japan Series]]\n* [[2009 Korean Series]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|2009 World Series}}\n{{WSExtLinks|year=2009}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100119032943/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/ps/y2009]\n* [http://espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2009/matchup/_/teams/phillies-yankees 2009 World Series] at ''[http://espn.go.com/ ESPN.com]''\n* [http://mlb.mlb.com/nyy/history/championship09.jsp New York Yankees championship page]\n\n{{2009 MLB Playoffs navbox}}\n{{World Series}}\n{{2009 MLB season by team}}\n{{Major League Baseball on Fox}}\n{{Major League Baseball on ESPN Radio}}\n{{2009 New York Yankees}}\n{{New York Yankees}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2009 World Series}}\n[[Category:World Series]]\n[[Category:2009 Major League Baseball season|World Series]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies postseason]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees postseason]]\n[[Category:2009 in sports in New York City|World Series]]\n[[Category:2009 in sports in Pennsylvania|World Series]