ghts of the Pink Table/Music Mix Up|publisher=KET|accessdate=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|8|7}}\n|ProdCode        = 134\n|LineColor       = FFC0CB\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 34\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 34\n|Title           = Whale of a Song/Pinkabubbles\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ket.org/episode/PIPE%20%20000136|title=Whale of a Song/Pinkabubbles|publisher=KET|accessdate=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|8|8}}\n|ProdCode        = 136\n|LineColor       = FFC0CB\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 35\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 35\n|Title           = Amazing Sled Run/Frost Fairy\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ket.org/episode/PIPE%20%20000135|title=Amazing Sled Run/Frost Fairy|publisher=KET|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|2}}\n|ProdCode        = 135\n|LineColor       = FFC0CB\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 36\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 36\n|Title           = Drawing Noses/Pinkalicious On Ice\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ket.org/episode/PIPE%20%20000129|title=Drawing Noses/Pinkalicious On Ice|publisher=KET|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|3}}\n|ProdCode        = 129\n|LineColor       = FFC0CB\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 37\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 37\n|Title           = A Real Hoot/Amazing Tower of Igloos\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ket.org/episode/PIPE%20%20000138|title=A Real Hoot/Amazing Tower of Igloos|publisher=KET|accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|4}}\n|ProdCode        = 138\n|LineColor       = FFC0CB\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 38\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 38\n|Title           = The Legend of Pinkfoot/Flossie the Mossling\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ket.org/episode/PIPE%20%20000137|title=The Legend of Pinkfoot/Flossie the Mossling|publisher=KET|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|5}}\n|ProdCode        = 137\n|LineColor       = FFC0CB\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 2 (2020)===\n{{Episode table|background=#FFFF00|total_width=90|overall=|season=|title=|airdate=|prodcode=|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 39\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n|Title           = A Birthday Party for Kendra/Norman Plans A Playdate\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://schedule.wttw.com/episodes/497011/Pinkalicious--and-ampPeterrific/A-Birthday-Party-for-Kendra/Norman-Plans-A-Playdate/|title=A Birthday Party for Kendra/Norman Plans A Playdate|publisher=[[WTTW]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|30}}\n|ProdCode        = 201\n|LineColor       = FFFF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 40\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n|Title           = Aqualicious/Sing in the Spring\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://schedule.wttw.com/episodes/497012/Pinkalicious--and-ampPeterrific/Aqualicious/Sing-in-the-Spring/|title=Aqualicious/Sing in the Spring|publisher=[[WTTW]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|31}}\n|ProdCode        = 202\n|LineColor       = FFFF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 41\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n|Title           = Mr. Socko/A Pinkapurrfect Pet\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://schedule.wttw.com/episodes/497013/Pinkalicious--and-ampPeterrific/Mr-Socko/A-Pinkapurrfect-Pet/|title=Mr. Socko/A Pinkapurrfect Pet|publisher=[[WTTW]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|1}}\n|ProdCode        = 203\n|LineColor       = FFFF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 42\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n|Title           = Yodelahee Goat/Pink Mascot\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://schedule.wttw.com/episodes/497014/Pinkalicious--and-ampPeterrific/Yodelahee-Goat/Pink-Mascot/|title=Yodelahee Goat/Pink Mascot|publisher=[[WTTW]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|2}}\n|ProdCode        = 204\n|LineColor       = FFFF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 43\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n|Title           = The Sparkle Kart/The Pinkville Merry-Go-Round\n|RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://schedule.wttw.com/episodes/497015/Pinkalicious--and-ampPeterrific/The-Sparkle-Kart/The-Pinkville-MerryGoRound/|title=The Sparkle Kart/The Pinkville Merry-Go-Round|publisher=[[WTTW]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|3}}\n|ProdCode        = 205\n|LineColor       = FFFF00\n}}\n}}\n\n==Special==\nA TV special entitled ''A Pinkaperfect Birthday'' aired on August 5, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pinkalicious & Peterrific: A Pinkaperfect Birthday |url=https://www.ket.org/episode/PIPB%20%20000000/ |website=KET |accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref> In the special, Pinkalicious receives a wand that makes everything in Pinkville pink, but not everyone loved what she did. So she and Peter go on quest to find out how to use the wand to turn everything back to normal.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{WGBH}}\n{{PBS Kids shows}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pinkalicious and Peterrific}}\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2018 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2018 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:American preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:American television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:American television series with live action and animation]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about siblings]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about families]]\n[[Category:British children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:British flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:British preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:British television programmes based on children's books]]\n[[Category:British television series with live action and animation]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:PBS Kids shows]]\n[[Category:PBS original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by WGBH]]\n", "name_user": "2601:240:e081:4880:41af:e123:75d5:3b08", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinkalicious_%26_Peterrific"}
{"title_page": "Lattice corneal dystrophy", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Lattice corneal dystrophy type\n| synonyms        =  '''Biber-Haab-Dimmer dystrophy'''\n| image           = Lattice corneal dystrophy type 1.JPEG\n| caption         = A network of thick linear corneal opacities in patient with a variant of LCD1 (LCD type III) due to a homozygous p. Leu527Arg mutation in the [[TGFBI]] gene\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Lattice corneal dystrophy type''',  is a rare form of [[corneal dystrophy]]. It has no systemic manifestations, unlike the other type of the dystrophy, Lattice corneal dystrophy type II. Lattice corneal dystrophy was first described by Swiss [[ophthalmologist]] Hugo Biber in 1890.<ref name=\"Biber1890\">H. Biber: \u00dcber einige seltenere Hornhauterkrankungen. Z\u00fcrich, 1890. Inaugural Dissertation, Zurich, 1890. Cited by O. Haab: Die gittrige Keratitis.</ref>\n\nLattice dystrophy gets its name from an accumulation of [[Amyloidosis|amyloid]] deposits, or abnormal protein fibers, throughout the middle and anterior stroma.\n\n== Presentation ==\nFilamentous opacities appear in the [[cornea]] with intertwining delicate branching processes. During an eye examination, the doctor sees these deposits in the stroma as clear, comma-shaped overlapping dots and branching filaments, creating a lattice effect. Over time, the lattice lines will grow opaque and involve more of the stroma. They will also gradually converge, giving the cornea a cloudiness that may also reduce vision. The disease is bilateral, usually noted before the end of the first decade of life. Although lattice dystrophy can occur at any time in life, the condition usually arises in children between the ages of two and seven.\n\nIn some people, these abnormal protein fibers can accumulate under the cornea's outer layer\u2014the epithelium. This can cause [[Recurrent corneal erosion|erosion of the epithelium]]. This condition is known as recurrent epithelial erosion. These erosions alter the cornea's normal curvature, resulting in temporary vision problems, and expose the nerves that line the cornea, causing severe pain. Even the involuntary act of blinking can be painful.\n\nIn systemic cases, kidney failure, heart failure and neuropathy such as facial nerve palsy, laxity of the skin may be noted.<ref name=omim2>{{OMIM|105120}}</ref>\n\n== Genetics ==\n[[File:Lattice corneal dystrophy type II cornea cut.jpg|thumb|250 px|Lattice corneal dystrophy type II. Black and white light micrograph showing deposits of amyloid in cornea. Congo red stain.]]\n[[File:Lattice corneal dystrophy type II diagram.gif|thumb|240 px|Diagram depicting gelsolin and the amyloid protein derived from it because of mutations in codon]]\n\nLattice corneal dystrophy has two types:<ref name=omim>{{OMIM|122200}}</ref>\n\n* type I: with no systemic association. It is caused by mutations in [[TGFBI]] gene encoding keratoepithelin, which maps to chromosome 5q.\n* type II or [[Familial Amyloidosis, Finnish Type|Finnish type amyloidosis]]: associated with manifestations of systemic amyloidosis due to accumulation of [[gelsolin]].<ref name=\"pmid1322359\">{{cite journal |vauthors=de la Chapelle A, Kere J, Sack GH, Tolvanen R, Maury CP |title=Familial amyloidosis, Finnish type: G654----a mutation of the gelsolin gene in Finnish families and an unrelated American family |journal=Genomics |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=898\u2013901 |date=July 1992 |pmid=1322359 |doi= 10.1016/0888-7543(92)90182-R}}</ref> Associated conditions may include [[cutis laxa]]<ref name=\"pmid15727635\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kiuru-Enari S, Keski-Oja J, Haltia M |title=Cutis laxa in hereditary gelsolin amyloidosis |journal=Br. J. Dermatol. |volume=152 |issue=2 |pages=250\u20137 |date=February 2005 |pmid=15727635 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2133.2004.06276.x }}</ref> and [[ataxia]].<ref name=\"pmid17453628\">{{cite journal |author=Tanskanen M |title=Severe ataxia with neuropathy in hereditary gelsolin amyloidosis: a case report |journal=Amyloid |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=89\u201395 |date=March 2007 |pmid=17453628 |doi=10.1080/13506120601116393 |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Paetau A |author3=Salonen O |display-authors=3 |last4=Salmi |first4=Tapani |last5=Lamminen |first5=Antti |last6=Lindsberg |first6=Perttu |last7=Somer |first7=Hannu |last8=Kiuru-Enari |first8=Sari }}</ref>\n* type III is also described which has an onset at age 70 to 90 years and is not associated with systemic amyloidosis.<ref name=omim />\n\n==Diagnosis==\n{{Empty section|date=April 2018}}\nIn the examination of biomicroscopy, it appears as branches spread on the corneal stroma in the appearance of ghost vessels. diagnosis can also be confirmed with anterior segment OCT (visante OCT ,spetral domain OCT).The interwoven linear opaque filaments have some resemblance to NERVES, but may not be observed in all affected members of families with the condition. Recurrent corneal erosions may precede the corneal opacities and even appear in individuals lacking recognizable stromal disease. Amyloid deposits are found throughout the corneal stroma. Linear and other shaped opaque areas accumulate particularly within the central corneal stroma, while the peripheral cornea remains relatively transparent.\n\n== Treatment ==\nIn case of corneal erosion, a doctor may prescribe eye drops and ointments to reduce the friction on the eroded cornea. In some cases, an eye patch may be used to immobilize the eyelids. With effective care, these erosions usually heal within three to seven days, although occasional sensations of pain may occur for the next six-to-eight weeks. As patients with LCD suffer with dry eyes as a result of erosion, a new technique involving the insertion of [[punctal plug]]s (both upper and lower) can reduce the amount of drops used a day, aiding ocular stability.\n\nBy about age 40, some people with lattice dystrophy will have scarring under the epithelium, resulting in a haze on the cornea that can greatly obscure vision. In this case, a [[corneal transplantation]] may be needed. There have been many cases in which teenage patients have had the procedure, which accounts for the change in severity of the condition from person to person.\n\nAlthough people with lattice dystrophy have an excellent chance for a successful [[corneal transplantation]], the disease may also arise in the donor cornea in as little as three years. In one study, about half of the transplant patients with lattice dystrophy had a recurrence of the disease between two and 26 years after the operation. Of these, 15 percent required a second corneal transplant. Early lattice and recurrent lattice arising in the donor cornea responds well to treatment with the excimer laser.\n\nPhototherapeutic keratectomy (PTK) using [Excimer laser] can restore and preserve useful visual function for a significant period of time in patients with anterior corneal dystrophies.<ref name=omim />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|H|18|5|h|15}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|371.54}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = 122200\n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = article\n| eMedicineTopic  = 1193793\n| MeshID          = \n| ICD10CM         = {{ICD10CM|H18.54}}\n}}\n<!--unused refs *Maury CPJ, Alli K, Baumann M ( January 1990) Finnish hereditary amyloidosis - amino acid sequence homology between the amyloid fibril protein and human plasma gelsolin. FEBS Letters  vol 260, pp 85\u201387 (1990)\n*Maury CPJ, Kere J, Tolvanen  R et al. ( Dec 1990) Finnish hereditary amyloidosis is caused by a single nucleotide substitution in the gelsolin gene. FEBS Letters vol 276, pp.&nbsp;75\u201377 (1990)\n*{{cite book|author1=Emmett T. Cunningham |author2=Paul Riordan-Eva |title=Vaughan & Asbury's general ophthalmology.|publisher=McGraw-Hill Medical|isbn=978-0071634205|edition=18th}}-->\n\n{{Human corneal dystrophy}}\n\n[[Category:Disorders of sclera and cornea]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Lattice corneal dystrophy type\n| synonyms        =  '''Biber-Haab-Dimmer dystrophy'''\n| image           = Lattice corneal dystrophy type 1.JPEG\n| caption         = A network of thick linear corneal opacities in patient with a variant of LCD1 (LCD type III) due to a homozygous p. Leu527Arg mutation in the [[TGFBI]] gene\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Lattice corneal dystrophy type''',  is a rare form of [[corneal dystrophy]]. It has no systemic manifestations, unlike the other type of the dystrophy, Lattice corneal dystrophy type II. Lattice corneal dystrophy was first described by Swiss [[ophthalmologist]] Hugo Biber in 1890.<ref name=\"Biber1890\">H. Biber: \u00dcber einige seltenere Hornhauterkrankungen. Z\u00fcrich, 1890. Inaugural Dissertation, Zurich, 1890. Cited by O. Haab: Die gittrige Keratitis.</ref>\n\nLattice dystrophy gets its name from an accumulation of [[Amyloidosis|amyloid]] deposits, or abnormal protein fibers, throughout the middle and anterior stroma.\n\n== Presentation ==\nFilamentous opacities appear in the [[cornea]] with intertwining delicate branching processes. During an eye examination, the doctor sees these deposits in the stroma as clear, comma-shaped overlapping dots and branching filaments, creating a lattice effect. Over time, the lattice lines will grow opaque and involve more of the stroma. They will also gradually converge, giving the cornea a cloudiness that may also reduce vision. The disease is bilateral, usually noted before the end of the first decade of life. Although lattice dystrophy can occur at any time in life, the condition usually arises in children between the ages of two and seven.\n\nIn some people, these abnormal protein fibers can accumulate under the cornea's outer layer\u2014the epithelium. This can cause [[Recurrent corneal erosion|erosion of the epithelium]]. This condition is known as recurrent epithelial erosion. These erosions alter the cornea's normal curvature, resulting in temporary vision problems, and expose the nerves that line the cornea, causing severe pain. Even the involuntary act of blinking can be painful.\n\nIn systemic cases, kidney failure, heart failure and neuropathy such as facial nerve palsy, laxity of the skin may be noted.<ref name=omim2>{{OMIM|105120}}</ref>\n\n== Genetics ==\n[[File:Lattice corneal dystrophy type II cornea cut.jpg|thumb|250 px|Lattice corneal dystrophy type II. Black and white light micrograph showing deposits of amyloid in cornea. Congo red stain.]]\n[[File:Lattice corneal dystrophy type II diagram.gif|thumb|240 px|Diagram depicting gelsolin and the amyloid protein derived from it because of mutations in codon]]\n\nLattice corneal dystrophy has two types:<ref name=omim>{{OMIM|122200}}</ref>\n\n* type I: with no systemic association. It is caused by mutations in [[TGFBI]] gene encoding keratoepithelin, which maps to chromosome 5q.\n* type II or [[Familial Amyloidosis, Finnish Type|Finnish type amyloidosis]]: associated with manifestations of systemic amyloidosis due to accumulation of [[gelsolin]].<ref name=\"pmid1322359\">{{cite journal |vauthors=de la Chapelle A, Kere J, Sack GH, Tolvanen R, Maury CP |title=Familial amyloidosis, Finnish type: G654----a mutation of the gelsolin gene in Finnish families and an unrelated American family |journal=Genomics |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=898\u2013901 |date=July 1992 |pmid=1322359 |doi= 10.1016/0888-7543(92)90182-R}}</ref> Associated conditions may include [[cutis laxa]]<ref name=\"pmid15727635\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kiuru-Enari S, Keski-Oja J, Haltia M |title=Cutis laxa in hereditary gelsolin amyloidosis |journal=Br. J. Dermatol. |volume=152 |issue=2 |pages=250\u20137 |date=February 2005 |pmid=15727635 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2133.2004.06276.x }}</ref> and [[ataxia]].<ref name=\"pmid17453628\">{{cite journal |author=Tanskanen M |title=Severe ataxia with neuropathy in hereditary gelsolin amyloidosis: a case report |journal=Amyloid |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=89\u201395 |date=March 2007 |pmid=17453628 |doi=10.1080/13506120601116393 |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Paetau A |author3=Salonen O |display-authors=3 |last4=Salmi |first4=Tapani |last5=Lamminen |first5=Antti |last6=Lindsberg |first6=Perttu |last7=Somer |first7=Hannu |last8=Kiuru-Enari |first8=Sari }}</ref>\n* type III is also described which has an onset at age 70 to 90 years and is not associated with systemic amyloidosis.<ref name=omim />\n\n==Diagnosis==\n{{Empty section|date=April 2018}}\nIn the examination of biomicroscopy, it appears as branches spread on the corneal stroma in the appearance of ghost vessels. diagnosis can also be confirmed with anterior segment OCT (visante OCT ,spetral domain OCT).The interwoven linear opaque filaments have some resemblance to NERVES, but may not be observed in all affected members of families with the condition. Recurrent corneal erosions may precede the corneal opacities and even appear in individuals lacking recognizable stromal disease. Amyloid deposits are found throughout the corneal stroma. Linear and other shaped opaque areas accumulate particularly within the central corneal stroma, while the peripheral cornea remains relatively transparent.\n\n== Treatment ==\nIn case of corneal erosion, a doctor may prescribe eye drops and ointments to reduce the friction on the eroded cornea. In some cases, an eye patch may be used to immobilize the eyelids. With effective care, these erosions usually heal within three to seven days, although occasional sensations of pain may occur for the next six-to-eight weeks. As patients with LCD suffer with dry eyes as a result of erosion, a new technique involving the insertion of [[punctal plug]]s (both upper and lower) can reduce the amount of drops used a day, aiding ocular stability.\n\nBy about age 40, some people with lattice dystrophy will have scarring under the epithelium, resulting in a haze on the cornea that can greatly obscure vision. In this case, a [[corneal transplantation]] may be needed. There have been many cases in which teenage patients have had the procedure, which accounts for the change in severity of the condition from person to person.\n\nAlthough people with lattice dystrophy have an excellent chance for a successful [[corneal transplantation]], the disease may also arise in the donor cornea in as little as three years. In one study, about half of the transplant patients with lattice dystrophy had a recurrence of the disease between two and 26 years after the operation. Of these, 15 percent required a second corneal transplant. Early lattice and recurrent lattice arising in the donor cornea responds well to treatment with the excimer laser.\n\nPhototherapeutic keratectomy (PTK) using [Excimer laser] can restore and preserve useful visual function for a significant period of time in patients with anterior corneal dystrophies.<ref name=omim />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB     =  \n|  ICD10          = {{ICD10|H|18|5|h|15}} \n|  ICD9           = {{ICD9|371.54}} \n|  ICDO           =  \n|  OMIM           = 122200\t\t \n|  MedlinePlus    =  \n|  eMedicineSubj  = article \n|  eMedicineTopic = 1193793 \n|  MeshID         = \n}}\n<!--unused refs *Maury CPJ, Alli K, Baumann M ( January 1990) Finnish hereditary amyloidosis - amino acid sequence homology between the amyloid fibril protein and human plasma gelsolin. FEBS Letters  vol 260, pp 85\u201387 (1990)\n*Maury CPJ, Kere J, Tolvanen  R et al. ( Dec 1990) Finnish hereditary amyloidosis is caused by a single nucleotide substitution in the gelsolin gene. FEBS Letters vol 276, pp.&nbsp;75\u201377 (1990)\n*{{cite book|author1=Emmett T. Cunningham |author2=Paul Riordan-Eva |title=Vaughan & Asbury's general ophthalmology.|publisher=McGraw-Hill Medical|isbn=978-0071634205|edition=18th}}-->\n\n{{Human corneal dystrophy}}\n\n[[Category:Disorders of sclera and cornea]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lattice_corneal_dystrophy"}
{"title_page": "Henri Tayau", "text_new": "'''Henri Tayau''' was an operetta singer and actor, and violinist, who during a short but successful career performed many light tenor roles in [[Op\u00e9ra-Bouffe|op\u00e9ra-bouffes]] of [[Jacques Offenbach|Offenbach]], and created several roles, the most notable being that of Orph\u00e9e in Offenbach's greatest success, ''[[Orph\u00e9e aux Enfers]]''.\n\n==Life and career==\nWhile a violin teacher in [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]], Tayau took part in a charity concert for the destitute in that city, singing for the first time in public with great success. In Paris the following month, Offenbach engaged him on the basis of an audition consisting of a simple song (chansonnette). Tayau soon gained experience and popularity. His witty expressions, fine diction and acting led to eminence in the theatre.<ref>Mercure de France. Couriers des Deux-Mondes - du 15 mars au 15 avril 1857, p13 (in Mus\u00e9e des Familles).</ref>\n\nTayau made his debut at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Bouffes-Parisiens]] as P\u00e2ris, an amourous veterinary violinist,<ref>Henri de Curzon. L\u00e9o Delibes - sa vie et ses oeuvres (1836-1892). Librairie Musical G Legouix, Paris, 1926, p22. Singing with him were Marie Garnier as Segovia and [[Marguerite Mac\u00e9-Montrouge|Marguerite Mac\u00e9]] as Sidonie his beloved, who would create, respectively V\u00e9nus and L'Opinion publique with Tayau in ''Orph\u00e9e aux enfers'' two years later.</ref> in ''Six demoiselles \u00e0 marier'', a one-act [[op\u00e9rette]] by [[L\u00e9o Delibes|Delibes]] (November 1856) in which he also played the violin,<ref name=\"Yon\">Yon, Jean-Claude. ''Jacques Offenbach.'' \u00c9ditions Gallimard, Paris, 2000.</ref> and followed this early the next year with Ramasse-ta-T\u00eate in the premiere of ''[[Croquefer, ou Le dernier des paladins|Croquefer]]'' by Offenbach<ref name=\"Yon\"/>, swiftly followed by the dancing master Tityre in ''Dragonette'',<ref>Le Nouvelliste : quotidien politique, litt\u00e9raire, industriel et commercial. Paris, 31 March 1857,  p2.</ref> and in May that year Arthur in ''[[Vent du soir, ou L'horrible festin]]'', before the Bouffes tour to the British Isles.<ref name=\"Yon\"/>\n\nIn ''Les Petits Prodiges'' (1857), alongside a cello solo from [[L\u00e9once]] and one on the bassoon by [[D\u00e9sir\u00e9 (baritone)|Desir\u00e9]], Tayau was required to execute 'variations excentriques' (excentric variations) on his violin.<ref>La Salle, Albert de. ''Histoire des Bouffes-parisiens''. Librairie Nouvelle, Paris, 1860, p64.</ref> Tayau sang at the competition stage in the [[Charles Lecocq|Lecocq]] version of ''Le Docteur Miracle'' which won the operatta prize jointly with a [[Le Docteur Miracle|setting by Bizet]] in a prize contest organized by Offenbach in 1857.<ref>Charles Lecocq 'Souvenirs'. Les Annales politiques et litt\u00e9raires : revue populaire paraissant le dimanche, 15 December 1912, No.1538, p519.</ref> He performed the title role in [[Aristide Hignard|Hignard]]'s ''M. de Chimpanz\u00e9'' in 1858 at the Bouffes in which he also (as the monkey) performed gymnastic movements.<ref>La Salle, Albert de. ''Histoire des Bouffes-parisiens''. Librairie Nouvelle, Paris, 1860, p71.</ref>\n\nHe sang Flavio / Florville in Offenbach's production of Rossini's ''[[Il signor bruschino]]'' at the Bouffes in 1858.<ref>Le M\u00e9nestrel : journal de musique. Paris, 3 January 1858, p3.</ref> In April 1858 he created another role: Guido in ''[[La chatte m\u00e9tamorphos\u00e9e en femme]]'' at the Bouffes.<ref name=\"Yon\"/> At this time he also appeared in concert, for instance at the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9s savantes circle, singing chansonettes.<ref>Le M\u00e9nestrel (Paris) 25 December 1859, p31.</ref>\n\nDuring a spring visit to the Grand-Th\u00e9\u00e2tre in Marseille, during which the Bouffes company performed 23 operas by Offenbach and other composers, Tayau, who was also one of the stage managers, was noted as \"premier amoureux comique\" (leading comic lover), who undertook his dual role as an \"intelligent artist\", as well as his violin playing.<ref>Th\u00e9\u00e2tres de la province. Le Monde dramatique; Journal des th\u00e9\u00e2tres, 17 June 1858, p3.</ref>\n\nHe created the title role in ''[[Orph\u00e9e aux Enfers]]'' in 1858, actually playing the violin in the Duo de Concerto in Act I \"Ah! C'est ainsi... C'est d\u00e9plorable, c'est affroyable\",<ref>[[Andrew Lamb (writer)|Lamb A]]. Orph\u00e9e aux Enfers. In: ''[[The New Grove Dictionary of Opera]]'', Macmillan, London and New York, 1997.</ref> and took part in a revival of the piece in 1866.<ref>Robert Burat. Les miettes de Paris. Le Figaro 1 February 1866.</ref> In April 1860 he sang Orph\u00e9e in the [[Royal Command Performance|command performance]] for the [[Emperor Napoleon III|Emperor]] at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre-Italien]].<ref name=\"Yon\"/> With the Bouffes on tour in the summer of 1860 he sang Orph\u00e9e, and Tarabisco in L'\u00c9pine's ''Croquignolle XXXVI'' in Lyon.<ref>L'Argus et le Vert-vert r\u00e9unis. Lyon, 12 August 1860.</ref>\n\nSubsequent premieres included ''La Polka des sabots'' in 1859, a one-act op\u00e9rette by [[Alphonse Varney|Varney]] (conductor of the Bouffes orchestra),<ref>Jules Noriac. \u00c9chos de Paris. Le Figaro, 30 October 1859.</ref> and ''Monsieur de Bonne-\u00c9toile'', another one-act op\u00e9rette, by Delibes in 1860, alongside Marchand, Gaillat and [[Marie Cico|Cico]].<ref>Georges Davidson. \u00c0 travers les th\u00e9\u00e2tres. Le Figaro, 5 February 1860.</ref>\n\nIn 1864 Tayau sang Raflafla in Offenbach's ''[[Mesdames de la Halle]]'' at the Bouffes-Parisiens.<ref>L'Orchestre : revue quotidienne des th\u00e9\u00e2tres. 1 November 1864, last page.</ref> The following year he sang S\u00e9rapion in the \"parade \u00e9gyptienne\" ''Le Boeuf [[Apis (deity)|Apis]]'' by Delibes (possibly a parody of Rossini's ''[[Mo\u00efse (opera)|Mo\u00efse]]'' or M\u00e9hul's ''[[Joseph (opera)|Joseph]]'') and was in a revival of ''Les Petits du premier'' by Albert.<ref>La Musique en 1864 [-1865], documents relatifs \u00e0 l'art musical recueillis et mis en ordre par Paul de Toyon. Paris, Publication date : 1865-1866.</ref> In 1867 he sang Prince Belazor in ''Peau-d'\u00c2ne'' by [[Clairville (Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Nicola\u00efe)|Clairville]] at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Ga\u00eet\u00e9 (rue Papin)|Ga\u00eet\u00e9]].<ref>L'Orchestre : revue quotidienne des th\u00e9\u00e2tres. Paris, 17 September 1867, p1.</ref>\n\nAlongside [[Hortense Schneider|Schneider]] and other company singers he took part in a tour to twenty towns in Ireland, Scotland and England in 1870 organized by the director of the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Porte Saint-Martin]]. The tour began on 14 March in Dublin, with a repertoire consisting of ''[[La Grande-Duchesse de G\u00e9rolstein|La Grande-Duchesse]]'', ''[[Barbe-bleue (opera)|Barbe-Bleue]]'', ''Orph\u00e9e'', and ''[[La P\u00e9richole]]''.<ref>Jules Pr\u00e9vel. Courrier des th\u00e9\u00e2tres. Le Figaro, 1 March 1870. quoted on the https://www.jacquesoffenbach.fr/ site</ref>\n\n==Family==\nTayau's daughter was the violinist and violin teacher Marie Tayau (1855-1892),<ref>N\u00e9crologie - Mademoiselle Marie Tayau. Le Courrier de la Rochelle, 25 August 1892, p3.</ref> who won a first prize at the [[Paris Conservatoire|Conservatoire]] aged 12, and later had a full career on the concert platform. She organized popular chamber music concerts at the [[Trocad\u00e9ro]],<ref>Le Parnasse - Organe des Concours Litt\u00e9raires de Paris. 5th year, No.48, 15 September 1881, p4.</ref> and gave the premiere of [[Gabriel Faur\u00e9|Faur\u00e9]]'s Sonate pour violon et piano no.1 in 1877.\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\nA photo of Tayau as Orph\u00e9e appears at http://www.offenbach-edition.com/EN/Media/Galerie (included in the CD-rom in their critical edition) as the first one in the fourth row.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tayau}}\n[[Category:French operatic tenors]]\n[[Category:French male stage actors]]\n[[Category:19th-century French male actors]]\n[[Category:19th-century French opera singers]]\n[[Category:French male violinists]]\n[[Category:People from Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]\n[[Category:Date of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Date of birth unknown]]\n", "text_old": "'''Henri Tayau''' was an operetta singer and actor, and violinist, who during a short but successful career performed many light tenor roles in [[Op\u00e9ra-Bouffe|op\u00e9ra-bouffes]] of [[Jacques Offenbach|Offenbach]], and created several roles, the most notable being that of Orph\u00e9e in Offenbach's greatest success, ''[[Orph\u00e9e aux Enfers]]''.\n\n==Life and career==\nWhile a violin teacher in [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]], Tayau took part in a charity concert for the destitute in that city, singing for the first time in public with great success. In Paris the following month, Offenbach engaged him on the basis of an audition consisting of a simple song (chansonnette). Tayau soon gained experience and popularity. His witty expressions, fine diction and acting led to eminence in the theatre.<ref>Mercure de France. Couriers des Deux-Mondes - du 15 mars au 15 avril 1857, p13 (in Mus\u00e9e des Familles).</ref>\n\nTayau made his debut at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Bouffes-Parisiens]] as P\u00e2ris, an amourous veterinary violinist,<ref>Henri de Curzon. L\u00e9o Delibes - sa vie et ses oeuvres (1836-1892). Librairie Musical G Legouix, Paris, 1926, p22. Singing with him were Marie Garnier as Segovia and [[Marguerite Mac\u00e9-Montrouge|Marguerite Mac\u00e9]] as Sidonie his beloved, who would create, respectively V\u00e9nus and L'Opinion publique with Tayau in ''Orph\u00e9e aux enfers'' two years later.</ref> in ''Six demoiselles \u00e0 marier'', a one-act [[op\u00e9rette]] by [[L\u00e9o Delibes|Delibes]] (November 1856) in which he also played the violin<ref name=\"Yon\">Yon, Jean-Claude. ''Jacques Offenbach.'' \u00c9ditions Gallimard, Paris, 2000.</ref>, and followed this early the next year with Ramasse-ta-T\u00eate in the premiere of ''[[Croquefer, ou Le dernier des paladins|Croquefer]]'' by Offenbach<ref name=\"Yon\"/>, swiftly followed by the dancing master Tityre in ''Dragonette'',<ref>Le Nouvelliste : quotidien politique, litt\u00e9raire, industriel et commercial. Paris, 31 March 1857,  p2.</ref> and in May that year Arthur in ''[[Vent du soir, ou L'horrible festin]]'', before the Bouffes tour to the British Isles.<ref name=\"Yon\"/>\n\nIn ''Les Petits Prodiges'' (1857), alongside a cello solo from [[L\u00e9once]] and one on the bassoon by [[D\u00e9sir\u00e9 (baritone)|Desir\u00e9]], Tayau was required to execute 'variations excentriques' (excentric variations) on his violin.<ref>La Salle, Albert de. ''Histoire des Bouffes-parisiens''. Librairie Nouvelle, Paris, 1860, p64.</ref> Tayau sang at the competition stage in the [[Charles Lecocq|Lecocq]] version of ''Le Docteur Miracle'' which won the operatta prize jointly with a [[Le Docteur Miracle|setting by Bizet]] in a prize contest organized by Offenbach in 1857.<ref>Charles Lecocq 'Souvenirs'. Les Annales politiques et litt\u00e9raires : revue populaire paraissant le dimanche, 15 December 1912, No.1538, p519.</ref> He performed the title role in [[Aristide Hignard|Hignard]]'s ''M. de Chimpanz\u00e9'' in 1858 at the Bouffes in which he also (as the monkey) performed gymnastic movements.<ref>La Salle, Albert de. ''Histoire des Bouffes-parisiens''. Librairie Nouvelle, Paris, 1860, p71.</ref>\n\nHe sang Flavio / Florville in Offenbach's production of Rossini's ''[[Il signor bruschino]]'' at the Bouffes in 1858.<ref>Le M\u00e9nestrel : journal de musique. Paris, 3 January 1858, p3.</ref> In April 1858 he created another role: Guido in ''[[La chatte m\u00e9tamorphos\u00e9e en femme]]'' at the Bouffes.<ref name=\"Yon\"/> At this time he also appeared in concert, for instance at the Soci\u00e9t\u00